<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Higher; Dow Up 190.07 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were sharply higher in late afternoon  
trading, as optimism about lower interest rates and some 
high-priced takeover deals encouraged investors to dip back into 
the market. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 190.07 at 9,530.02, led by banking and technology issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher, with the Nasdaq composite  
up 36.95 at 2,320.55, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index up 28.14 
at 1,267.36. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange. A volume figure was not immediately 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices were higher, pushing interest rates down, ahead of  
Federal Reserve Chairman Greenspan's semi-annual Humphrey-Hawkins 
testimony to the Senate Banking Committee, scheduled to begin at 10 
a.m. EST Tuesday. Later Tuesday, Greenspan will discuss with the 
same panel his views on the modernization of the financial-services 
industry. On Wednesday, he will address the House Banking 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	He will go to Capitol Hill on a high note, after data released  
last Thursday and Friday showed an economy still growing while 
price inflation remains quiet, said Alan Skrainka,chief market 
strategist at Edward Jones in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year Treasury bond was up 15/32 point, pushing its yield,  
which moves opposite the price, down to 5.35 percent from 5.38 
percent late Friday, amid optimism that Greenspan would have an 
upbeat message. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the odds are very slim that he would say something to  
upset the apple cart,'' Skrainka said. ``Alan Greenspan probably 
has to pinch himself to make sure he's not dreaming. There's 
perfection in the economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of technology companies, which need to borrow frequently  
and therefore benefit from lower interest rates, moved higher after 
dropping last week. The Dow was led higher by IBM, up 4 13/16 at 
176 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks also moved higher on lower interest rates.  
American Express was up 4 13/16 at 108. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was also helped higher by some merger news, most  
prominently in the energy industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominion Resources agreed to buy gas and oil-pipeline company  
Consolidated Natural Gas for $6.3 billion. The union would create 
one of the country's largest electric and gas utilities. Dominion 
Resources' shares were down 1 15/16 at 40 5/16, while CNG's shares 
were down 1 1/16 at 55 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra Energy agreed to acquire KN Energy, a big natural-gas  
pipeline and storage operator, for $1.9 billion. KNE's stock was up 
3/8 at 21 7/8, but Sempra's shares were down 5/8 at 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, aircraft engine maker and Dow component United  
Technologies said it would buy Sundstrand for about $4.3 billion in 
cash and stock, in a move that will expand United Technologies' 
aerospace and aviation businesses. United Technologies' shares were 
up 1/16 at 125 1/2, after making back a loss of more than 2 points, 
and Sundstrand's shares were up 10 1/4 at 68 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Telecom Italia, the leading telecommunications service  
provider in Italy, is the target of a hostile takeover bid by 
smaller rival Olivetti. Telecom Italia's shares were up 7 1/16 at 
113 1/2. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
