<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yahoo! Seeks Damages in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- California-based Yahoo! will seek  
unspecified damages from Indian ``cybersquatters'' in a patent 
case, counsel for the U.S. company said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	An Indian court granted an injunction Friday to the Santa Clara,  
California-based Yahoo!, which has brought a civil suit against 
``Yahooindia,'' whose World Wide Web site resembles the familiar 
Yahoo! home page and offers India-related services and information. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahooindia is run by New Delhi-based Netlink Internet Solutions.  
Monday, its Internet page read only: ``Under Construction. Please 
Come Back Later.'' The company's lawyer, Harish Malhotra, said he 
would appeal the injunction keeping Yahooindia from operating or 
seeking advertising pending a final ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yahoo is a common word in trade circles,'' Malhotra told The  
Associated Press. ``No one can own the name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys representing Yahoo! said the ruling was a rarity in a  
case related to the Internet, rife with the practice of 
``cybersquatting'' or copying of domain names. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are seeking punitive damages. Let this case be a deterrent  
for cybersquatters,'' Yahoo counsel Pravin Anand told The 
Associated Press. Anand, a leading patent attorney, said the ruling 
also rebutted the notion that Indian courts offered little redress 
to domestic and foreign companies in cases of patent law 
violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge M.K. Sharma said in his ruling: ``There is every  
possibility of an Internet user being confused and deceived in 
believing that both the domain names belong to one common source 
and connection, although the two belong to two different 
concerns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The court rejected defense counsel Malhotra's argument that  
Indian patent laws protected only physical goods, saying the domain 
name served the same function as a trademark and was not a mere 
address. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! was developed by David Filo and Jerry Yang in 1994 and  
offers services ranging from stock quotes to news to live chats. In 
January, Yahoo! announced it was acquiring Geocities to form the 
world's largest online company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
