<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 02:44:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Illinois Mayor Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) -- He was always a little too flashy, a  
little too quick to kiss the women. He presided over the city 
during an era when mountains of trash grew along the streets and 
workers went unpaid. 
</P>
<P>
	So what is former Mayor Carl Officer doing in Tuesday's primary,  
seeking the office voters took away from him eight years ago? 
</P>
<P>
	``I've changed,'' he said last week.  
</P>
<P>
	Since leaving office in 1991, the confirmed bachelor with a  
penchant for fast living has married, become an ordained minister 
and taken over his family's funeral home business. 
</P>
<P>
	Everywhere he goes, Officer is greeted warmly by people who know  
him more for helping ease families through the death of a mother or 
brother than for the controversies of his 12 years as mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to see him back in,'' said cab driver Charlie  
Bourragh. ``George Wallace changed, didn't he? You can't judge a 
man by his past alone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officer, 46, prefers to remember the accomplishments of his  
three terms as mayor: bringing businesses to town and laying the 
groundwork for development of the city's riverfront, among other 
things. 
</P>
<P>
	But the prospect of his return, just as the city is showing  
signs of revival, leaves his critics cold. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelvin Jones, another mayoral candidate, said Officer left East  
St. Louis with ``the lowest conditions in the city's history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officer faces an uphill battle in his effort to regain the  
office he held from 1979 to 1991. The city's powerful Democratic 
Party machine backs candidate Eddie Jackson, a school principal. 
</P>
<P>
	City Councilwoman Debra Powell and retired firefighter Henry  
Birge are also on the ballot. The top two finishers among the 
all-Democratic slate move on to the April 13 general election. 
Incumbent Gordon Bush has decided not to seek a third term. 
</P>
<P>
	Without party backing, Officer is taking his campaign directly  
to residents with an hour of paid radio programming each morning 
and a full day of campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	On a recent campaign swing, Officer swept through the downtown  
business district to the beat of an aide's portable stereo blasting 
hip-hop music, tossing out campaign literature and kisses. 
</P>
<P>
	``No big date?'' he asks one woman outside a beauty salon.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I hadn't promised my wife, you'd be first on my list,'' he  
said, planting a kiss on her cheek. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite greeting dozens of residents in a matter of minutes, he  
never introduces himself. ``I don't need to,'' he said. ``I've 
buried most of these folk's relatives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officer may still have that same old charisma, but he said the  
immaturity that once got him in trouble is gone. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a wisdom that comes from age and experience,''  
Officer said. 
</P>
<P>
	This from a man who once promised to rid the city of gangs in  
less than 12 weeks, used a City Hall phone to call a 900-number 
dating service and, shortly before leaving office in 1991, was 
pulled over for speeding 105 mph in a Jaguar owned by an imprisoned 
drug dealer. 
</P>
<P>
	Officer traces his transformation to a visit to Israel in 1993,  
when he recalls looking up during a boat trip on the Sea of Galilee 
to see the path Jesus would have taken to descend from Nazareth. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time, the lifelong Baptist said he felt the true  
presence of God. ``My whole life changed that morning, and 
nothing's been the same since,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He has since been ordained in the Baptist church and expects to  
receive his final ordination in the African Methodist Episcopal 
church in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he understands through his religious awakening what  
his purpose is here on earth. I trust him totally,'' said the Rev. 
Samuel Bradford, pastor of Shiloh AME church and one of Officer's 
teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Resident Darlean Lasley doesn't accept Officer's claim of  
transformation and classes him with other longtime city power 
brokers who she said are responsible for the city's impoverished 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had his shot and he blew it,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Officer said most of the problems weren't his fault.  
</P>
<P>
	He blames the decline of the city's housing stock and a garbage  
crisis that made the city a national laughingstock on lazy 
residents. The city was so deeply in debt in the early 1990s it 
allowed trash to pile up on the streets for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	And he takes credit for beginning the process that brought the  
Casino Queen riverboat to East St. Louis and for bringing new 
businesses to downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	Locals do support Officer, but just how much remains unclear,  
said James Jones, executive director of the East St. Louis 
Community Action Network, a nonprofit association of neighborhood 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think some people think that he might be the most qualified  
candidate, but they won't say that publicly because they don't want 
to be associated with his checkered past,'' Jones said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 08:56:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks To Expand Gun Tracing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying they've identified a potent new tool in  
fighting youth crime, Clinton administration officials are asking 
Congress for money to expand a program that traces guns routed 
illegally into the hands of young people. 
</P>
<P>
	The call came as the Treasury Department's Bureau of Alcohol,  
Tobacco and Firearms released an analysis Sunday of its Youth Crime 
Gun Interdiction Initiative. The program traced guns used in 76,260 
crimes in 27 cities over the past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	ATF found that one-third to one-half of the traced guns were  
purchased from licensed dealers by people acting as ``straw'' 
intermediaries for the real owners, and only 35 percent were 
stolen. The rest came from private sellers not required to obtain 
identification or subject their customers to background checks. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, President Clinton said the figures go a long way  
toward helping authorities find and punish those responsible for 
providing guns for young criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	``With more police on the streets and tougher gun laws on the  
books, crime has dropped to its lowest level in a generation. But 
we must do more,'' he said. ``Tracing crime guns to their source, 
and putting gun traffickers out of business for good, will make our 
streets even safer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Howard Matre, an ammunition distributor in Seven Miles,  
Ohio, said the ATF report ``misrepresents the facts'' about straw 
sales, and provides an avenue for opponents to use in trying to 
overturn the right to bear arms. 
</P>
<P>
	``First you have the study, and then you justify the erosion of  
the rights,'' Matre said. ``It's very frustrating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's budget request for fiscal 2000 includes an additional  
$11.2 million to expand the tracing program to 10 additional 
cities: Charlotte, N.C.; Dallas; Denver; Louisville, Ky.; New 
Orleans; Oakland, Calif.; Omaha, Neb.; Phoenix; Portland, Ore.; and 
Tampa, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	That 25 percent of the guns moved quickly from sale to recovery  
by police indicates they were bought legally, then resold, 
officials said. Semiautomatic pistols were the most commonly 
recovered weapon in each city, making up 52 percent of all trace 
requests. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the traces, 397 people have been referred to  
state and federal courts over the past year for prosecution as gun 
traffickers, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't stop them from buying the guns, but as soon as they  
turn those guns over to felons, we can prosecute that,'' ATF 
director John Magaw told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Denise Dunleavy, an attorney for seven families who won a $4  
million negligence verdict against gun manufacturers in a Brooklyn, 
N.Y., court last week, said, ``If the manufacturers took more 
rigorous precautions up front, you wouldn't have the guns being 
trafficked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brooklyn case, brought in 1995 by a mother whose son was  
shot to death two years earlier, is being watched closely by cities 
anxious to sue manufacturers to recover costs from gun violence. 
ATF's report ``proves our evidence was certainly on the right 
track,'' Dunleavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study found that new guns reaching the hands of young  
criminals from straw purchasers made up between 25 and 36 percent 
of all firearms recovered from juveniles over the past three years, 
and between 32 percent and 49 percent of firearms recovered from 
offenders aged 18 to 24. 
</P>
<P>
	The report identified five types of semiautomatic pistols that  
move rapidly from dealers to young offenders: the Lorcin 9 mm, the 
.40-caliber Smith &AMP; Wesson, the Bryco 9 mm, the Hi-Point 9 mm and 
the .40-caliber Glock. 
</P>
<P>
	It said 11.3 percent of the offenders involved were under 17  
years old, and 32 percent were between 18 and 24. Thirty-one 
percent of the guns were used in drug offenses, 28 percent in 
assaults and 18 percent each in homicides and robberies. 
</P>
<P>
	The report was the result of Clinton's 1996 directive that the  
Treasury and Justice departments establish a program to identify 
and reduce the illegal transfer of firearms to young people. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27 cities involved in the report are Atlanta; Baltimore;  
Birmingham, Ala.; Boston; Bridgeport, Conn.; Chicago; Cincinnati; 
Cleveland; Detroit; Gary, Ind.; Houston; Inglewood, Calif.; Jersey 
City, N.J.; Los Angeles; Memphis, Tenn.; Miami; Milwaukee; 
Minneapolis; New York; Philadelphia; Richmond, Va.; Salinas, 
Calif.; San Antonio; St. Louis; Seattle; Tucson, Ariz.; and 
Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
