<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ichiro Suzuki at Seattle's Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ariz. (AP) -- The Seattle Mariners have found the player  
to wear Randy Johnson's old No. 51 -- Ichiro Suzuki, a five-time 
batting champion from Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki, 25, will take part in the Mariners' first full workout  
for pitchers and position players Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Suzuki will be joined at the Mariners' spring training by two  
other players from the Japanese Pacific League, pitchers Nobuyuki 
Hoshino and Nobuyuki Ebisu. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese translations have been posted on doorways at the  
Mariners' complex for signs such as ``Authorized Personnel Only.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 100 media members from Japan will report on the Japanese  
players and countryman Mac Suzuki, a reliever in the Seattle 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be prepared for the media circus as well as we  
can,'' manager Lou Piniella said. 
</P>
<P>
	Piniella and pitching coach Stan Williams have drawn up a spring  
training strategy for the team's pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Piniella said the Mariners will pitch left-hander Jeff Fassero  
one inning in his first spring training start. He had bone chips 
removed from his left elbow in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're being cautious early on with all the starters,''  
Piniella said. ``Our plan is to give starters six to seven 
appearances, have them pitch a total of about 27 innings, with the 
last appearance going six or seven innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will throw one day, rest the next, throw 10 to 12 minutes  
the day after, rest the next and then pitch again. We've gotten 
away from that in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All-Stars Alex Rodriguez and Ken Griffey Jr. were not among the  
Mariners' position players who took physicals Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey is already in the Phoenix area. Rodriguez will arrive  
Tuesday in time for the first workout, which is scheduled to last 
3 1/2 hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
