<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans At 23-Year Lows / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures tumbled to 23-year lows Monday  
on the Chicago Board of Trade after the U.S. Agriculture Department's 
chief economist predicted crop prices could fall to $4 a bushel later 
this year. Grain futures also retreated. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans fell after USDA chief economist Keith Collins predicted  
at a farm outlook conference that there is no end in sight this year 
to falling prices, largely because economic troubles in Asia have caused 
exports to fall sharply. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybean prices have fallen each day for more than a week amid  
indications world production will continue to increase at a time when 
there are few takers for the commodity. 
</P>
<P>
        U.S. farmers last year harvested a record crop, and analysts  
are predicting they will plant record acreage this year because of 
farm programs that pay more for that crop than others. Further exacerbating 
the problem are expectations for a near-record Brazilian crop and a 
large crop from Argentina. South American soybeans account for a third 
of the world's supply, and Brazil is the world's second-largest grower 
behind the United States. 
</P>
<P>
        Collins predicted farm income would drop this year by $3 billion  
to $4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat futures fell on news of the USDA outlook and more near-ideal  
weather in winter-wheat growing regions. Corn futures suffered least, 
propped by continued steady domestic and export demand. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans for March delivery fell 4 1/4 cents to $4.74 a bushel.  
Prices earlier in the session had fallen to $4.64 1/2 a bushel. March 
wheat fell 3 cents to $2.51 3/4 a bushel; March corn fell 1 cent to 
$2.14 a bushel; March oats fell 1/4 cent to $1.01 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef and pork bellies futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while lean hogs were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
        April live cattle fell 0.25 cent to 66.45 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle fell 0.58 cent to 72.77 cents a pound; April lean hogs 
fell 0.02 cent to 45.80 cents a pound; March pork bellies fell 1.75 
cents to 52.55 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
