<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HSBC Buys Korean Bank Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In another sign of progress in South  
Korea's financial cleanup, British banking giant HSBC is paying 
$700 million for a 70 percent stake in Seoulbank, a troubled lender 
that was nationalized last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal announced Monday by HSBC Holdings PLC and South  
Korea's Financial Supervisory Commission, the South Korean 
government would keep 30 percent of the bank. South Korea will also 
take over the remainder of Seoulbank's bad debt. 
</P>
<P>
	London-based HSBC Holdings owns the Marine Midland Bank in the  
United States and the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corp., Hong 
Kong's leading bank. It also owns Midland Bank, the largest bank in 
England. 
</P>
<P>
	Seoulbank was one of two banks nationalized last year by the  
South Korean government as part of a broad effort to restructure 
the country's financial system. The other one, Korea First Bank, 
sold a 51 percent stake in itself late last year to a U.S. 
investment group led by Newbridge Capital Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea poured $3.22 billion into Korea First Bank and $2.68  
billion into Seoulbank to write off half of their bad loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Both banks were forced to shed thousands of workers and close  
down dozens of retail branches across the country as part of a 
restructuring program. 
</P>
<P>
	Selling the two troubled banks was among conditions laid down by  
the International Monetary Fund in exchange for its $58 billion 
bailout of South Korea's sinking economy in late 1997. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
