<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Slips Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar slipped against the yen in late  
profit-taking Monday after rising earlier on speculation that Group 
of Seven finance officials had approved a lower rate for the 
Japanese currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar edged higher against the euro. In late New York  
trading, the euro was quoted at $1.1028, down from $1.1076 late 
Friday. Also in late trading, the dollar was quoted at 120.91 
Japanese yen, down from 121.15 Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar climbed to an 11-week high against the yen during  
early trading. Investors later sold yen after the G-7 meeting of 
industrial nations failed to say anything about exchange rates 
following a weekend meeting. Investors interpreted that as 
officials' approving of the falling yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was aided by Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's  
influential vice finance minister for international affairs, who 
was quoted in a Tuesday newspaper saying he favored a weak yen, a 
continuation of his position last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``An excessive rise in the yen should be avoided. Although we  
will not refer to a target level, we must send a message (to the 
market) at some point,'' he was quoted as saying in an interview 
published in Tuesday's Nihon Keizai Shimbun newspaper. Sending a 
message would mean intervening in foreign exchange markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market was a little sensitive to that'' and took the yen  
lower against the dollar, said Jeremy Fand, a foreign exchange 
strategist at BankBoston's Boston office. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar did end the day lower against the yen as  
profit-taking set in. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar initially fell against the euro in Asian trading  
following weekend comments by Hans Tietmeyer, president of 
Germany's central bank, who intimated that a weak euro was 
worrisome for Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was surprisingly supportive of the euro,'' Fand said. But  
the dollar later got a boost from rising U.S. stocks and bonds. 
``That's always good news,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4495 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4468, and 1.4962 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4852. The British 
pound rose to $1.6258 from $1.6226. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7734 German 
marks, up from 1.7658; 5.9488 French francs, up from 5.9207; and 
1,754.39 Italian lire, up from 1,748.25. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
