<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes Education Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today asked the nation's  
governors to support his proposed education reforms, saying winning 
approval will be ``tough politics'' but ultimately worth the 
battle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some will say the federal government should be giving states  
more flexibility, not demanding more accountability,'' Clinton 
said. ``I say it's a false choice, and the federal government 
should be giving you more of both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Vice President Al Gore held a roundtable discussion  
at the White House with 53 governors from the states and 
territories attending the National Governors' Association's annual 
winter meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton sought to find common ground with governors who are  
split along political lines over the federal role in improving the 
performance of public schools. Democrats have largely backed 
Clinton's proposal, while Republican governors say Washington 
should have limited say in the way education dollars are used. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is tough politics. I don't know that I could have passed  
this through my legislature,'' Clinton said, referring to his 
tenure as governor of Arkansas. ``We don't have any business 
telling you whom to hire, how to teach, how to run schools. ... But 
let's not kid ourselves. We're not doing our children any favors by 
continuing to subsidize practices that do not work and failing to 
invest in practices that do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Delaware Gov. Thomas Carper, chairman of the association, said  
governors ``want and expect both'' flexibility and guidance from 
the federal government when it comes to education. He said he 
expects the governors can resolve their differences over the issue 
and unite behind a common agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can find some middle ground, and we want to work  
hard to that end,'' Carper said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Carper, a Democrat, also cautioned Clinton that states would  
not accept federal interference over the way states use money from 
their settlement with the tobacco industry. He said they would 
deliver the same message to congressional leaders Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we don't want ... is the federal government simply  
telling us how to spend our money,'' Carper said. ``Keep that in 
mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt, a Republican, was more succinct:  
``This is state money. The federal government was invited to 
participate, but declined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's proposals include building or modernizing 6,000  
classrooms, hiring 100,000 teachers, reducing class size in the 
early grades, starting more after-school programs, connecting all 
classrooms and libraries to the Internet, stopping social promotion 
and insisting on effective discipline. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said his education plan is simply a means for the  
federal government to expand upon reform measures that already are 
under way in states such as North Carolina, Michigan, Pennsylvania, 
Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not dream up these ideas in Washington,'' Clinton said.  
``I could mention every governor in this room in some specific or 
another, because these ideas represent the best practices in 
education reform today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president also lavished praise on Florida Gov. Jeb Bush for  
proposing that his state set aside some of its tobacco settlement 
money for a children's foundation named in memory of Bush's late 
Democratic predecessor, Lawton Chiles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those of us who knew and cared for Lawton, we are profoundly  
grateful for that,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:56:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wells: Yanks Are Still in My Heart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUNEDIN, Fla. (AP) -- On his first day with the Toronto Blue  
Jays, David Wells said part of him was still with the New York 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are the enemy now but they are in my heart and on my  
mind,'' Wells said Monday, four days after New York dealt him to 
Toronto for Roger Clemens. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, who has always been a Yankees fan, became a star in New  
York by pitching a perfect game against Minnesota last May. He even 
wore an original cap worn by Babe Ruth on the mound one day. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was fun while it lasted,'' the 35-year-old left-hander  
said. ``There were no heroes last year; we just played as a team. I 
love everyone of them as my brother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, who didn't want to talk about his feelings on the day of  
the trade, was angry at reporters who went to his residence in Palm 
Harbor, saying they were ``invading my privacy,'' and at one point 
made an obscene gesture at media members. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coming onto private property is something that's uncalled  
for,'' he said. ``It's something that in the situation that went on 
was very emotional for me. But to come over to my house and bother 
me like that, is very inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells began his major league career with the Blue Jays in 1987  
and spent six years in Toronto before being released. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm clear-minded and ready to get started and ready for the  
1999 season, to help this team win the pennant,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto general manager Gord Ash said he has no intention of  
trading Wells. Cleveland and the New York Mets have been mentioned 
as possible suitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not discuss any deals with David Wells,'' Ash said.  
``In the words of George Bush: Read my lips -- David Wells will not 
be traded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following the stunning trade, Wells went to Miami for a few days  
of golf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went down there, played golf and saw some friends,'' he  
said. ``Being traded isn't fun, but I'm a grown man and I can 
adapt. It's tough to leave a team that won 125 games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto thinks the deal, in which it also acquired reliever  
Graeme Lloyd and second baseman Homer Bush, makes it a wild-card 
contender. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Toronto got the better part of the deal,'' Wells said.  
``The key to winning is pitching and this team has some good 
pitchers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He'll have to prepare himself for a return to SkyDome, a much  
different place to play than Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a different culture in Toronto and you have to adjust,''  
he said. ``The fans aren't like in New York but they're fans. Now 
I'll make those fans happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells said his carefree personality won't change.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just like to have fun; I just like to be me,'' he said.  
``It's what my Mom made me -- she made me a complete person. You 
live your life the way you want it, as long as you do your job 
between the lines.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
