<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belle Reports Early to Orioles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Albert Belle not only joined the  
Baltimore Orioles two days early, he talked about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle strode to the back fields and took some swings in the  
batting cage. He also threw in the outfield and signed some 
autographs on his way to the clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	```I've said all along that I'll put forth the effort to work  
with the media,'' Belle said. ``Spring training is a lot easier to 
talk to everyone. Once the season starts, I won't be accessible 
every day, but I've become more and more accessible every year 
compared to the past, when I just cut everybody off. It's been a 
gradual improvement and we'll just go from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belle was the only AL player to rank in the top three last year  
in batting average (.328), homers (49) and RBIs (152). He exercised 
an escape clause in his contract with the Chicago White Sox and 
signed a $65 million, five-year contract with the Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees had expressed interest in Belle before  
re-signing Bernie Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would rather have come to Baltimore than the Yankees,''  
Belle said. ``You look at their situation, they're the kingpin and 
you want to be that underdog that knocks them off the top. That's 
pretty much the situation I've been in my whole career. It just 
makes for a better season when you knock the big guys off the 
top.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While there was no arguing that Belle would have a big impact in  
the lineup, the Orioles had to consider his numerous suspensions 
and controversies. Manager Ray Miller had a lengthy discussion with 
Belle in Baltimore after the signing and said he was impressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The attitude thing, I haven't seen any problems,'' Miller  
said. ``I was quite taken aback when I spent some time with him, 
how articulate and candid he was about everything. 
</P>
<P>
	``He looked me right in the eye and said, `I'll be the first one  
here and the last one to leave. I study film, I take my own notes 
and I play every day.' If there's a manager who doesn't like to 
hear that statement, something's wrong,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	A left fielder and cleanup hitter most of his career, Belle is  
projected as a right fielder and No. 3 hitter in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I broke in as a right fielder in '89 so that's nothing new to  
me,'' Belle said. ``I didn't realize that B.J (Surhoff) only made 
three errors in left field, so if playing right field is what it 
takes for us to get over the top, that's fine. I'd rather hit 
fourth. It'll be an adjustment for me, but that's what spring 
training's for.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
