<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Soar; Dow Gains 212.73 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices blasted higher Monday, pushing the  
Dow industrials to within 90 points of an all-time high, amid 
renewed confidence that interest rates would stay low and that the 
market for mergers and acquisitions is still hot. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 212.73, or by 2.3  
percent, to 9,552.68, its biggest point gain in five weeks. That 
left the Dow 1 percent shy of the record 9,643.32 reached Jan. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume was moderate, with 874.62 million shares changing hands  
on the New York Stock Exchange, and advancing issues had a 9-to-5 
lead on decliners on the Big Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad-market indexes posted solid gains as well.  
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index was up 58.41, or by 2.6 percent, at  
2,342.01 amid a renewed interest in Internet and other technology 
shares. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index added 32.92, or 2.6 
percent, to 1,272.14. 
</P>
<P>
	Even veteran market experts were somewhat at a loss to explain  
the strong rally at a time when big-name stocks already are trading 
at prices that many fear are excessively above company earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have been worried about the market for several years  
because the valuations in the big-cap stocks have risen so high and 
the broad market hasn't kept pace,'' said Larry Wachtel, the 
Prudential Securities market strategist. 
</P>
<P>
	But some analysts are coming to terms with the extraordinary  
resilience of large-company stocks, Wachtel said. With interest 
rates so low, big companies can borrow easily to make acquisitions. 
They can also afford to make technological improvements that boost 
productivity and help their earnings and stock prices, Wachtel 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Big companies are able to ... fend better, and as a result,  
people continue to buy the big-cap companies because they can do 
the deals, spend on the technology,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The market got a lift from a drop in bond-market interest rates  
ahead of Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's semiannual 
testimony on the state of the economy. Greenspan appears before the 
Senate Banking Committee on Tuesday morning and testifies Wednesday 
before the House Banking Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	With inflation tame despite a robust economy, and with a third  
of the world in recession, Greenspan is not expected to signal any 
move to raise interest rates and cool off the market and the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In anticipation that his testimony would be upbeat for the  
market, yields on 30-year Treasury bonds fell to 5.35 percent from 
5.38 percent Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The lower rates encouraged a broad rally in stocks, from  
financial and technology issues to retail, transportation and 
consumer issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow industrials were led higher by IBM, which rose 6 5/16 to  
177 15/16; American Express, up 5 5/16 at 108 1/2; WalMart, up 3 1/2 at 
88 1/5; and Merck, up 2 4/5 to 81 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was also helped higher by some merger news, although  
some of the stocks directly involved in merger discussions actually 
went down. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcements included a bold attempt at a hostile takeover  
of Telecom Italia, the leading telecommunications service provider 
in Italy, by smaller rival Olivetti. Telecom Italia's U.S. shares 
rose 3 3/8 to 109 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, aircraft engine maker and Dow component United  
Technologies said it would buy Sundstrand for about $4.3 billion in 
cash and stock, in a move that will expand United Technologies' 
aerospace and aviation businesses. United Technologies shares 
initially fell on the news but ended up 1 1/16 at 126 1/2. 
Sundstrand's shares added 10 1/4 to 68 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	In the energy arena, Dominion Resources agreed to buy gas and  
oil-pipeline company Consolidated Natural Gas for $6.3 billion. The 
union would create one of the country's largest electric and gas 
utilities. And Sempra Energy agreed to acquire KN Energy, a big 
natural-gas pipeline and storage operator, for $1.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominion Resources shares fell 2 1/4 to 40, and Consolidated  
Natural Gas fell 1 1/16 to 55 3/16. Sempra's shares fell 3/4 to 21 5/8, 
while KN's shares added 1/8 to 21 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The takeover bids buoyed prices throughout the market. The  
American Stock Exchange's market index climbed 7.46 to 700.03, and 
the NYSE composite added 13.67 to 600.23. The Russell 2000 index of 
mid-sized companies added 5.52 to 397.82. 
</P>
<P>
	In overseas stock markets, the Nikkei index in Tokyo rose 1.13  
percent. In Europe, the FT-SE 100 index in London added 0.64 
percent, the DAX in Frankfurt added 0.89 percent, and the CAC in 
Paris advanced 0.86 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
