<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Players Sent to Europe League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- If Andre Ware makes it back to the NFL this  
season, it will be by way of Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware, the 1989 Heisman Trophy winner and a first-round draft  
pick by Detroit, signed in January with the Oakland Raiders. He did 
not play last season after three years in the Canadian Football 
League, which followed four weak seasons in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Ware was one of 152 players allocated to play in NFL  
Europe this year. The six-team league will have 15 quarterbacks who 
were on NFL rosters in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``The quality of the players being allocated by NFL teams is  
getting better every year,'' said Oliver Luck, president of NFL 
Europe, which has three teams in Germany, one in the Netherlands, 
one in Scotland and one in Spain. ``We want to give those players 
the best possible opportunity to play and develop their skills.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos allocated seven players,  
including linebacker Nate Wayne, who as on the championship game 
roster. NFC champion Atlanta is sending one player, linebacker Shad 
Freeman. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans allocated 12 players, while Kansas City is sending  
11 and Philadelphia made 10 available to NFL Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The league begins play the weekend of April 17-18.  
</P>
</TEXT>
