<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Payback,' 'Message' Top Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kevin Costner's romantic ``Message in a  
Bottle'' and Mel Gibson's violent ``Payback'' both hit it big at 
the box office this weekend, estimates showed. 
</P>
<P>
	``October Sky,'' the story of a coal miner's son with dreams of  
building rockets, opened to respectable business by grossing a 
studio-estimated $6 million for fifth place. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other new releases, the workplace comedy ``Office Space''  
and the bad-girl teen movie ``Jawbreaker,'' did lackluster 
business. ``My Favorite Martian'' continued to do attract 
theatergoers after two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Message in a Bottle,'' starring Costner as a widower who finds  
love again, and ``Payback,'' a violent revenge story with Gibson as 
a double-crossed criminal, both had estimated three-day grosses of 
$10.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	If the estimates are correct, ``Message'' had a slightly higher  
per-location average since it was playing on fewer screens. Final 
figures are due today. 
</P>
<P>
	``October Sky's'' fifth-place opening launches it closer to the  
Brendan Fraser fish-out-water comedy ``Blast from the Past.'' The 
comedy, co-starring Alicia Silverstone, made $6.1 million for 
fourth, according to the studio. But several rivals disputed New 
Line's estimate for ``Blast'' as too high. 
</P>
<P>
	``October Sky's'' per-location average of just more than $4,000  
was hardly stellar, buy was still the second-highest of the 
wide-releases, just behind ``Message in a Bottle.'' That's an 
encouraging sign for a small movie that is tricky to market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a film that needs to find its place in the marketplace  
because of the importance of the word of the mouth,'' said Nikki 
Rocco, president of Universal Pictures distribution. ``I think it 
has that word of mouth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Academy Award nominations helped the Elizabethan romance  
``Shakespeare in Love'' and Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private 
Ryan.'' ``Shakespeare'' grossed $5.8 million for fourth place and 
the re-issue of ``Ryan'' got $2.4 million for 10th. 
</P>
<P>
	The new business for ``Ryan,'' pushed the World War II saga  
passed last summer's space adventure ``Armageddon'' to become the 
highest-grossing film released in 1998. ``Ryan'' now has grossed 
$203.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The other best-picture nominees for the March 21 awards, ``Life  
is Beautiful,'' ``The Thin Red Line'' and ``Elizabeth,'' were out 
of the top 10. Italy's ``Life is Beautiful,'' the tragic-comedy 
story set against the Holocaust, was 11th with $2.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the box office was down more than 11 percent from the  
same weekend last year, as 1999 still can't compete with the 
``Titanic''-powered 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Other new releases stumbled. ``Office Space,'' from the creator  
of ``Beavis and Butt-head,'' opened with $4.3 million for eighth 
place, and ``Jawbreaker'' -- trying to compete in the crowded teen 
movie market -- didn't even make the top 10 with its $1.6 million 
gross. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, another teen film, ``She's All That,'' grossed $5.4  
million in its fourth week for seventh place. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, ``My Favorite Martian,'' the big-screen adaptation of  
the 1960s sitcom, lost just 24 percent of its business in the 
second week to collect $6.7 million for third. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rushmore,'' the quirky love-triangle tale with Bill Murray,  
also maintained most of its audience, collecting $2.7 million for 
ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are estimated grosses at North American theaters for Friday  
through Sunday. Final figures were expected today: 
</P>
<P>
	1. (tie) ``Message in a Bottle,'' $10.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	1. (tie) ``Payback,'' $10.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``My Favorite Martian,'' $6.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Blast from the Past,'' $6.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``October Sky,'' $6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Shakespeare in Love,'' $5.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``She's All That,'' $5.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Office Space,'' $4.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Rushmore,'' $2.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``Saving Private Ryan,'' $2.4 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
