Nasdaq              2,342.01  +  58.41
Gold(final) -    $289.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.

</P>
<P>
	U.S., Russia Reach Steel Pact  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia agreed today to limit steel shipments  
into the United States, avoiding punitive tariffs that had been 
sought by the U.S. steel industry. The agreement was announced by 
Commerce Secretary William Daley. He said it will mean a cut of 
almost 70 percent in Russian steel shipments coming into the United 
States compared to their levels last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Levi Strauss To Slash 5,900 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Levi Strauss, the company that put baby boomers  
in jeans but has been shunned by today's teens, is closing 11 
plants and laying off 30 percent of its work force in the United 
States and Canada. The cutbacks are Levi's latest step to bridge a 
generation gap that has seen sales of its stodgy five-pocket jeans 
eroded by trendier offerings from the likes of Old Navy, the Gap, 
Tommy Hilfiger, MUDD and JNCO. 

</P>
<P>
	Regulatory Hurdle in Olivetti Plan  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Olivetti SpA's bid for the world's sixth-largest  
phone company ran into a regulatory obstacle that will make it 
easier for Telecom Italia to defend itself against the hostile $58 
billion offer. Italy's stock market regulator, Consob, said 
Olivetti's weekend filing failed to meet the standards for a 
full-fledged takeover announcement. That's important because 
Italian law limits the defense a company can mount once it becomes 
the target of a takeover bid ruled valid by Consob. Telecom Italia 
shares were at 109 13/16, up 3 3/8. Olivetti shares were up 0.531 to 
3.875. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Sides With FCC Over Bells  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court lifted a court order that  
had limited the Federal Communication Commission's authority over 
local Bell telephone companies' efforts to provide long-distance 
service. The high court's action further strengthens the FCC's 
ability to open the $110 billion local phone market to competition, 
and is considered another defeat for the nation's five Bell 
telephone companies. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Nixes Japan Computer Appeal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today let stand findings  
that Japan's largest computer maker tried to sell four 
supercomputers to a U.S. research consortium at illegally low 
prices in 1996. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal in 
which NEC Corp. said it was denied a fair and impartial hearing 
before the Commerce Department found it in violation of antidumping 
laws by offering the supercomputers at prices far below their fair 
market value. 

</P>
<P>
	Ruling Barring Aliens' Suits Stands  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today left intact a ruling  
that bars aliens from suing over the discrimination they 
encountered in their U.S. jobs if they lacked the authority, under 
federal immigration law, to work in this country. The court, 
without comment, rejected an appeal by a Nigerian citizen whose 
undocumented immigration status squelched his 1995 job-bias lawsuit 
even though his employer had not known he was unauthorized to work. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Black Spending Increases  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Highly educated black women helped drive a 7  
percent jump in the spending power of black Americans during 1997, 
a new report said. The annual study of wages and salaries by 
Chicago-based Target Market News found that black buying power 
increased to $392 billion in 1997, up from $367 billion in 1996, 
and suggested new areas where corporations can target their 
marketing. 

</P>
<P>
	Peterman Prepares To Liquidate  
</P>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Put the duster-clad man in the J. Peterman  
logo on a horse and point him west. The catalog retailer is 
preparing to ride off into the sunset. Founder John Peterman said 
last-ditch attempts to find a buyer for his struggling company had 
failed. He said he expects a U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge to set a 
date tomorrow for an auction at which the company's assets will be 
sold to the highest bidder, with proceeds going to the company's 
creditors. 

</P>
<P>
	US Checks Report on Lauder Deal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is investigating a  
report that a company chaired by cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder has 
signed a deal with a state-run Yugoslav communications company in 
violation of U.S. sanctions. State Department spokesman James Foley 
said the administration became aware of the purported deal last 
August as a potential sanctions violation. In response to a 
Treasury Department request, Lauder's firm responded with a full 
report, Foley said. 

</P>
<P>
	United Tech To Acquire Sundstrand  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- United Technologies Corp. is snapping up smaller  
rival Sundstrand Corp. in a $4.3 billion cash-and-stock bid. It's 
aimed at bolstering United Technologies' position in the rapidly 
consolidating aerospace and industrial parts industry. The 
Hartford, Conn.-based maker of Pratt &AMP; Whitney jet engines 
announced it plans to fold Rockford-based Sunstrand into its 
Hamilton Standard division. The deal requires shareholder and 
regulatory approval. United Technologies shares were up 1 1/8 to 126 
9/16. Sundstrand shares rose 10 1/4 to 68 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	GM Halts Output of Some Minivans  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will cease production of its  
U.S.-built Opel and Vauxhall Sintra minivans sold in Europe due to 
weak sales. The Sintra is the European version of the minivan sold 
in North American as the Chevrolet Venture, Oldsmobile Silhouette 
and Pontiac Montana. All are built in Doraville, Ga. General Motors 
shares were at 87 1/2, up 2 1/16. 

</P>
