<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charges Filed in Newspaper Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) -- A man pleaded innocent to arson charges  
Monday in connection with a weekend fire that destroyed the offices 
of a local newspaper and a dozen other businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	George Aldrich, 26, a former tenant of the building, was ordered  
to a hospital for a 20-day observation period, said Anson Kaye, a 
spokesman for prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire early Saturday consumed the three-story brick building  
that housed The News Tribune -- a 7,500-circulation community 
newspaper serving readers in Newton and Waltham -- a military 
recruiting office, offices belonging to the Massachusetts 
Parent-Teacher Association Inc., a violin repair shop and several 
other businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, The News Tribune, which publishes only on weekdays,  
printed a front page with a headline reading ``Out of the Ashes'' 
and a photo of a violin maker with an instrument that was spared by 
the blaze. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper's editors and reporters were relocated to Needham at  
the central offices of parent company Community Newspaper Co., the 
Fidelity-owned newspaper group that publishes papers in dozens of 
Massachusetts communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 13:56:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Starters Throw Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- If ever there was an image to scare AL teams,  
it was on view Monday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Clemens, David Cone, Orlando Hernandez, Andy Pettitte and  
Hideki Irabu all throwing together off bullpen mounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I found myself watching them and not getting my work done,''  
Cone joked. ``It was pretty unique to see all of us throwing at the 
same time. It may be the only time this spring, because we will 
going about our individual work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As was the case when Clemens threw for the first time in a New  
York uniform Saturday, fans lined a stadium ramp to watch the five 
pitchers go through the 15-minute session. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was funny. I walked in there and suddenly there they  
were,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``A little theater.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Clemens remains a focal point among the fans, the  
five-time Cy Young Award winner has quickly adjusted to his new 
team following his acquisition from Toronto last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``After a couple days, everything feels like normal again,''  
Clemens said. ``It feels good to be settling in and getting into 
the routine. I'm happy to be on the field with these guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any questions about Clemens' fitting in were answered on Monday.  
The pitcher and shortstop Derek Jeter, who was drilled by a Clemens 
pitch at spring training last year, talked in the clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeter, in jest, said the Yankees hit by Clemens in the past  
``would get him back when he least expects it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to turn the page ... he wasn't trying to hurt me''  
Jeter said. ``He's one of those guys you don't want to face when 
he's on the other team. When he's on your team, he'll back you 
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The five starters got through their workouts fine, but Mike  
Stanton, the lone veteran left-handed reliever, will be out a few 
days by a reoccurring lower back problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a chronic thing he has. It comes and goes,'' Torre said.  
``It's usually one time during the spring after we've had a few 
workouts.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Centerfielder Bernie Williams has the flu and did not work  
out Monday ... Torre may consider going with 10 pitchers in April 
and carrying catcher Mike Figga, who is out of options. ... Torre 
said Darryl Strawberry, coming back following colon cancer surgery, 
was a little tired Monday and did not take batting practice. ... 
Outfielder Paul O'Neill reported with the position players and said 
the highlight of his offseason was playing drums for John 
Mellencamp during a concert in Indianapolis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
