<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Inquiry To End This Weekend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The IOC plans to end its investigation this  
weekend into possible misconduct by members implicated in the Salt 
Lake City scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic officials said Monday the six-man investigative panel  
will begin meeting late this week at International Olympic 
Committee headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have three options,'' said one panel member, speaking on  
condition of anonymity. ``We can exonerate (members). We can issue 
a warning or propose a warning, or we recommend expulsions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The meetings will be private, with no news conferences or  
announcements planned, pending final decisions by the IOC executive 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do hope we will have completed our work by the end of the  
week,'' IOC director general Francois Carrard said. ``We will then 
prepare recommendations for the executive board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No board meeting is scheduled until March 14-15, just before the  
March 17-18 general assembly called to deal with the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard said it is possible the board could decide earlier by  
conference call. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's up to the executive board if they want to wait until the  
14th or take a decision next week,'' he said. ``In any case, there 
will probably be nothing to announce before early next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the IOC inquiry panel recommended the expulsions of  
six members for accepting cash payments, scholarships for their 
relatives or other inducements stemming from Salt Lake City's bid 
for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those six members has since resigned, joining two others  
who had quit previously. The IOC panel notified three other members 
they were still under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, 10 additional members were cited for possible rules  
violations in a report by a Salt Lake City ethics panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cases of expulsion will be put to next month's general assembly,  
where a two-thirds vote is required for ratification. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Chilean IOC member Sergio Santander, one of those  
facing expulsion, resigned as president of his country's national 
Olympic committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The 72-year-old Santander has admitted receiving $4,700 from Tom  
Welch, former president of the Salt Lake City bid organizers, but 
called it a personal contribution to an unsuccessful political 
campaign in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	As with the previous cases, the IOC sent letters seeking  
explanations to those members named in the Salt Lake report. The 
members were given a chance to reply in writing or in person. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to study the files for which we've sent letters  
to all the members on the second list,'' the panel member said. 
``The general interest is to decide on the cases as soon as 
possible, especially for the members themselves whose names have 
been mentioned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The official said he believes the commission will also complete  
its inquiry into the three previous pending cases involving South 
Korea's Kim Un-yong, Russia's Vitaly Smirnov and Ivory Coast's 
Louis Guirandou-N'Diaye. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, a senior IOC executive board member, is the highest-ranking  
official implicated in the Salt Lake case. He was cited in both the 
IOC's internal investigation and that of the Salt Lake ethics 
panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim has mounted an aggressive defense, describing the  
allegations against him as a politically motivated plot to smear 
his name and undermine his ambitions to succeed Juan Antonio 
Samaranch as IOC president. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel member said it's possible that not all remaining cases  
will be completed this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not unthinkable that we might need more information on  
one or two cases,'' he said. ``This is a serious matter. You are 
not going to judge on incomplete documents or information. You 
cannot rule out that some cases will be deferred to the future. I 
would hope not in the interest of the members themselves, but you 
cannot be sure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Also, Kevan Gosper, an Australian member of the IOC's  
executive board, rebuked John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance 
president Dave D'Alessandro for speaking out against the 
international committee's handling of the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed he should be debating this in public as if he  
is the conscience of the IOC,'' Gosper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
