<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 13:56:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior IOC Exec Decries US Sponsor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A senior IOC member rebuked the chief executive of  
a top American sponsor Monday for speaking out against the 
international committee's handling of the Olympic corruption 
scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevan Gosper, an Australian member of the International Olympic  
Committee's executive board, said he was dismayed that David 
D'Alessandro had aired his criticism through the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed he should be debating this in public as if he  
is the conscience of the IOC,'' said Gosper, one of the IOC 
leadership's chief spokesmen. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Alessandro, president of Boston-based John Hancock Mutual Life  
Insurance, has been the only corporate executive so far to publicly 
challenge the IOC over its handling of the Salt Lake bribery 
scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	John Hancock has canceled negotiations with NBC for $20 million  
in Olympic advertising and removed the Olympic rings from its 
stationery. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Alessandro voiced his complaints in interviews and in written  
opinion pieces in U.S. newspapers that the IOC was losing 
credibility every day it allowed the scandal to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think D'Alessandro's comments are unfortunate,'' Gosper said  
in a telephone interview from Melbourne, Australia. ``I think it's 
quite improper for him to debate this through the media. After all, 
he's a (Olympic) partner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone call to John Hancock seeking comment from  
D'Alessandro was not immediately returned Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In his criticism nearly two weeks ago, D'Alessandro said he had  
taken his concerns to top IOC officials and ``their response was 
`We're going to investigate thoroughly and we're going to do things 
right.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Hancock is one of 11 major international corporate sponsors of  
the Olympics who pay around $50 million for exclusive advertising 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The sponsors fear their investment is being devalued by the  
continuing fallout from Salt Lake City's successful bid for the 
2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four IOC members, a fifth of the total roster, have been  
implicated in receiving cash payments, scholarships, free health 
care and other improper inducements. 
</P>
<P>
	Hancock was one of the companies represented when top sponsors  
met with IOC marketing chiefs in New York 10 days ago. The sponsors 
strongly urged the IOC to clean up the scandal quickly or risk a 
rebellion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, (the sponsors) are demonstrating their concern,''  
Gosper said. ``It's understandable. The reputation of our rings has 
been tarnished. But, from my corporate experience, the way to 
manage this is to quietly talk with your partners, not to debate it 
through the media.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gosper also urged IOC investigators to move quickly to clear any  
members who are innocent of any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was concerned that some members have been left in  
limbo for too long and should be exonerated before the March 17-18 
general assembly called to deal with the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine members have either resigned or been ousted in the scandal.  
Three others have been under investigation since December, and 10 
additional members were cited in the Salt Lake ethics panel report 
issued earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC inquiry commission, headed by vice president Dick Pound,  
is to meet late this week and this weekend to deal with the 
remaining cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Gosper said the Salt Lake panel had unfairly cited some members,  
including Australia's Phil Coles, by failing to contact them in 
advance for their version of events. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem with the current procedure is that anyone who has  
been mentioned appears to be guilty of misconduct,'' he said. 
``This is a very unfortunate situation. To rectify that, the Pound 
commission should act quite rapidly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The executive board, which must finalize any verdicts, is not  
scheduled to meet until March 15-16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 06:47:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
