<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> College Produces 2 Grammy Nominees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEVELLAND, Texas (AP) -- Big-city record producers often say that  
star quality and stage savvy can't be taught in school. 
</P>
<P>
	Folks in the small community of Levelland hope to prove that  
notion wrong when two alumni of South Plains College's commercial 
music program -- Natalie Maines of the Dixie Chicks and Lee Ann 
Womack -- compete at the 41st annual Grammy Awards on Wednesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Womack is nominated for best female country vocal  
performance. The Dixie Chicks, long known around Texas for their 
contemporary country sound, are nominated for three awards, 
including best new artist and best country album. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lee Ann is a very energetic, enthusiastic performer who gave  
100 percent every performance at SPC,'' recalled her instructor, 
John Hartin, creator of the commercial music program. 
</P>
<P>
	``Natalie has incredible musical energy and takes command of any  
material she is performing. I certainly hope they both win a 
Grammy. I feel that they are the ones who ought to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The program teaches students the skills they need to walk out  
and become professional musicians, including songwriting, 
performing, navigating the industry and writing music for 
instruments they don't know how to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Womack graduated in 1985, Ms. Maines in 1994.  
</P>
<P>
	Hartin, who traveled the country with his band The Classics in  
the late '60s, took a position at South Plains College in 1975 
because he wanted to escape the sleepless nights and small-town 
diners of life on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't a place that a person could go to learn about  
what it takes to survive in the music business,'' Hartin said. 
``You could learn music and you could learn business but to learn 
how the two intermingled was impossible in 1975 when I came here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hartin's vision began with classes in the women's gymnasium and  
drew six students from the small towns around Levelland, the aptly 
named, pancake-flat community near the New Mexico state line. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the program is staffed by 10 full-time faculty members and  
has more than 60 students. The college of 6,700 students also 
boasts two TV studios and several recording studios. 
</P>
<P>
	Heath Wright, lead singer for the country band Ricochet and a  
graduate of the school's music program, said the training boosts an 
aspiring star's chances of success. 
</P>
<P>
	``You learn a lot about songwriting and creativity,'' Wright  
said. ``Many bands are out there reproducing other people's sounds. 
Out there, they teach you how to find your own sound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cory Williams, a third-year student, found himself playing  
alongside country music artist Ray Price when the musician was 
passing through Lubbock and needed a fiddle player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was able to play the whole show with him because I was able  
to sight-read the music,'' Williams said. ``You can never have a 
guarantee, but people who get their degree here seem to be doing 
pretty well these days.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
