<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Retreat / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices retreated early  
today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid a gloomy outlook for U.S. 
exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans posted new lows for the ninth consecutive session as  
market participants see few rays of light in the supply and demand 
picture. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil is expected to harvest a near-record competing crop in  
the coming weeks amid sharply lower world demand because of 
economic turmoil that has left the biggest importers hurting for 
cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the gloomy outlook are predictions that U.S. farmers  
this spring will plant even more acreage to soybeans than they did 
last year, when they produced a record-large crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures also retreated as market participants sought to  
find a level at which export demand will be stimulated and domestic 
feed demand will pick up. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures suffered the least, finding some support from  
continued-steady demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for March delivery fell 1 1/4 cents to $2.53 1/2 a bushel; March  
corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.14 1/2 a bushel; March oats were unchanged at 
$1.01 1/2 a bushel; March soybeans fell 5 1/4 cents to $4.73 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mostly lower on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle was unchanged at 66.70 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle fell .33 cent to 73.02 cents a pound; April lean hogs 
fell .07 cent to 45.75 cents a pound; March pork bellies fell 1.5 
cents to 52.80 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
