<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks-Pirates Trade On Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Pirates' 2-for-1 trade with the  
Arizona Diamondbacks -- supposedly a done deal last week -- remained 
on hold Monday with Pirates general manager Cam Bonifay uncertain 
if it will be completed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates planned to send second baseman Tony Womack and  
outfielder Al Martin to Arizona for outfielder Bernard Gilkey as 
soon as they signed shortstop Pat Meares. But the deal stalled over 
the weekend when Pittsburgh balked at paying any of Gilkey's $6 
million in deferred salary. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing to report,'' Bonifay said from the Pirates'  
spring training camp in Bradenton, Fla. ``They said they were going 
to consider some things and get back to us, but there's nothing 
new.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bonifay talked Monday with Diamondbacks general manager Joe  
Garagiola Jr., but Arizona did not alter its offer either by paying 
more of Gilkey's contract or throwing in another player. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates want Arizona to pay the difference in the $6 million  
owed Martin through the 2000 season and the $11 million due Gilkey. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be nice to have this resolved ... to the point of  
Diamondbacks making a decision,'' Bonifay said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilkey, who slumped in 1997 and 1998 after hitting 30 homers and  
driving in 117 runs with the New York Mets in 1996, is owed $2.5 
million in base salary each of the next two seasons. He also is due 
$2.5 million each year in deferred salary and one additional $1 
million deferred payment. 
</P>
<P>
	The deferred salary goes into an annuity that will pay Gilkey $1  
million a year for 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he thought the trade would eventually be done, Bonifay  
said, ``I don't know. I can't honestly say that. It's not in my 
hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trade would allow both sides to deal off outfielders who  
prefer to play elsewhere; Martin first asked Pittsburgh to trade 
him last season. But it would cost the Pirates their only proven 
leadoff hitter in Womack, the two-time NL stolen base champion and 
the player most coveted in the trade by Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin, who lives in Scottsdale, Ariz., was counting on the deal  
being completed and has yet to leave for camp. Womack arrived in 
Florida 10 days ago and said he is preparing as if a trade wasn't a 
possibility. 
</P>
<P>
	But with position players due in camp Wednesday, Martin must  
decide whether to report to a team that has spent much of the 
offseason trying to deal him. He lost his starting job when Bonifay 
swung off-season trades for left fielder Brian Giles and center 
fielder Brant Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonifay realizes Martin will be unhappy if he reports to  
Bradenton, and is concerned about the effect that would have on his 
teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm concerned for both Tony and Al because of this being so  
publicly well known,'' Bonifay said. ``You've got to go back and 
talk to the players. We have to tell them we still like them. ... 
I'm not going to say that both players' feelings have not been 
affected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin hasn't talked to reporters in recent days, but has told  
friends on the Pirates he is discouraged the trade has not been 
completed. Mike Benjamin, who played for Boston last season, also 
can't be too happy after signing with the understanding he would 
play either second or shortstop, positions now filled by Womack and 
Meares. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've got excellent depth in the middle infield ...  
with Tony on the club, Mike Benjamin and (spring invitee) Rafael 
Bournigal. The middle of the diamond turns into one of our 
strengths,'' Bonifay said. ``We're going to be excited about 
getting underway, to be honest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the Arizona trade falls through, Bonifay said it doesn't  
mean the Pirates must begin the season with their current roster. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we need to make a move, it's not like we have to make it on  
the first day of spring training,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Meares reported to Bradenton on Monday after landing  
neither the length or value of contract he wanted. He turned down 
an $11 million, three-year offer from Minnesota last fall and 
reportedly sought $4 million a year, only to sign with Pittsburgh 
for less than half that. 
</P>
<P>
	There also was no progress in talks with first baseman Kevin  
Young, who wants a five-year contract worth about $30 million. The 
Pirates have offered $16.5 million over three years. Young said he 
will not discuss negotiations once camp begins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
