<DOCNO> APW19990222.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 17:55:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HMO Trade Group Urges Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As prospects for ``patients' rights''  
legislation brighten, the HMO trade group is urging its members to 
voluntarily let patients who are denied care appeal to outside 
experts. 
</P>
<P>
	And fearful that Congress will give patients the right to sue  
HMOs, the American Association of Health Plans says it could accept 
legislation requiring health plans to offer external appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	At its board meeting Monday, the group endorsed a set of  
principles for Congress to use in designing an external review 
process. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to be part of the discussion,'' said Karen Ignagni,  
the group's president, who will outline the board's actions at a 
news conference Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Ignagni said, the group spent its energies fighting  
legislation mandating benefits and expanding the right to sue. It 
argued that any new requirements would drive up costs and force 
employers to drop insurance coverage. Now, with Congress set to 
act, things have changed, Ignagni said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we enter a year when people are looking at policy, we want  
to be clear on what we're prepared to say yes to,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	External appeals give patients the right to challenge decisions  
to doctors not associated with the insurance company. In recent 
months, many large health insurance companies have adopted these 
procedures on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there are big differences among the federal and private  
proposals, including who pays for the appeals, who picks the 
external panel, the timeliness of the review and what services are 
covered. 
</P>
<P>
	HMO legislation was hotly debated last year, though Republicans  
and Democrats never engaged in serious negotiations and nothing 
ultimately passed. But chances appear much better in 1999 as 
Republicans look to prove they can do more than impeachment and 
President Clinton searches for a policy victory. 
</P>
<P>
	While Americans are generally happy with the health care they  
receive, many fear that cost-conscious insurance companies might 
deny care they may someday need. The right to appeal such denials 
is a central feature of every comprehensive proposal to regulate 
health maintenance organizations and other managed care plans. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, patients generally got whatever care their doctors  
recommended, and health costs spiraled. Under managed care, the 
insurance company controls access to specialists and expensive 
tests and treatments, trying to avoid paying for unnecessary costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The HMO trade group is not requiring its member plans to adopt  
appeals processes in order to remain in the group. That could come 
later this year, Ignagni said. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's actions are a step in the right direction, though the  
details will be crucial, said Judy Waxman, chief lobbyist for 
Families USA, a consumer group that is pushing for new laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like they're not just stonewalling, which is good,''  
she said. ``Obviously, the plans are trying to stave off any kind 
of ability to sue them. They may feel this is the lesser of two 
evils.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 05:30:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Controversy for DiCaprio Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Life hasn't been a beach for Leonardo DiCaprio  
on the set of his new movie in Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Beach'' has been awash in controversy and protests over  
the planting of non-native coconut trees and the smoothing over of 
sand dunes on Phi Island, where it is being filmed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a stab at my reputation if I'm associated with a film  
that comes in and recklessly destroys things,'' DiCaprio said in 
the March 1 edition of Time. ``This is something I probably have to 
get used to -- lies culminating into something much more hysterical 
and out of hand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiCaprio defended the movie, saying producers have worked hard  
to try and portray the landscape's beauty. 
</P>
<P>
	``The facts are that absolutely nothing wrong was done to that  
island,'' DiCaprio said. ``If anything, I've seen our people take 
meticulous care with every little branch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Beach'' is based on Alex Garland's novel about an island  
paradise settled by a commune of world travelers. The movie marks 
DiCaprio's return to the big screen since taking a year off after 
the success of ``Titanic.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
