<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Set To Air Lewinsky Interview </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky was very frank about her  
feelings toward President Clinton and Kenneth Starr in an interview 
with ABC but had a hard time explaining her attraction to married 
men, Barbara Walters said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Walters met with reporters to describe her long-awaited  
interview with the former White House intern, who has yet to appear 
in public to discuss her relationship with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The interview took place Saturday in New York and will be  
broadcast over two hours starting at 9 p.m. EST on March 3, the 
final day of a television ``sweeps'' period used to set advertising 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is open, she is expressive, she is sometimes very  
touching,'' Walters said. ``Sometimes when she describes herself 
you realize she can be very difficult. She is funny and extremely 
articulate. This is not a Valley Girl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the impeachment saga, Ms. Lewinsky was hotly pursued by  
interviewers, including talk show host Roseanne, who offered Ms. 
Lewinsky more than $1 million to talk. ABC did not pay for the 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky said she chose Walters because she felt it was the  
best way to establish her credibility, Walters said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Monica was a little apprehensive in the beginning but  
was not nervous,'' Walters said. ``She looked very striking in 
appearance, very attractive. Once she began I think she forgot 
there were cameras there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The most difficult question for her to address is why she gets  
involved with married men, Walters said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky is ``teary'' at some points, but ``this is not a  
sobbing interview,'' Walters said. 
</P>
<P>
	After nailing down the interview in November, ABC had to wait  
until last week for permission from Starr. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky balked only once at answering a question due to  
restrictions placed on her by Starr. It concerned the events of 
Jan. 16, 1998, when she was first questioned about her relationship 
with Clinton by Starr's representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr had asked that Ms. Lewinsky have a lawyer present during  
the interview, and she was told not to characterize what was said 
to her by prosecutors, Walters said. Instead, Ms. Lewinsky talks 
about how she felt during the questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr also insisted Ms. Lewinsky not comment on other  
investigations being conducted by the special prosecutor, according 
to ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC has not decided whether it will air excerpts of the  
interview before March 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky gave another interview to British news anchor Jon  
Snow on Sunday at her mother's New York apartment. It will air in 
Britain on March 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Channel 4 would not comment on the amount it paid for the  
interview, but the British national news agency Press Association 
reported the sum was $660,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
