<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Advocates Bid To Save Horses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) -- A month before Howard Brand died of  
cancer, the farmer amended his will to say he wanted his 1964 
Cadillac crushed and his animals destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after he died in January at age 88, animal rights groups  
hired a lawyer and launched a campaign to save the animals. Their 
fate now rests with a probate court judge, who decided Monday to 
consider whether it's legal to order the destruction of animals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pleased that the judge is letting us be heard,'' said Mary  
Ingham, who is leading the campaign and whose uncle has taken care 
of the animals for years at Brand's farm in Essex Junction. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyer for the estate and those who knew Brand say he wanted  
to ensure his animals -- believed to be four horses and a mule -- 
would not be treated poorly after he was gone. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was not a man who abused animals, he was a man who was  
practical about animals,'' attorney Tom McCormick said Monday. 
``This was best for his animals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCormick contends the animals are private property and Brand  
had every right to destroy them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Legislature permits this,'' he said. ``Laying down animals  
is not in of itself cruelty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the group trying to save Brand's animals argues that  
destroying an animal for no cause is inhumane. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the right to dispose of property that is  
living and breathing is limited,'' attorney Alan Bjerke said. 
``It's against the public policy of the state to allow an animal to 
be put to death by will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Fitzpatrick, the attorney who drafted the amendment to the  
will, recalled his surprise when Brand told him of his final 
wishes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wanted the Cadillac crushed and he wanted to make sure I  
was there to see the Cadillac crushed,'' to make sure no parts were 
removed, Fitzpatrick said in court. In the same conversation, he 
said he wanted his animals destroyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
