<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices rose early Tuesday following  
a jump earlier on Wall Street. The dollar slipped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average rose 66.75 points, or 0.47 percent, to  
14,323.42 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Monday, the 
average closed up 158.63 points, or 1.13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.08 yen, down 0.90 yen from late Monday in  
Tokyo but above its level of 120.91 yen in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices started higher after  
the Dow Jones industrial average surged 212.73, or 2.3 percent, to 
9,552.68 at Monday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Dow's best showing in five weeks and left it within  
90 points of its Jan. 8 all-time high of 9,643.32. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow's advance came on the back of a drop in bond market  
interest rates ahead of U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan's semiannual testimony on the state of the economy before 
the U.S. Senate Banking Committee on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo market was also cheered by comments Monday by Taku  
Yamasaki, a former head of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's 
policy research affairs council that Japan should use public funds 
to buy land and boost stock prices to solve its asset deflation 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting the market was the yen's recent weakness against  
the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger dollar helps Japanese exporters by increasing the  
value of their export earnings when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar met some profit-taking after  
climbing to an 11-week high against the yen Monday. Also, the euro 
was traded at 133.46 yen, up from 134.40 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section gained 2.45 points, or 0.22 percent, to 1,111.36. The 
TOPIX closed up 14.41 points, or 1.32 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond  
rose to 1.760 percent from Monday's finish of 1.725 percent, 
driving its price down to 100.32 yen from 100.60 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
