<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cost of Tyson Hearings Taxes NAC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) -- The cost of hearing boxer Mike Tyson's  
plea to reinstate his license has cleaned out the Nevada Athletic 
Commission's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Marc Ratner, the commission's executive director, on Monday told  
lawmakers that an $18,500 emergency appropriation is needed to keep 
the panel from going broke by late March. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously we were not budgeted to pay for this,'' said Ratner.  
``We did not have the legal right to ask him to pay for the 
hearings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that could change. The commission has requested a bill that  
would allow costs of future hearings to be collected from fighters 
asking for a license. 
</P>
<P>
	The unanticipated costs included rent for a hearing room big  
enough to handle a crowd of more than 300, including 135 members of 
the media, Ratner told the Senate Finance Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's license was suspended after he bit Evander Holyfield  
during a June 1997 title bout won by Holyfield. The Athletic 
Commission voted 4-1 to restore Tyson's boxing license in October 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least you won't have the cost of another Tyson hearing for  
another year,'' said state Sen. Ray Rawson, referring to the 
boxer's most recent jailing. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson pled no contest to two counts of second-degree assault and  
was sentenced earlier this month to one year in jail for assaulting 
a motorist after a car accident in Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	He will learn Wednesday whether he'll lose privileges and time  
off for good behavior for hurling a television set Friday during an 
outburst in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson, 32, is still on probation from a 1991 rape conviction,  
and authorities in Indiana must decide if he has violated the terms 
of his probation there. Tyson was released in 1995 after serving 
three years of a six-year sentence, and his probation was set to 
expire in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
