<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CompuServe Gets a New Look </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- CompuServe, the pioneer online service  
that was overtaken and bought by America Online Inc., updated its 
software today in an effort to reposition itself as a home on the 
Internet for busy adults. 
</P>
<P>
	CompuServe says it will continue to serve the professional  
people key to its business, but with more user-friendly software, 
flashier features and lower prices for the service. 
</P>
<P>
	The software upgrade, called CompuServe 2000, supports  
higher-speed modem connections and is easier for users to install 
and customize on their personal computers. Users will see a ``Main 
Menu'' screen with a continuously updated news ticker with 
headlines from The Associated Press, market analysis from 
CBSMarketWatch.com and personalized news folders. 
</P>
<P>
	E-mail is easier to use, modeled after the version that helped  
America Online become the world's leading online service with more 
than 15 million subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Subscribers will be given five user names per account, each  
ending in the domain name ``cs.com,'' shortened from 
``compuserve.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New members will pay just $9.95 a month for 20 hours of online  
access, with each additional hour billed at less than 5 cents a 
minute. In addition, CompuServe is cutting the cost of unlimited 
access from $24.95 to $19.95 a month. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL bought CompuServe's content and subscribers after former  
owner H&AMP;R Block sold it to WorldCom Inc. in January 1998. 
CompuServe's subscriber base then fell from about 2.6 million to 2 
million, as the huge influx of new Internet users found more 
convenient ways to go online. 
</P>
<P>
	Long a favorite of technology lovers, CompuServe was known for  
identifying its members online with long strings of numbers instead 
of catchy names, and charging subscribers a premium to get 
specialized business, computer and financial information. 
</P>
<P>
	``CompuServe 2000 is for grown-ups who want fast solutions to  
manage their busy lifestyles -- from content to commerce to 
connectivity to customer service,'' said CompuServe chief operating 
officer Audrey Weil. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 03:45:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Little Guys Could Steal Boxing Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Last Friday afternoon, in the Maryland jail he calls home these  
days, Mike Tyson threw a fit, then a TV set, and finally got 
himself tossed into an isolation cell for the weekend. All things 
considered, it probably could have been worse. 
</P>
<P>
	Because if Tyson had been sitting in front of the TV set the  
next evening, when welterweights Felix Trinidad and Pernell 
Whitaker fought 12 very entertaining rounds at Madison Square 
Garden in New York, he might be feeling more desperate still. 
</P>
<P>
	Not too long ago, Iron Mike was the glamour puss in boxing's  
glamour division. It seemed like people would throw down good money 
forever to see him fight anybody, so long as he was bigger than Joe 
Pesci and smaller than a Chevy Cavalier. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson probably wasn't thinking career when he got into it with  
two older men during a traffic altercation in Maryland last summer, 
which is how he wound up being jailed. But truth be told, a few 
months in the slammer didn't figure to affect his appeal much, one 
way or the other. 
</P>
<P>
	All of a sudden, though, the tectonic plates below boxing's  
surface are shifting dramatically. All of a sudden, neither Tyson 
nor the heavyweights he's been carrying all these years can count 
on fans of the ``sweet science'' to make pay-per-view deposits 
directly into their retirement accounts. All of a sudden -- first 
with last Saturday's Oscar De La Hoya-Ike Quartey bout, and then 
the Trinidad-Whitaker fight -- their faster, lighter, flashier 
cousins are proving to be much more entertaining buys. 
</P>
<P>
	This fact was not wasted on Don King, who promotes Trinidad and  
used to promote Tyson, but now is being sued by Iron Mike. The 
referee had barely raised Trinidad's hand in victory Saturday when 
King opened negotiations for what could be a megafight against De 
La Hoya. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is he going to be chicken De La Hoya and not fight Trinidad or  
will he be macho Oscar and accept this challenge?'' King said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people deserve to see the best fighting the best. Tito  
Trinidad is ready to fight anybody, any place, any time. Are you 
listening Oscar?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boxing insiders have long insisted the soap opera surrounding  
Tyson diverted attention from a wealth of deserving fighters in 
several divisions, and Trinidad, a 26-year-old Puerto Rican, was a 
perfect example. He was 33-0 going in, but still largely unknown, 
even though the Whitaker fight marked the 12th time in five years 
he was defending his IBF title at 147 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad was such an unknown, in fact, that while the weigh-in  
was going on Friday, he took off running through the streets of 
Manhattan to lose three pounds and make the weight at 147. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the way Trinidad pummeled Whitaker, recognition should  
flow his way. ``Sweet Pea,'' one of the great defensive fighters of 
the last two decades, got mashed. He was floored early, he suffered 
a broken jaw in the middle rounds and picked up a nasty cut over 
his right eye toward the end. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old Whitaker hadn't fought in the past 16 months  
while engaged in drug and alcohol rehabilitation. But he was 
surprisingly sharp and even sharper-tongued afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't do anything well,'' Whitaker said. ``Hell, yeah , I  
think I won. I had a good time. I'll be back. ... It was close, but 
I'm not going to whine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whitaker even had enough left to compare Trinidad and De La  
Hoya, who beat him in April 1997. He gave the nod to Trinidad. 
``Much better than De La Hoya,'' Whitaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the welterweights intend to steal the thunder from the  
heavies, they had better move quickly to match Trinidad and De La 
Hoya -- even though his promoter, Bob Arum, is King's sworn rival. 
</P>
<P>
	Both fighters are committed to opponents in May, De La Hoya  
against Oba Carr, Trinidad against Vincent Pettway. The only 
remaining obstacle is agreeing to a TV network into which the rest 
of us can pour our pay-per-view dollars. De La Hoya has an 
exclusive contract with HBO, and King has already said he is 
willing to go there; he's already done the math. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fight,'' King said, ``will do two million buys on  
pay-per-view.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With those kind of numbers in the air, Tyson should be in a  
hurry to get out of jail and back into the ring. Not only is his 
own window of opportunity closing, but by missing the sportscasts 
on television Friday, he also spared himself this chilling tidbit: 
</P>
<P>
	Buster Douglas, the same Buster Douglas whose 1990 knockout of  
Tyson, started Iron Mike's downward spiral, won for the eighth time 
Friday night in nine matches on the comeback trail. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@apmail.ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
