<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fishermen Saved From Ice Floe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ten people fishing on a frozen lake were rescued  
when the ice beneath their feet broke into a floe and stranded them 
on open water. 
</P>
<P>
	The fishermen were stranded for about 30 minutes Sunday on Lake  
St. Clair. They were rescued by the Coast Guard, which lowered a 
rescue swimmer by hoist cable to ensure there was no one left on 
the floe in ice shanties. 
</P>
<P>
	Already nine times this season, the Coast Guard in Detroit has  
been deployed to rescue fishermen stranded on floating ice, said 
Philip Myers, a search-and-rescue controller. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 95 people have been rescued from Lake St. Clair and the  
Saginaw Bay area, and one person has died, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know a lot of people who have gone out risking life and limb  
because there's fish in the water,'' he said. ``Some of them are 
actually repeat rescuees and think, `It hasn't killed me yet, and 
hey, somebody will come and rescue me.''' 
</P>
<P>
	State lawmakers are proposing legislation to make fishermen pay  
for their rescues and punish those who ignore warnings about unsafe 
ice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
