<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 14:56:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Jones Starts Internet Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dow Jones &AMP; Co. has created an index to track 40  
key Internet stocks in a move that should help investors keep track 
of one of the hottest sectors of the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The list, inaugurated last week, joins a plethora of Internet  
indexes sponsored by brokerages, research firms and trade 
magazines, all seeking to become a benchmark for measuring the 
health of the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to the strength of the Dow Jones name, the index is sure  
to become widely used. Dow Jones, publisher of the Wall Street 
Journal, keeps track of hundreds of indexes, including the most 
easily recognized benchmark for blue chip stocks, the Dow Jones 
industrial average, which the company started in 1896. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet index has two components: a 15-stock average that  
will track electronic commerce companies, and a 25-stock indicator 
that follows Internet service-related stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The commerce portion includes bookseller Amazon.com, auction  
house eBay, the broker ETrade and the Web portal site Yahoo! Two of 
the companies on this list will be removed if the merger deals they 
have struck are approved by shareholders. Geocities, a provider of 
individual Web pages, is being acquired by Yahoo!, and the portal 
site Excite is being bought by At Home, a high-speed Internet 
service provider.. 
</P>
<P>
	The services index, in addition to At Home, also includes  
companies such as the software maker Netscape Communications Corp. 
and the company that has agreed to buy it, America Online Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Due to the rapid pace of consolidation among Internet stocks,  
Dow Jones plans to review the index quarterly in order to make any 
adjustments. 
</P>
<P>
	In order to be listed on either part of the index, a company  
must derive at least half of its revenues from Internet-related 
business, have been listed on a stock exchange for at least three 
months, have a market value of at least $100 million, and have 
enough trading activity to meet certain tests of liquidity. 
</P>
<P>
	The index closed at 180.19 points Monday, up 9.85 points, or  
5.78 percent from Friday. The index is calculated from a base of 
100 points as of June 30, 1998, and Dow Jones has compiled data on 
the index as far back as June 30, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading in options on the electronic commerce portion of the  
index was to begin Friday on the Chicago Board Options Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 18:43:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blackhawks Fire Graham as Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Dirk Graham, who was known as a hard-hitting  
forward when he played for the Chicago Blackhawks but who led them 
to their worst record in 42 years as coach, was fired Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant coach Lorne Molleken will replace Graham as interim  
coach, the team announced. Denis Savard will stay on as assistant 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham, just 59 games into his first season as coach, will  
remain with the Blackhawks organization, team officials said. His 
new position was unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham had little coaching experience when he was hired by the  
Blackhawks last June. He had spent just one season, 1995-96, as an 
assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the time of Graham's appointment, general manager Bob  
Murray insisted that Graham's demeanor in the locker room as a 
player and captain of the Blackhawks was what mattered. Graham was 
known for motivating his teammates when he played for the 
Blackhawks from 1988 to 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	However, this year's team has shown little motivation under  
Graham. The Blackhawks have lost 10 of their last 12 games and are 
19 games under .500. That hasn't happened since 1955-57, when the 
Blackhawks finished 23 games under .500. 
</P>
<P>
	The team has the worst record in the Western Conference and the  
second-worst record in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	After the team's 6-3 loss to the Boston Bruins on Sunday, a  
frustrated Graham said the coaching staff believed in what they 
were teaching, but had received a negative response from the 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	A tough and aggressive player, Graham won the 1991 Frank Selke  
award for his defensive skills. 
</P>
<P>
	He had 152 goals, 190 assists and 685 penalty minutes in 546  
games for Chicago. He also holds the team record for most 
shorthanded goals in a season, 10 in 1988-89. 
</P>
<P>
	But most importantly, he was a leader. He was captain for 6 1/2  
seasons and part of the 1992 squad that won 11 straight playoff 
games before losing to Pittsburgh in the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham replaced Craig Hartsburg, who was fired in April after  
Chicago's 30-39-13 season, when they failed to make the playoffs 
for the first time since 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	Molleken, 42, came to the Blackhawks last June from the Edmonton  
Oilers, where he was head coach of two minor league affiliates. He 
previously coached the Saskatoon Blades of the Western Hockey 
League and was a coach in the Saskatchewan Junior Hockey League. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blackhawks also announced the appointment of defenseman  
Trent Yawney as an assistant coach. Yawney, 33, a 12-year veteran 
of the NHL, broke his arm in a game at Nashville and is out for the 
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
