<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Feb. 22, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Albanians Deciding on Plan  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- Facing tomorrow's deadline, ethnic  
Albanians met tonight to decide whether to accept the self-rule 
plan for Kosovo designed to end their yearlong conflict. They were 
told by Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, that a peacekeeping 
force would ensure their security in event an agreement is reached. 
Meanwhile, Serb negotiators continued to refuse to accede to 
demands that a NATO peacekeeping force be part of any peace deal. 
But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has said that NATO would 
not carry out threatened airstrikes against Serb targets if the 
ethnic Albanians did not give final approval to the agreement. 

</P>
<P>
	Dragging Death Case Nears End  
</P>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- Closing arguments will be made tomorrow in  
the capital murder case of John William King, one of three men 
accused of dragging James Byrd Jr. to his death last June. 
Prosecutors wrapped up their case following the testimony of a 
pathologist. Dr. Tommy Brown said Byrd was conscious as he was 
dragged by a pickup truck until his head was torn off by a concrete 
drainage duct. Prosecutors need to prove Byrd was alive when he was 
dragged in order to prove kidnapping and murder, which together 
would expose alleged white supremacist King to the death penalty. 
The defense called only three witnesses, whose testimony lasted 
less than an hour, before resting. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 212.73 As Stocks Soar  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices blasted higher today amid renewed  
confidence that interest rates would stay low and that the market 
for mergers and acquisitions is still hot. The Dow industrials 
climbed 212.73 points to 9,552.68, the biggest point gain in five 
weeks. That left the Dow 90 points shy of the record 9,643.32. 
Broad-market indexes posted solid gains as well. On the NYSE, 
advancers led decliners 1,953-1,061. The Nasdaq was up 58.41 at 
2,342.01. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, Govs. Clash on Education  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and the nation's governors  
grappled with differences over education policy today at a 
roundtable discussion at the White House. Some governors raised 
doubts about Clinton's education initiative to build more schools, 
hire more teachers and penalize states for poor classroom 
performance. Michigan Gov. John Engler, a Republican, said it was 
impossible for the federal government to design ``a 
one-size-fits-all system.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Tobacco Co. Tops Soft Money List  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tobacco giant Philip Morris, which pushed for  
defeat of anti-smoking legislation, gave $2.4 million in 
unregulated soft money to the two major political parties over the 
last two years, the advocacy group Common Cause said. The company 
gave more than any other soft money contributor. Philip Morris 
contributed $2 million to the Republicans and $419,164 to the 
Democrats in 1997 and 1998, according to Common Cause. 

</P>
<P>
	Obasanjo Party Winning Nigeria Vote  
</P>
<P>
	LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) -- American election observers reported  
incidents of fraud in legislative elections held days before 
Saturday's presidential vote that will lead to Nigeria's return to 
democracy. The observers said they witnessed ballot box-stuffing, 
voter intimidation and lax adherence to elections standards. The 
party of Nigeria's presidential front-runner, former Gen. Olusegun 
Obasanjo, seemed likely to sweep both the Senate and the House of 
Representatives. 

</P>
<P>
	NHTSA Probing Ford Explorer SUVs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The National Highway Traffic Safety  
Administration is investigating dozens of complaints of fires or 
heavy smoke in some earlier model Ford Explorer sport utility 
vehicles. A hot portion of the blower assembly may ignite debris 
that can collect in the venting system in explorers from model 
years 1992-1994, an agency report said. The safety agency is also 
looking into complaints that some 1997 and 1998 Explorers continue 
to accelerate after the driver takes his foot off the gas or 
disengages the cruise control. 

</P>
<P>
	Chemo Cuts Cervical Cancer Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- In the first breakthrough in the treatment of  
spreading cervical cancer since the 1950s, a series of studies 
found that adding chemotherapy to radiation can cut the risk of 
death in half. The five studies proved so convincing that the 
National Cancer Institute took the unusual step of mailing letters 
to thousands of doctors urging them to adopt the new approach 
immediately. 

</P>
<P>
	Rodman Plans To Sign With Lakers  
</P>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Dennis Rodman moved closer to  
playing for the Los Angeles Lakers today, announcing at a news 
conference that he hoped to sign a contract before the day was 
through. The team said it wants to have the seven-time rebounding 
champion in uniform ``sometime very soon.'' Rodman insisted he is 
in good shape and could immediately play 30 to 35 minutes a game. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  

</P>
