<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Lawyer Seeks Tobacco Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A groundbreaking tobacco litigator from New  
Jersey claims a prominent Baltimore lawyer is withholding his share 
of attorneys' fees due from Maryland's $4.2 billion share of the 
national tobacco settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Marc Z. Edell of Morristown, who won the first jury award  
against a tobacco company, is suing the law firm of Peter G. 
Angelos to recover the money -- perhaps as much as $250 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed earlier this month in U.S. District court here  
charges fraud and breach of contract. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for the Angelos firm issued a statement Monday denying  
that Edell was owed a contingency fee -- the legal term for a 
percentage of the settlement -- and that any suggestion of fraud is 
``outrageous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Edell maintains Angelos, who is also majority owner of the  
Baltimore Orioles baseball team, reneged on what was essentially a 
handshake deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Informal understandings are common among lawyers, according to  
Richard Daynard, another attorney who worked with the Angelos firm 
in the Maryland tobacco case. Daynard said Monday he is still 
wrangling with the firm over his compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Edell had obtained the first jury award against a tobacco  
company in a liability case, $400,000 for the family of Rose 
Cipollone of New Jersey in 1988. But the award was overturned on 
appeal, and the lawsuit was dropped in 1992, a process that drained 
Edell's finances. 
</P>
<P>
	Edell contends the Angelos firm recruited him in December 1995  
to join forces and bid on handling Maryland's lawsuit against the 
tobacco industry. 
</P>
<P>
	He believed he would serve as a consultant, but the Angelos  
proposal ultimately accepted by Maryland said Edell would be 
co-lead counsel involved in daily case management and supervision. 
It called him the ``premier tobacco litigation expert in the United 
States,'' the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	As Maryland's suit proceeded, Edell devoted increasing amounts  
of time to depositions and court arguments, his lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, Maryland agreed to accept $4.2 billion as part of  
the national tobacco settlement with major tobacco companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland set attorneys' fees at 12.5 percent, according to the  
Edell lawsuit. That would leave a pot of $525 million to be split 
among the lawyers. The actual amount, however, was to be determined 
by negotiations between the lawyers and the tobacco companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still hoping that Mr. Angelos will do the right thing,  
rather than letting this litigation go forward, because we have 
lived up to all of our obligations to the state of Maryland,'' 
Edell's lawyer, Michel F. Baumeister said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angelos firm's statement maintains Edell ``did not want the  
risk of a contingent fee, particularly in light of the disastrous 
financial consequences of the Cipollone litigation to himself and 
his former firm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point downstream, when he apparently sensed that there  
might be a potential for substantial fees, he sought to participate 
on a contingent basis. This proposal was rejected,'' the statement 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It contends that Edell was only guaranteed $500,000 ``on an  
exceedingly generous hourly rate.'' The Edell lawsuit acknowledges 
that guarantee, but maintains it was based on him having only a 
limited role. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
