<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't. Has Jan. Surplus of $70.3B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government piled up a $70.3 billion  
surplus in January, putting the budget in the black for the first 
four months of fiscal 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists had expected a big surplus because Social Security  
checks for January went out Dec. 31 instead of the usual Jan. 3, 
which fell on a Sunday this year. 
</P>
<P>
	But the actual surplus was even larger than the predicted $55  
billion to $60 billion, and it more than offset monthly deficits in 
October, November and December. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first four months of fiscal 1999, which began Oct. 1,  
the government had a $15.3 billion surplus, compared with a $14.3 
billion deficit during the same period of fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Clinton administration predicted a $79.3 billion  
surplus for all of fiscal 1999, up 13 percent from $70.2 billion in 
1998, which marked the government's first surplus since 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists agreed that the government should be able to expand  
the surplus, if it doesn't disburse it in the form of tax cuts or 
spending increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The robust economy is fueling strong growth in personal income  
tax receipts. They totaled $287.4 billion from October through 
January, up 5.6 percent from 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	That's more than offsetting a 5.2 percent decline in corporate  
tax receipts, to $52.7 billion, reflecting the world economic 
slump's impact on profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
