<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 10:56:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tyson Awaits Hearing After Outburst </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Mike Tyson had been taken off antidepressant drugs two days  
before he became enraged and threw a TV set in a Maryland jail, a 
source close to the boxer told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's daily dose of Zoloft was stopped after he refused to be  
evaluated by a prison physician on grounds he had already been 
examined by a team of psychiatrists, said the source, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The former heavyweight champion was put in an isolation cell at  
the Montgomery County (Md.) Detention Center after the outburst. He 
faces a hearing this week that could lead to loss of privileges but 
will not result in further jail time. 
</P>
<P>
	Corrections officials in Montgomery County are meeting today to  
assess Tyson's medical care, a law enforcement source told the AP, 
speaking on condition of anonymity. The source added that Tyson 
faces disciplinary but not criminal charges stemming from his 
actions at the county jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Russ Hamill, county corrections director, will make the final  
decision. He said Tyson can speak at the hearing but will not be 
represented by a lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	A source familiar with the proceedings said the 32-year-old  
boxer probably will be disciplined for disorderly conduct and 
destruction of county property. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Goldberg, Tyson's regular doctor who heads the  
psychiatric program at Georgetown University, apparently couldn't 
convince prison officials that the fighter should stay on his 
medication. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson had been taking Zoloft on a daily basis for the past four  
months, except for the week prior to his Jan. 16 fight with 
Francois Botha. He was weaned gradually from the drug during that 
week, and began taking it again the day after the fight, said the 
source, who asked not to be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither jail officials nor Goldberg could be reached for  
comment. A call to the home of Tyson's Washington lawyer, Paul 
Kemp, was not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson was in a common area with other prisoners on Friday and  
was talking on the phone when a guard came in and hung up the 
phone, the source close to the fighter said. 
</P>
<P>
	The action enraged Tyson, who picked up the television set and  
threw it against some bars. Tyson, the source said, immediately 
apologized and offered to pay for the TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors at Massachusetts General testified at Tyson's licensing  
hearing before the Nevada Athletic Commission in October that Tyson 
was often depressed, but that his mood swings could be controlled 
if he took the proper medication. 
</P>
<P>
	On the medication, Tyson was cheerful and cooperative in  
interviews with reporters when training for the Botha fight in 
Phoenix in December. The week of the fight, though, he was 
combative at times and engaged in a profanity-laced tirade against 
a New York television reporter four days before the fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson was being held in an 8-by-5-foot isolation cell pending a  
hearing either today or Tuesday on a citation for destruction of 
county property in the jail in the Washington suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson was sentenced Feb. 5 to a one-year jail sentence for  
assaulting two men after a minor traffic accident in August in 
Gaithersburg, Md. Tyson pleaded no contest to the charges, but 
might appeal the sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson's advisers had been hoping he would be put in a prerelease  
program within 60 days of beginning his sentence that would allow 
him to stay in a halfway house and leave during the day for 
training. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident with the television, though, could harm hopes of an  
early release. 
</P>
<P>
	The boxer is also on probation in Indiana for raping a beauty  
pageant contestant in an Indianapolis hotel room in 1991. He served 
three years in prison and was released in March 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana officials say they will wait to see what happens in  
Maryland before deciding whether to revoke his probation. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson stopped Botha in the fifth round of their fight, his first  
since losing his boxing license for biting Evander Holyfield during 
a championship bout in June 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 14:36:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brown's Scoring Surge Sparks Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Heat are so hot that even P.J. Brown is  
scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	This is akin to Tim Hardaway blocking shots or Alonzo Mourning  
running the offense. Brown would rather rebound than score, but 
he'd rather shoot than lose, so lately he's been taking -- and 
making -- wide-open jumpers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Other teams are under the notion that P.J. is not a good  
shooter,'' coach Pat Riley said. ``One of these days they're going 
to learn that you can't leave him open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Miami's victory last Tuesday at Indiana, Brown scored 22  
points. That was the 6-foot-11 power forward's personal best in 
three seasons with the Heat -- until Saturday, when Brown scored 24 
to help beat the Houston Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather have 24 rebounds than 24 points,'' Brown said.  
``Everybody on the team wants me to shoot the ball. I've never been 
a shooter. When your teammates push you, that gives you a lot more 
confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``But tell the fans not to get used to it.''  
</P>
<P>
	Sparked by Brown's scoring surge, the Heat take a five-game  
winning streak into Tuesday's game at Washington. Brown figures 
he'll stop shooting when teams start guarding him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been happening since I got here -- teams want to  
double-team Zo or Tim, and they come off of me. All I try to do is 
take advantage of the opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not doing anything spectacular. I'm just taking a rhythm  
jumper from 15 to 18 feet. I shoot it every day, so I'm going to 
try to put it in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown went 10-for-14 against the Rockets, with most of his  
points uncontested from the perimeter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew he could hit that shot, but not like that on a  
consistent basis,'' Houston's Othella Harrington said. 
</P>
<P>
	During an offseason extended by the NBA lockout, Brown worked on  
his midrange jumper every day, and the practice paid off. He's 
shooting 54 percent this season, compared with 45 percent for his 
career, and he's scoring 12.1 points per game, an improvement from 
his average of 8.8 in five previous seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The Heat's bruising forward is perhaps best known for flipping  
the New York Knicks' Charlie Ward into the stands during the 1997 
playoffs. Even with two starters now sidelined by injuries, the 
Heat depend on Brown for rebounding and defense, not scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley said he'll call a play for Brown perhaps once every five  
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's see, that would mean the next one would be against  
Detroit'' on Friday, Brown said with a smile. ``Yeah, that sounds 
about right.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
