<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Feb. 22, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Albanians Mull Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- American mediators at the Kosovo  
peace talks were not optimistic that there would be an agreement 
before tomorrow's deadline, according to a U.S. official. But chief 
U.S. mediator Christopher Hill remained overnight to oversee 
completion of the proposed text of the accord and to present it to 
the Serbs and ethnic Albanians. U.S. and European mediators have 
pushed the ethnic Albanians to give their final approval to the 
settlement. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has said that 
NATO would not carry out the threatened airstrikes against Serbs 
without Albanian support for the pact. Ethnic Albanians meeting to 
decide whether to accept the self-rule plan. 

</P>
<P>
	Both Sides Rest in Dragging Case  
</P>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- Closing arguments are scheduled to begin  
tomorrow in the capital murder case of John William King, the first 
of three white men to be tried in the dragging death of a black 
man. A pathologist, Dr. Tommy Brown, was the last of 43 prosecution 
witnesses to take the stand. He said James Byrd Jr. was conscious 
when he was dragged along a road by a chain around his ankles until 
his head was torn off by a concrete drainage duct. Prosecutors need 
to prove Byrd was alive when he was dragged in order to prove 
kidnapping and murder, which together would expose the white 
supremacist to the death penalty. The defense rested their case 
this afternoon after calling only three witnesses. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets With Governors  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Washington went back to work today after the  
year-long impeachment fight, with President Clinton meeting with 
the nation's governors to discuss education, tobacco money and 
Internet sales taxes. Republican leaders of the Senate and House 
will get their first chance in 19 months to sit down with the 
president tomorrow. House Majority Leader Dick Armey said 
Republicans would push Clinton for more details on his plans to 
save Social Security and on the possible deployment of U.S. troops 
to Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraqi Missiles Said To Cause Damage  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Iraqi missiles aimed at U.S. and British  
planes flying over the northern no-fly zone have caused some 
civilian damage and hampered U.N. operations, according to a U.N. 
report. The United Nations is concerned that continued aerial 
confrontations could affect food deliveries in northern areas. It 
already has restricted staff movements, the report said. Iraq has 
challenged allied forces in the ``no-fly'' zones almost daily since 
the United States and Britain launched airstrikes in mid-December. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Warns Greece Over Kurd Aid  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey asserted today it has a ``right to  
self-defense'' if Greece provides support to separatist Kurds -- a 
thinly veiled threat of military force against its neighbor and 
rival. The warning came as a Turkish newspaper reported that 
imprisoned rebel warlord Abdullah Ocalan had told interrogators 
that Greece gave his fighters weapons and training, claims that 
Greece has rejected in the past. A judge is expected to file 
charges tomorrow against Ocalan for waging a nearly 15-year 
insurrection in Turkey's southeast. 

</P>
<P>
	Treatment Cuts Cervical Cancer Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A series of studies on cervical cancer has found  
that adding chemotherapy to radiation can cut the risk of death in 
half. Since the 1950s, radiation has been the standard treatment. 
The five-year survival rate for these women is now about 50 
percent. The National Cancer Institute took the unusual step of 
mailing letters to thousands of doctors urging them to adopt the 
new approach immediately. 

</P>
<P>
	AmWest Halts United Merger Talks  
</P>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- America West Holdings Corp. has terminated  
talks on possible buyouts by other carriers, company chairman 
William Franke announced today. UAL Corp., which controls the 
nation's largest airline, United, and America West had been talking 
for several weeks about a deal for the ninth-largest airline. 
Analysts have said a United-America West merger would have faced 
regulatory hurdles. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices rose on Tuesday with the  
Nikkei Stock Average gaining 66.75 points to 14,323.42 in early 
trading. In New York, the Dow industrials climbed 212.73 points to 
9,552.68, 90 points shy of the record 9,643.32. 

</P>
<P>
	Blackhawks Fire Graham As Coach  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Dirk Graham, who was known as a hard-hitting  
forward when he played for the Chicago Blackhawks but who led them 
to their worst record in 42 years as coach, was fired today. 
Assistant coach Lorne Molleken will replace Graham as interim 
coach. The Blackhawks have lost 10 of their last 12 games and are 
19 games under .500. That hasn't happened since 1955-57. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  

</P>
