<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> International Anti-Bribery Pact Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Commerce Secretary William Daley said Monday  
that the Salt Lake City Olympic bribery scandal shows no country is 
immune from bribery, and he called for strong enforcement and 
monitoring of a new international anti-bribery treaty that went 
into effect Feb. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``Corruption affects rich and poor nations, multinational  
corporations and small businesses. We are all in this together,'' 
Daley said at a conference on the role of the private sector in 
fighting corruption in developing countries and emerging economies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Conference on Corruption, held under the auspices  
of the 29-nation Organization for Economic Cooperation and 
Development, brings together 150 high-level government and private 
sector participants from around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Vice President Al Gore will open an 80-nation  
first-of-its-kind conference that will specifically target fighting 
corruption among police, prosecutors, judges, military personnel, 
customs officers, border guards and government budget and 
procurement officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is a positive coming out of Salt Lake City or  
cronyism in Asia,'' Daley said, ``it is that to the cost of bribery 
has been added a political price -- people have lost their 
positions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Salt Lake City Olympic Organizing Committee officials,  
Daley was alluding to the resignation after 32 years in power of 
Indonesian President Suharto last year, which came about, in part, 
because of his family's involvement in controlling the commodity 
import market. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley said the U.S government plans to increase the pressure on  
the World Trade Organization and Latin American and Asian regional 
organizations to adopt strong anti-corruption measures. 
</P>
<P>
	In discussing the OECD's anti-corruption treaty -- now in effect  
for a week -- Daley named France, Belgium, the Netherlands and Italy 
as countries that had signed the accord but not yet ratified it 
though they promised to do by the end of 1998. Those countries 
account for nearly a quarter of OECD exports. 
</P>
<P>
	He said 12 member nations, including the United States, had  
formally adopted the OECD treaty, and that he hoped other members 
would fulfill their commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley also urged private companies to establish codes of  
conduct, set up ethics offices and train employees to watch out for 
bribes and report them to these offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
