<DOCNO> APW19990222.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:35:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Securitas To Acquire Pinkerton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. (AP) -- Pinkerton Inc., the legendary  
American detective agency that guarded Abraham Lincoln, chased 
Jesse James and gave rise to the term ``private eye,'' is being 
bought by a Swedish security company. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal with Securitas AB would create a global company with  
$3.5 billion in annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Securitas agreed Monday to pay $384 million for Pinkerton, which  
will keep its name, management and worldwide staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not losing an icon. Pinkerton will remain Pinkerton.  
We're just trading shareholders,'' said Denis R. Brown, Pinkerton's 
president and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined companies would have about 5 percent of the  
worldwide security market and 114,000 employees in more than 30 
countries in Europe, North and South America, and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger reflects the need of both companies to expand their  
international reach, Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinkerton will rely on Securitas to serve its clients throughout  
much of Europe, where Pinkerton is weak. Pinkerton, in return, 
gives Securitas access to the North American and South American 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, it looks like they will be a major global presence in  
this business, and frankly, I think Securitas is getting it at a 
very reasonable price,'' said Steve Percoco, an analyst with Lark 
Research. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinkerton's profits have been weak and it has been revamping  
some of its businesses in response. On Monday it said 
fourth-quarter profits were off 35 percent to $4.3 million, or 35 
cents per share, from $6.6 million, or 50 cents per share, a year 
ago. For the year, Pinkerton lost $463,000, or 4 cents per share, 
compared to earnings of $14.7 million or $1.12 per share in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinkerton was founded in 1850 by Allan Pinkerton, a barrel maker  
who turned detective after helping authorities capture a band of 
counterfeiters operating near his business in Dundee, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinkerton himself won fame as Lincoln's protector in the early  
days of the Civil War. The company wasn't working with Lincoln when 
he was assassinated in 1865. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinkerton agents were hired by banks and railroads to track down  
robbers and swindlers. Pinkerton agents chased the James and 
Younger Brothers gangs across the South and Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	During the Wild West years, Pinkerton gents were credited with  
killing or capturing most members of the Wild Bunch. The gang's 
leaders, Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid, escaped capture by 
fleeing to South America. 
</P>
<P>
	During the late 19th century, Pinkerton agents infiltrated  
unions and attempted to disrupt strikes and organizing activities. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the best-known cases, testimony from Pinkerton agents  
helped convict 19 coal miners who belonged to the terrorist group 
known as the Mollie Maguires. The miners were found guilty of 
crimes committed during a bitter strike and were hanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pinkerton logo, a large eye with the words ``We Never  
Sleep'' under it, is said to have given rise to the term ``private 
eye.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nowadays, Pinkerton employees range from uniformed security  
guards to computer experts who protect corporate databases and 
other intellectual property. Clients include 80 percent of the 
companies in the Fortune 1000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say there's nothing in the area of security that we're  
not involved in somewhere in the world,'' Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	On news of the merger, Pinkerton stock jumped $11.68 3/4, or 69  
percent to $28.56 1/4 on the New York Stock Exchange. Securitas agreed 
to pay $29 for each Pinkerton share. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition has been approved by the boards of both  
companies, but it still must undergo regulatory scrutiny. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Sides With FCC Over Bells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court lifted a court order Monday  
that had limited the Federal Communication Commission's authority 
over local Bell telephone companies' efforts to provide 
long-distance service. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court's action further strengthens the FCC's ability to  
open the $110 billion local phone market to competition, and is 
considered another defeat for the nation's five Bell telephone 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, the Supreme Court, without comment, vacated the  
8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals' order forbidding the FCC from 
requiring local Bell telephone companies to open their networks to 
competitors at certain prices, as a prerequisite for entering the 
long-distance market. 
</P>
<P>
	No Baby Bell has won FCC clearance to offer long-distance  
service in its local phone market. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices ordered the appeals court in St. Louis to  
reconsider its 1998 ruling in light of another recent Supreme Court 
decision upholding the FCC's authority to oversee such pricing. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the high court said a 1996 law gives the FCC the  
power to set pricing guidelines for long-distance companies and 
other potential competitors to connect with local phone companies' 
networks. Rivals need to do this to offer competing local service. 
That Supreme Court decision was a loss for the Bell companies and 
GTE and a win for the FCC and long-distance carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	That ruling overturned a 1997 decision by the St. Louis court  
that said states -- not the FCC -- had that power. 
</P>
<P>
	GTE and the Bell telephone companies are now challenging the  
substance of the FCC's price rules, which the high court did not 
address in its Jan. 25 order, at the St. Louis court. The court 
will determine whether the FCC's price rules are consistent with 
the 1996 law. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to state telephone regulators meeting in Washington,  
Solomon Trujillo, president of Bell company US West, again urged 
Congress to rewrite a provision of a 1996 law that would permit the 
Bell companies to provide long-distance service at a specific date 
in the future. He didn't recommend what that date should be. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rockies Comfortable With New Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Golf clubs are allowed on the baggage  
carousel and Armani suits are not required on road trips. Welcome 
to the new rules under Colorado Rockies manager Jim Leyland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I normally don't have too many rules,'' Leyland said. ``The  
more you've got, the more you break.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In six years under manager Don Baylor, coats and ties were  
mandatory on Colorado's charter plane. Golfing was allowed on the 
road but golf clubs were not. Spring workouts started by 
mid-morning and finished well after lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, the Rockies are able to schedule afternoon tee times  
at posh resort courses because they are typically finished by noon 
following 2 1/2-hour workouts efficiently coordinated by third-base 
coach Rich Donnelly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody just feels comfortable,'' said infielder  
Kurt Abbott, who played for Leyland when the Florida Marlins won 
the World Series in 1997. ``Everybody knows what they have to do. 
It's about baseball, about doing things right. It's not about 
having to dress up or looking good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While some players trade their three-piece suits for polo shirts  
from the Greg Norman collection, don't expect the Rockies to show 
up at a New York hotel looking like a leftover from a Pearl Jam 
concert. 
</P>
<P>
	In giving his players some leeway, Leyland is trusting they will  
police themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be neat,'' he said. ``I basically let the players  
make the rule. You can wear a nice pair of jeans, but if guys start 
wearing jeans with holes in them, we can wear a suit and tie. We 
can wear tuxedos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under Baylor, the Rockies were allowed to have mustaches and a  
well-kept goatee. That policy will not change. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want my team to act like professionals and I want them to be  
disciplined, but I don't believe telling a grown man he can't have 
a mustache is a form of discipline,'' Leyland said. 
</P>
<P>
	The longer leash can be attributed to Leyland's resume, which  
includes 13 years as a major league manager, a World Series ring 
and three straight NL East pennants with the Pittsburgh Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Rockies were born in 1993, everything was a learning  
experience, and the owners had more input into the team rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of like with a family,'' Rockies owner Jerry  
McMorris said. ``It's always easier to loosen the reins than 
tighten the reins. ... We're changing with the times and the new 
manager.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Leyland's standards stem from common sense. The shorter  
workouts prevent players from getting bored shagging fly balls, and 
the dress code keeps them comfortable on cross-country charter 
flights that sometimes land at 3 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who's going to see us?'' relief pitcher Chuck McElroy said.  
``You don't want to spill soda or anything on an $1,100 suit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules are sure to be a hit with Colorado's more  
flamboyant personalities such as outfielder Dante Bichette -- who 
showed up with his hair dyed black and Elvis sideburns last season 
-- and relief pitcher Curtis Leskanic. 
</P>
<P>
	``He might have to have a dress code with me,'' Leskanic said,  
``otherwise I'll show up looking like I'm playing in the New York 
Penal League. Seriously though, it's just a matter of not doing 
anything stupid.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 16:13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Today In History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Today is Tuesday, Feb. 23, the 54nd day of 1999. There are 311  
days left in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Highlight in History:  
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 23, 1945, U.S. Marines on Iwo Jima captured Mount  
Suribachi, where they raised the American flag. 
</P>
<P>
	On this date:  
</P>
<P>
	In 1822, Boston was granted a charter to incorporate as a city.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1836, the siege of the Alamo began in San Antonio, Texas.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1847, U.S. troops under Gen. Zachary Taylor defeated Mexican  
Gen. Santa Anna at the Battle of Buena Vista in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1848, the sixth president of the United States, John Quincy  
Adams, died of a stroke at age 80. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1861, President-elect Lincoln arrived secretly in Washington  
to take office after an assassination plot was foiled in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1870, Mississippi was re-admitted to the Union.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1905, the Rotary Club was founded.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1927, President Coolidge signed a bill creating the Federal  
Radio Commission, forerunner of the Federal Communications 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1954, the first mass inoculation of children against polio  
with the Salk vaccine began in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1965, Stan Laurel, the ``skinny'' half of the Laurel and  
Hardy comedy team, died in Santa Monica, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, scientists in Scotland announced they had succeeded in  
cloning an adult mammal, producing a lamb named ``Dolly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years ago: The Senate Armed Services Committee voted against  
recommending the nomination of John Tower to become secretary of 
defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Military chiefs of Bosnia's Muslim-led  
government and their second-strongest foes, Bosnia's Croats, signed 
a truce. Russia's new parliament took a swipe at President Boris 
Yeltsin by granting amnesty to leaders of the 1991 Soviet coup and 
the hard-liners who'd fought him in 1993. Nancy Kerrigan led the 
women's figure skating short program at the Winter Olympics in 
Norway, while Tonya Harding placed tenth. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: Forty-two people were killed, some 2,600 homes and  
businesses damaged or destroyed, by tornadoes in central Florida. 
President Clinton gave cautious approval to a U.N. agreement 
reached by Secretary-General Kofi Annan with Saddam Hussein for 
monitoring suspected weapons sites in Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Birthdays: Actor Peter Fonda is 59. Singer-musician  
Johnny Winter is 55. South African activist Allan Boesak is 54. 
Country-rock musician Rusty Young is 53. Actress Patricia 
Richardson (``Home Improvement'') is 48. Rock musician Brad 
Whitford (Aerosmith) is 47. Singer Howard Jones is 44. Rock 
musician Michael Wilton (Queensryche) is 37. Tennis player Helena 
Sukova is 34. Rock musician Jeff Beres (Sister Hazel) is 28. Rock 
musician Lasse Johansson (The Cardigans) is 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Thought for Today: ``Loving a child doesn't mean giving in to  
all his whims; to love him is to bring out the best in him, to 
teach him to love what is difficult.'' -- Nadia Boulanger, French 
composer and teacher (1887-1979). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
