<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merger of Shipbuilders Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The proposed merger between the Navy  
shipbuilders Newport News Shipbuilding and Avondale Industries Inc. 
has received anti-trust clearance from the U.S. Justice Department, 
but the future of the deal remains uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	Other federal officials still must OK the merger. Also, General  
Dynamics' recent proposal to acquire Newport News could still 
scuttle the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale said in a brief statement Monday that the Justice  
Department had determined the merger would not violate federal 
anti-trust law. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger would create a company with estimated 1999 revenues  
of $2.6 billion. The company would be capable of building any 
warship in the Navy's fleet, from behemoth nuclear-powered aircraft 
carriers to fast-moving amphibious landers. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger still must be approved by the stockholders of both  
companies and the Maritime Administration of the U.S. Department of 
Transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Pentagon signed off on the deal between  
Virginia-based Newport News and New Orleans-based Avondale. The 
Defense Department said the merger ``would not an adverse impact on 
competition to build and repair Navy ships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was unrelated to General Dynamics' proposed  
$1.36 billion cash takeover of Newport News. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News has said that General Dynamics' proposal required  
careful review of potential antitrust problems in the rapidly 
consolidating defense industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Department said Friday it is evaluating the proposed  
General Dynamics-Newport News merger. The Pentagon has said it 
supports mergers that reduce excess capacity or lower costs while 
sustaining competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avondale-Newport News deal would reduce the Navy's pool of  
primary contractors for ships to three: the new company; General 
Dynamics, which owns Electric Boat, Bath Iron Works, and National 
Steel and Shipbuilding Co.; and Litton Industries, parent of 
Ingalls Shipbuilding. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News Shipbuilding builds all the Navy's aircraft  
carriers and many of its submarines, and it repairs and performs 
maintenance on various types of Navy ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale designs, builds and overhauls Navy surface ships as  
well as commercial vessels. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
