<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Times Buying TheStreet.com Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Times Co. is buying a minority  
stake in TheStreet.com, a popular financial news Web site, for $15 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, announced Monday, will give the publisher a stake in  
one of the Internet's hottest areas as a growing number of 
investors flock to the Web for financial news and investment 
advice. 
</P>
<P>
	TheStreet.com was co-founded in 1996 by James J. Cramer, a  
well-known money manager who writes a daily column for the site and 
also appears regularly as a commentator on the CNBC cable business 
news network. 
</P>
<P>
	TheStreet.com currently has about 37,000 paid subscribers.  
</P>
<P>
	The Times Co. is buying the undisclosed stake strictly as an  
investment and will not be contributing any news to the site. The 
purchase will be made with a combination of cash and services, but 
those services have yet to be determined, said spokeswoman Lisa 
Carparelli. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal, The Times Co.'s vice chairman, Michael  
Golden, will become a member of TheStreet.com's board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to its flagship newspaper, The New York Times Co.  
publishes The Boston Globe, 21 regional newspapers and three 
magazines. It also operates eight television and two radio 
stations, and has several Internet-related investments. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
