<HEADLINE> Mets Co-Owner Tours Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- Nelson Doubleday was so excited  
about the prospects for the New York Mets that he decided to take a 
look for himself. 
</P>
<P>
	The 65-year-old co-owner of the Mets toured the club's complex  
Monday with general manager Steve Phillips while the team went 
through a three-hour workout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the chemistry is there,'' Doubleday said. ``I think  
you saw it at the end of last year, I think you saw it when Mike 
(Piazza) showed up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taking time out from his stroll, Doubleday spent several minutes  
talking with fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a very interesting spring,'' he said. ``We've  
got Steve (Phillips) and that's a very important thing, you can see 
what he's put together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Shea Stadium is going to be fun this season,'' Doubleday said.  
``Hopefully, we'll see some games that are 9-2 in our favor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doubleday reported that 100,000 seats were sold at Shea Stadium  
on first day tickets went on sale, a substantial increase from the 
22,000 bought on the same day last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Doubleday also shared the story about receiving a gift from a  
friend consisting of two belts with wording stitched into them. The 
matching pair of belts are for Doubleday and his wife to wear to 
Shea Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``One says, `Hey sweetheart, what are we doing tonight?'''  
Doubleday said. ``The other one says, `We're going to see Mike 
Piazza hit.''' 
</P>
