<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sempra Energy Is Buying KN Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- Sempra Energy is buying the natural gas  
pipeline operator KN Energy Inc. for about $1.8 billion in cash and 
stock in a deal that would extend the rapid expansion of the 
California-based energy concern. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company under the deal announced Sunday would  
retain the name Sempra Energy and continue to be based in San 
Diego. It would have revenue of about $9.9 billion annually and 
more than 15,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra was formed last June with the merger of Los Angeles-based  
Pacific Enterprises and San Diego based Enova Corp. Sempra said it 
has 21 million customers among its eight subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	KN Energy, based in Lakewood, has $9 billion in assets in 16  
states, including natural gas pipelines, more than 30 gas 
processing plants, 25 storage facilities and more than 200,000 
residential customers in addition to business customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal needs approval by both state and federal regulators and  
both companies' shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Between 200 and 300 jobs would be eliminated, with most  
reductions in headquarters and staff positions at both companies, 
said Richard Farman, Sempra's chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	KN Energy employs about 3,300 people. Sempra has 12,000  
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the agreement, Sempra will offer 1.115 shares of  
its common stock for each share of KN Energy stock, or $25 in cash 
for each share. KN Energy has about 70 million shares outstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra would also assume more than $4 billion in KN Energy debt  
as part of the deal, pushing its total value to about $6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	KN Energy picked up a high debt load last year with the $3.5  
billion purchase of MidCon Corp. pipeline company. Reduced demand 
for natural gas with the warm winter sent KN stock to a 52-week low 
earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said Farman will remain as chairman and CEO of the  
combined company. KN Energy CEO Larry Hall will join Sempra's board 
of directors. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
