<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Ruling Party Leads Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHETUMAL, Mexico (AP) -- Mexico's ruling party appeared it would  
beat back a stiff challenge by opposition parties in a race for the 
governorship of the Caribbean coast state of Quintana Roo. 
</P>
<P>
	With 12.68 percent of the vote counted late Sunday, the  
Institutional Revolutionary Party's candidate, Joaquin Hendricks, 
had 40.93 percent of the vote. Gaston Alegre of the leftist 
Democratic Revolutionary Party had 31.8 percent, and a pro-business 
party, National Action, had 23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Democratic Revolution held out hope it could win,  
Hendricks proclaimed victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have won cleanly,'' he told a cheering crowd of supporters  
in Chetumal, the state capital. ``I'm going to govern for everyone 
... with honesty and commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintana Roo, where wealthy tourist resorts like Cancun are  
located near dirt-poor Maya Indian communities, was seen as a test 
of the ruling party's ability to convince voters it can narrow the 
income gap and overcome the image of corruption and 
authoritarianism that dogs current Gov. Mario Villanueva. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need a change. The worst thing that could happen is for  
things to go on the same way,'' said Manuel Peraza, a businessman 
in Chetumal. 
</P>
<P>
	Early results were not available Sunday for another race, the  
governor election in Hidalgo state. The ruling party, known as the 
PRI, had expected to easily retain control of the central plains 
state. The race between Hendricks, a former army officer, and 
Alegre had been much closer, according to pre-election polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Alegre had pledged more protection for workers and the state's  
fragile environment, while Hendricks wants to develop agribusiness 
to keep poor farmers from flocking to slums surrounding the 
resorts. 
</P>
<P>
	The PRI has governed Quintana Roo since it was admitted as a  
state in 1974. At the federal level, the party has held the 
presidency without interruption since 1929 and would like to 
maintain its strength for the 2000 presidential vote. Earlier this 
month, it won the governorship of Guerrero state but lost in Baja 
California Sur. 
</P>
<P>
	The party faces serious problems in Quintana Roo.  
</P>
<P>
	Two days before Sunday's vote, federal prosecutors announced 38  
arrest warrants for former Quintana Roo state officials and 
businessmen linked to the cocaine-trafficking Juarez cartel. 
</P>
<P>
	Many believe the U.S. government would like to see Villanueva  
prosecuted for alleged links to drug traffickers. Villanueva, who 
maintains his innocence, has won a court order allowing him to see 
evidence in a Mexican investigation against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the PRI's big challenge was coming in places like the  
largely Indian town of Felipe Carrillo Puerto, where farmworkers 
earn about $1.70 per day, well below the national minimum wage of 
$3.45 a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Hermino Cab was one voter who said he supported Democratic  
Revolution ``because the PRI never does anything for us. We don't 
have irrigation, we don't have tractors ... the hospital won't take 
care of us, and sometimes our children die.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
