<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Movies Were Siskel's First Love </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Writing for rival newspapers, the young Gene  
Siskel and Roger Ebert were fierce competitors, always trying to 
out-scoop each other. 
</P>
<P>
	The icy relationship warmed -- after time -- when they reluctantly  
teamed up to co-host a public television program called ``Sneak 
Previews'' in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first five years that we knew each other, Gene Siskel  
and I hardly spoke. Then it seemed like we never stopped,'' Ebert 
wrote in a column titled ``Farewell, my friend'' on the front page 
of Sunday's Chicago Sun-Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Siskel, 53, a married father of three, died in a hospital in  
suburban Evanston on Saturday surrounded by his family. The death 
of the Chicago Tribune critic ended a quiet but strenuous battle 
against complications that arose after a growth was removed from 
his brain in May 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't even imagine what it will be like (without Siskel),''  
Ebert said Saturday. ``There was a history there, a respect that 
I'm never really going to replace in my life. It's going to be 
tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The public television show that the pair hosted became so  
popular it was syndicated nationwide and later renamed ``Siskel &AMP; 
Ebert.'' With their trademarked ``thumbs up, thumbs down'' reviews, 
the program became a powerhouse in the film industry. A ``thumbs 
up'' could give a film a boost, while a ``thumbs down'' could sink 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two thumbs up has become an icon in the film industry,''  
said Paul Dergarabedian, a spokesman for Exhibitor Relations Co. 
which compiles box office receipts. ``The average person would look 
toward them about whether to take their hard-earned dollars to the 
box office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The show will continue on with Ebert and revolving guest  
critics. 
</P>
<P>
	Siskel's love affair with movies started when he was a child  
living on Chicago's North Side. As an orphan schoolboy, he'd walk 
eight blocks to his neighborhood theater to catch a Saturday 
matinee with his friends. There, surrounded by red velvet, his 
lifetime love of movies began. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of his death, Siskel had taken a leave of absence  
from his work not only with ``Siskel &AMP; Ebert'' and the Chicago 
Tribune, but also as a film critic for ``CBS This Morning'' and 
WBBM-TV, and as a columnist for TV Guide. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sunday's column, Ebert recalled how Siskel strove to deflect  
attention away from his illness and toward his film criticism after 
his surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although it was obvious sometimes that he walked slowly and  
was in pain, I never once heard him complain. He carried on with a 
bravery that is hard to imagine,'' Ebert wrote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
