<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Babbitt To Name Everglades Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, reacting to  
criticism from some leading scientists, on Monday announced the 
creation of an independent advisory panel to help guide the 
government's $8 billion restoration plan for the Florida 
Everglades. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sheer scale of this restoration demands that we take full  
advantage of the range of talent our nation has to offer,'' Babbitt 
said in a statement after meeting with three of the scientists who 
have been critical of the project. 
</P>
<P>
	Six leading ecologists in a letter to Babbitt last month had  
complained that the ambitious Everglades restoration does not go 
far enough. They said it should be subject to closer scrutiny by 
independent scientists who have not been involved in developing the 
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt met Monday with three of the scientists -- Stuart Pimm,  
an ecologist at the University of Tennessee, Gordon Orians of the 
University of Washington, and Peter Raven, director of the Missouri 
Botanical Gardens -- to discuss ways to involve independent 
scientists in the project. 
</P>
<P>
	After the meeting, the Interior Department issued a statement  
saying that Babbitt had agreed to creation of the independent 
scientific panel that would advise on implementation of the 
Everglades restoration program. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, whose members would be appointed by Babbitt and  
represent a broad range of expertise, will provide ``independent 
scientific advice ... to help ensure the success'' of the long-term 
restoration programs, according to a draft proposal agreed to by 
the scientists. 
</P>
<P>
	Pimm said the scientists felt an independent group of advisers  
were needed to monitor the Everglades project. ``This review panel 
provides it and we are absolutely delighted,'' said Pimm after the 
meeting with Babbitt. 
</P>
<P>
	The other scientists who raised concerns in the Jan. 28 letter  
were Paul Ehrlich an ecologist at Stanford University, Edward O. 
Wilson, a Harvard University biologist, and Gary Meffe, a 
conservation biologist at the University of Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration unveiled the $8 billion Everglades plan last  
October, saying it's aim is to restore one of America's ecological 
wonders by returning the natural water flows that long ago were 
disrupted by a series of government built dams, levies and canals. 
</P>
<P>
	Developed by the Army Corps of Engineers, the plan calls for  
building a comprehensive network of water storage systems to 
provide flood protection, preserve water for agriculture and 
residents and also protect the area's marshlands. 
</P>
<P>
	The project must still be reviewed in a series of public  
hearings and much of it is subject to approval by Congress which 
must come up with half of the money. The other half is financed by 
state and local governments. 
</P>
<P>
	While piecemeal efforts to revitalize the Everglades have been  
under way for years, the long-range recovery plan represents the 
most ambitious attempt yet to rescue the unique ecosystem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 17:23:16 </DATE_TIME>
