<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux To Meet With Marino Lawyer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Former Pittsburgh Penguins star Mario Lemieux,  
who is working on a proposal to take over the bankrupt franchise, 
will meet Tuesday with team co-owner Roger Marino's lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	The session is not expected to cover the competing bids by  
Lemieux and Marino to reorganize the team's finances, but rather 
the $26.2 million in deferred compensation owed Lemieux. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux is chairman of the committee representing the team's  
unsecured creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino also plans to submit a reorganization plan to U.S.  
Bankruptcy Court, even though he has lost nearly $40 million 
operating the club the last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Baldwin, the Penguins' primary owner from 1991-97 and  
still a co-owner, also seeking to reorganize the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry L. Manion III, Marino's lawyer, originally planned to hold  
a joint meeting of the team's creditors but decided to change that 
to individual meetings. Marino, who has feuded publicly with 
Lemieux, will not attend the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Any concessions that Manion can derive from the meetings would  
be part of the reorganization plan he will submit to U.S. 
Bankruptcy Court Judge Bernard Markovitz next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, who is trying to raise at least $40 million from  
investors, also expects to submit his plan next month. He is 
willing to exchange some of the millions he is owed for equity in 
the team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
