<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke Tops Men's Basketball Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Texas was in chaos less than a year ago. The  
season had a dismal ending with two players leaving for other 
schools, the head coach resigning and a record that set the 
Longhorns near the bottom of the Big 12. 
</P>
<P>
	This season was not expected to be much better, but new coach  
Rick Barnes has turned Texas around. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being one win away from clinching the top seed in  
the conference tournament, the Longhorns (17-10, 12-2) have moved 
into the AP college basketball rankings for the first time this 
season at No. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't gawk about it. It was the farthest thing from our  
mind,'' Barnes said Monday after practice. ``But I'm happy for our 
players. I think they worked hard for it, but all we're concerned 
about right now is finding a way to keep winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a slow start, Texas has won eight of its last nine games  
and holds a two-game lead over Big 12 rivals Oklahoma and Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	At the top of the poll is Duke, winner of 22 straight games and  
one victory shy of Atlantic Coast Conference history. The Blue 
Devils (27-1) were first on 70 ballots and received 1,774 points 
from the media panel. 
</P>
<P>
	A victory Saturday night at North Carolina would give Duke,  
which beat Florida State by 26 points and Clemson by 27 last week, 
the first 16-0 regular season in the ACC. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn (25-1), which beat Vanderbilt in its only game last week,  
moved up one place to No. 2 with 1,685 points. The ranking matches 
the highest in school history, a one-week stay at No. 2 in February 
1959. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State (25-4), which won the Big Ten regular-season  
title Sunday with a 56-51 victory over Wisconsin, also moved up one 
place and received the other No. 1 vote and 1,617 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut (23-2), which lost to Miami 73-71 on Saturday,  
dropped from second to fourth, the first time this season the 
Huskies haven't been ranked either No. 1 or 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland held No. 5 and was followed by Stanford, Arizona, St.  
John's, Cincinnati and Ohio State. 
</P>
<P>
	The Second Ten was Miami, Utah, Kentucky, North Carolina, UCLA,  
Wisconsin, College of Charleston, Iowa, Florida and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	The last five teams in the Top 25 were New Mexico, Texas,  
Purdue, Syracuse and Temple, with the last two tied for 24th. 
</P>
<P>
	Temple (18-8) was No. 7 in the preseason poll, but fell out of  
the rankings four weeks into regular season after losing four 
straight games. The Owls returned to the rankings after winning 
five of six. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri (18-7) and Miami of Ohio (19-6) both lost two games  
last week to fall out of the poll after returning for one week. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky, which beat Georgia and lost to Arkansas, had the  
week's biggest drop falling from No. 6 to 13th and out of the Top 
Ten for the first time this season. Purdue, which was the third 
ranked team to lose two games last week, fell from 17th to No. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	The week's biggest jumps were the moves of Miami from 15th to  
No. 11 and Florida from 23rd to No. 19, the highest rankings for 
both this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
