<HEADLINE> Wilson Will Not Seek Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	After meeting with advisers, checking his bank account and  
considering his chances, former Gov. Pete Wilson has decided not to 
run for president -- for a second time. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson determined that he could not raise the $20 million to $25  
million that he believed was necessary to run a credible campaign 
for the Republican nomination, according to a veteran Wilson 
strategist who spoke to The Associated Press on the condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've reluctantly reached the conclusion that it's just not  
practical to pursue the nomination,'' Wilson told the Los Angeles 
Times, which reported the decision in today's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Michelle Hart, spokeswoman for Citizens for California's Future,  
a Wilson organization, declined comment Sunday night and said the 
group would release a statement today. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-term governor and two-term U.S. Senator concluded that  
Texas Gov. George W. Bush had gained so much momentum a year before 
the first primary that his early lead in several key polls was 
insurmountable. Bush has not announced whether he will run for 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, who moved from Sacramento to Century City after leaving  
office last month, plans to inform supporters of his decision 
today, the source said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson told Los Angeles Times columnist George Skelton that he  
decided last Wednesday that it would be senseless for him to run 
for president. ``I don't pretend I'm not disappointed,'' Wilson 
said. ``But life goes on and there's much to do and much to enjoy 
and I intend to do both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former governor has not decided whom he will endorse in the  
presidential race, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson abandoned his last presidential run after one month in  
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Recovery from throat surgery hampered the start of that  
presidential campaign, making him one of the last aspirants to 
officially announce his candidacy. He also was haunted by his own 
pledge made during his 1994 re-election campaign that he would not 
seek higher office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
