<DOCNO> APW19990222.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 10:37:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Simon To Brand Name Malls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Millions of consumers flock to malls each year,  
but few have a clue who actually operates these shopping meccas. 
</P>
<P>
	That might change as Simon Property Group, the nation's biggest  
mall owner, launches a branding campaign that will thrust its name 
into the public eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Simon, which is expected to announce the initiative today, says  
the campaign will differentiate its properties from the competition 
by connecting its 145 malls under one name and guaranteeing 
superior levels of service to the consumer. 
</P>
<P>
	Retailers, meantime, will benefit from national advertising and  
other programs that Simon will use to promote its name and its 
malls. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to drive both consumer loyalty and tenant loyalty,''  
said Jonathan Litt, a real estate analyst at PaineWebber. ``As 
opposed to going to a no-name mall where you don't know what you 
will get, they want you to see the Simon name and know what kind of 
experience it will be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simon's new campaign comes as malls fight for shoppers in the  
fiercely competitive and crowded retail marketplace. While 
consumers have long been loyal to certain stores, most haven't had 
the same attachment to any given mall and base where they shop on 
price and convenience. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent study by the Atlanta-based consulting firm Kurt Salmon  
Associates reported consumers cut back shopping trips to large 
indoor malls by 12 percent last year, while they shopped 21 percent 
more at local stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts question whether mall-owner branding has any real  
value. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless you change what is under the roof, just sticking the  
name on the door won't make a difference,'' said Wendy Liebmann, 
president of the retail consulting firm WSL Strategic Retail. 
</P>
<P>
	But Simon says its initiative will give shoppers reasons to come  
to their malls. One is Simon's pledge to aggressively tackle issues 
like customer service and safety, a regular consumer complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	They also will nationalize their MALLPeRKS program. Shoppers  
receive a point for every $1 spent at any store in any Simon mall, 
and they then get a selection of rewards to redeem -- like discounts 
or gift certificates to retailers -- based on the number of points 
they attain. 
</P>
<P>
	Simon also sees the branding program as a way to attract more  
outside marketers to use its malls to reach millions of people. 
More than 2.3 billion visitors come to Simon's properties each 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	PepsiCo, for instance, has the exclusive rights to sell drinks  
at vending machines in Simon malls. Last week, Simon partnered with 
Time Inc. to create S magazine that will be distributed at all 
Simon malls. It will include mall-specific events, like promotions 
and special events, as well as advertisements from tenants. The 
articles will come from Time Inc.'s magazines, including Money, 
InStyle and Sports Illustrated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Blackhawks Fire Graham as Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Dirk Graham, who was known as a hard-hitting  
forward when he played for the Chicago Blackhawks but who led them 
to their worst record in 42 years as coach, was fired Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant coach Lorne Molleken will replace Graham as interim  
coach, the team announced. Denis Savard will stay on as assistant 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham, just 59 games into his first season as coach, will  
remain with the Blackhawks organization, general manager Bob Murray 
said. However, Murray said a decision hasn't been made on Graham's 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	Molleken called his appointment as interim coach a sad moment  
for him, adding that Graham is a close friend. But he vowed to do 
things differently than the man he replaced. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be more structure, more discipline,'' Molleken  
said. ``Team play has been horrendous. That is what we will focus 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Murray said he wanted to see signs of things getting better with  
the Blackhawks. But with 23 games remaining, the team remained at 
the bottom of the Western Conference with the second-worst record 
in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to start getting ready for next season,'' Murray  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham had little coaching experience when he was hired by the  
Blackhawks last June. He had spent just one season, 1995-96, as an 
assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the time of Graham's appointment, Murray insisted that  
Graham's demeanor in the locker room as a player and captain of the 
Blackhawks was what mattered. In announcing Graham's firing, Murray 
admitted to his mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've learned to never put a person in the position we put  
Dirk,'' Murray said. ``We set him up to fail. You have to have some 
experience to do this job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham was known for motivating his teammates when he played for  
the Blackhawks from 1988 to 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	However, this year's team has shown little motivation under  
Graham. The Blackhawks have lost 10 of their last 12 games and are 
19 games under .500. That hasn't happened since 1955-57, when the 
Blackhawks finished 23 games under .500. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham also made news for his conflicts with players.  
</P>
<P>
	During a recent practice, Graham and right wing Tony Amonte got  
into an expletive-laced argument as the coach denounced the 
Blackhawks' star for turning over the puck. He later said Amonte 
and the rest of the first unit should be demoted to the second unit 
because they weren't doing their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their disagreement, Amonte said it was unfortunate  
Graham was losing his job. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had the respect of the players,'' he said. ``The players  
listened to him. (But) everyone sees the game differently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A tough and aggressive player, Graham won the 1991 Frank Selke  
award for his defensive skills. 
</P>
<P>
	He had 152 goals, 190 assists and 685 penalty minutes in 546  
games for Chicago. He also holds the team record for most 
shorthanded goals in a season, 10 in 1988-89. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham was captain for 6 1/2 seasons and part of the 1992 squad  
that won 11 straight playoff games before losing to Pittsburgh in 
the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	As coach, he replaced Craig Hartsburg, who was fired in April  
after Chicago's 30-39-13 season, when they failed to make the 
playoffs for the first time since 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	Molleken, 42, came to the Blackhawks last June from the Edmonton  
Oilers, where he was head coach of two minor league affiliates. He 
previously coached the Saskatoon Blades of the Western Hockey 
League and was a coach in the Saskatchewan Junior Hockey League. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blackhawks also announced the appointment of defenseman  
Trent Yawney as an assistant coach. Yawney, 33, a 12-year veteran 
of the NHL, broke his arm in a game at Nashville and is out for the 
year. He said Monday he is ``hanging up the blades.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vizquel Shows Up to Indians Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINTER HAVEN, Fla. (AP) -- He never asked for a trade. He never  
said he wouldn't report to training camp. He's a happy camper. 
Let's play ball. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the message from Omar Vizquel on Monday as he arrived  
at the Cleveland Indians training camp following an offseason in 
which the six-time Gold Glove shortstop had voiced unhappiness with 
his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ready to put all that behind me,'' Vizquel said. ``Nobody  
put a gun to my head to sign the contract. My situation is good 
here. I want to be a Cleveland Indian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This winter, Vizquel lobbied the Tribe front office for an  
extension of the contract he signed after the 1995 season. The deal 
has three years remaining at $3 million per year, plus a $3 million 
option for 2002. But Indians officials refused. 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel had said asking for a trade or refusing to report to  
training camp were both options. In the end, he reported to camp on 
time and said Monday he is willing to live with the terms of the 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel said his situation, which has been the talk of Cleveland  
fans during in an offseason in which the Indians signed Gold Glove 
second baseman Roberto Alomar, ``was blown out of proportion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As an employee of the Cleveland Indians, I have the right to  
go in and ask (general manager) John Hart about my contract. I did 
that,'' Vizquel said. ``I walked into his office friendly and I 
walked out friendly. We couldn't find an answer to it now, so for 
now the talks are done. I am not going to talk about it anymore 
this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart left the door open for future discussions with Vizquel.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a closed issue,'' Hart said. ``We'd like Omar to  
retire as a Cleveland Indian. It's his right to ask for more years 
in his contract, but that doesn't mean we have to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel said he was not asking for a renegotiation.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't trying to change the deal. I just wanted to add some  
years to it,'' he said. ``It was not a renegotiation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indians catcher Sandy Alomar has said Vizquel should honor the  
contract, and that if Indians officials renegotiated, it would open 
the door for other players to seek new deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel and Alomar met with manager Mike Hargrove on Monday to  
defuse any potential hard feelings between the two players. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is straight between us,'' Vizquel said. ``I've been  
good friends with Sandy for a long time, but the last thing you 
want to hear from a friend is him saying something that was not a 
benefit to you. My situation was none of Sandy's business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alomar also said he and Vizquel have cleared the air between  
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have nothing against Omar,'' Alomar said. ``If he was  
offended by my comments, I apologize. I am not upset with him, and 
I don't think he is upset with me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 20:13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
