<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Unemployment Holds Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Unemployment held steady at a record 5.8  
percent in the three months ending in January, the government said 
Monday in a report that offered up a gloomy outlook for the Chinese 
New Year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Census and Statistics Department said 202,000 people were  
out of work in the November-January period, compared with 201,200 
in October-December. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Wong, the secretary for education and manpower, warned  
there were no signs that the situation would improve soon. Hong 
Kong's economy shrank by 7 percent in the third quarter of 1998 and 
is believed to have contracted by 5 percent for all of last year. 
Nobody is predicting a quick recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``The economic situation in the coming months remains  
uncertain,'' Wong said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Unionists warn more people would be thrown out of work during  
the Chinese New Year, when many companies traditionally review 
their books and lay off unneeded staff after giving them their 
year-end bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
	``At present, it would probably be fair to say a lot more  
companies will be thinking of downsizing more than anything else,'' 
said Tang Kwong-yiu, the government economist. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong people greet each Chinese New Year with wishes of  
prosperity, but with the new year less than a week old, prosperity 
doesn't seem to be in the cards as the territory struggles through 
its deepest recession in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, the trend will continue,'' said Anthony Chan, chief  
regional economist at HSBC Securities. Chan added that unemployment 
may hit 6.5 percent by midyear -- ``emphasized by corporate 
downsizing at small and medium-sized enterprises.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others predict the jobless figures could hit 7 percent -- or  
240,000 people out of work -- by year-end. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect the situation to continue to deteriorate,'' said  
Shamus Mok, chief economist at Bank of East Asia Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor activists echoed the dismal forecasts. Despite government  
job-enhancing projects, the absence of social welfare insurance 
specifically for the unemployed will most likely cause a rise in 
poverty figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't need time, we need government commitment,'' said  
Mabel Au of Oxfam Hong Kong, which leads a coalition of 16 
non-government organizations studying poverty and unemployment in 
the territory. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wong warned there were limits to what the government can do.  
</P>
<P>
	``One must not forget that whenever businesses are not doing  
well, whatever we do to ease the situation will not bring down the 
rate of unemployment,'' Wong said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Slips Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar slipped against the yen in late  
profit-taking Monday after rising earlier on speculation that Group 
of Seven finance officials had approved a lower rate for the 
Japanese currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar edged higher against the euro. In late New York  
trading, the euro was quoted at $1.1028, down from $1.1076 late 
Friday. Also in late trading, the dollar was quoted at 120.91 
Japanese yen, down from 121.15 Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar climbed to an 11-week high against the yen during  
early trading. Investors later sold yen after the G-7 meeting of 
industrial nations failed to say anything about exchange rates 
following a weekend meeting. Investors interpreted that as 
officials' approving of the falling yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was aided by Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's  
influential vice finance minister for international affairs, who 
was quoted in a Tuesday newspaper saying he favored a weak yen, a 
continuation of his position last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``An excessive rise in the yen should be avoided. Although we  
will not refer to a target level, we must send a message (to the 
market) at some point,'' he was quoted as saying in an interview 
published in Tuesday's Nihon Keizai Shimbun newspaper. Sending a 
message would mean intervening in foreign exchange markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market was a little sensitive to that'' and took the yen  
lower against the dollar, said Jeremy Fand, a foreign exchange 
strategist at BankBoston's Boston office. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar did end the day lower against the yen as  
profit-taking set in. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar initially fell against the euro in Asian trading  
following weekend comments by Hans Tietmeyer, president of 
Germany's central bank, who intimated that a weak euro was 
worrisome for Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was surprisingly supportive of the euro,'' Fand said. But  
the dollar later got a boost from rising U.S. stocks and bonds. 
``That's always good news,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4495 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4468, and 1.4962 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4852. The British 
pound rose to $1.6258 from $1.6226. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7734 German 
marks, up from 1.7658; 5.9488 French francs, up from 5.9207; and 
1,754.39 Italian lire, up from 1,748.25. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
