<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial To Resume in Cable Car Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine aviator who operated  
electronic equipment from his jet's rear seat and had no control 
over the plane's operation may command the fate of pilot Capt. 
Richard Ashby. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. William Raney was expected to testify this week in the  
court-martial of Ashby, the Marine pilot whose jet sliced a ski 
gondola cable in Italy last year, killing 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby is charged with 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter, one  
count of each destroying private and government property and one 
count of dereliction of duty. 
</P>
<P>
	Raney and Capt. Chandler Seagraves both rode in the back seats  
of the EA-6B Prowler and operated the jet's radar detection and 
jamming gear. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Seagraves told the eight-man jury that he didn't hear  
the plane's radar altimeter sound any warnings as it flew lower 
toward the cable, and that he didn't think Ashby was flying 
dangerously. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors claim Ashby was flying too low and too fast when the  
jet hit the cable. His lawyers have said the Mount Cermis ski lift 
wasn't on Ashby's government-issue map, his radar altimeter 
malfunctioned, and he suffered from an optical illusion that made 
him think he was flying higher than he really was. 
</P>
<P>
	The jet was stationed at a NATO base at Aviano, Italy, at the  
time of the accident last Feb. 3. Although the mishap occurred 
during a low-level training flight, Prowlers typically operated 
thousands of feet higher during missions over Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, six members of Ashby's squadron testified that he was  
a top pilot and usually calm and friendly. After the accident, said 
the unit's doctor, there was a concern that Ashby might consider 
suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	The aviators testified a week earlier than scheduled because  
their Prowler squadron was sent Saturday to Europe to fly missions 
over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Michael Recce, a pilot, said he watched Ashby's crew  
discuss a 1,000-foot altitude restriction for the low-level 
training flight the day of the mishap. 
</P>
<P>
	Recce said none of the squadron members knew of the 2,000-foot  
restriction imposed the previous October. The Prowler hit the 
gondola cable at 360 feet to 370 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted on all counts, Ashby faces more than 200 years in  
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby's navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury,  
N.Y., will face the same charges as Ashby at a court-martial next 
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
