<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Starts Own Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- Trans-Atlantic mergers require lots of  
trans-Atlantic travel. Just ask DaimlerChrysler, which started its 
own flights between Stuttgart and Detroit on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating under the name DaimlerChrysler Aviation, the  
automaker's Airbus A320 with 52 seats will fly four times a week 
between its two main bases of operations, with a refueling stop in 
Iceland, the company announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting in November, the A320 will be replaced with an Airbus  
A319, which will make the trip nonstop. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler said it started the flights because the need for  
its employees to fly back and forth across the Atlantic has risen 
dramatically since last year's merger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
