<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sempra To Buy KN Energy for $1.8B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Sempra Energy announced Monday the $1.8 billion  
purchase of Colorado-based KN Energy, extending its natural gas 
pipeline reach 25,000 miles throughout the Midwest and giving it 
the largest customer base in the utility industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock and cash transaction will increase Sempra's payroll to  
15,000 employees and its revenues by $4.4 billion annually. The 
combined company will serve 21 million customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra would also assume more than $4 billion in KN Energy debt  
as part of the deal, pushing its total value to about $6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a breakout strategy to new regions of the country, from  
the Gulf Coast to Chicago, across the Plains to the Rockies and 
California,'' said Stephen Baum, vice chairman and chief operating 
officer at San Diego-based Sempra. ``We have a premier position in 
the gas delivery market and it transforms us from a regional 
utility to a national player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	KN Energy is the nation's second-largest natural gas pipeline  
and storage company, and operates the largest pipeline in Chicago 
and Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	KN Energy will not close its main office in Locoweed, Colo., but  
the companies expect to eliminate duplicate operations and jobs, 
resulting in a loss of about 300 jobs through layoffs and attrition 
and a savings of $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra isn't alone in its plans to be a big player nation's  
energy industry. Virginia-based Dominion Resources Inc. announced 
Monday it was buying Consolidated Natural Gas for about $6 billion 
in stock. The merger will form a company serving 4 million 
customers in the Midwest, mid-Atlantic and Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Before deregulation, a lot of companies had no competition, or  
minimal competition,'' said Barry Liden, director of government 
relations for Texas-based Bustin &AMP; Co. ``In this new, competitive 
environment, companies are trying to find efficiencies for 
themselves and benefits for their shareholders. That happens by 
diversifying their interests and offerings, and that likely means 
more mergers to capture a bigger share of the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the proposed agreement, Sempra will acquire KN  
Energy for a fixed ratio of 1.115 shares of Sempra common stock, or 
$25 in cash, for each KN Energy share. That represents a premium of 
about 24 percent above the average closing price of KN Energy 
shares over the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	KN Energy shareholders will have the option of cash or stock,  
such that 70 percent of KN Energy shares are converted to Sempra, 
while 30 percent are sold for cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of KN Energy rose 12 1/2 cents to $21.62 1/2 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. Shares of Sempra fell 75 cents to $21.56 1/4, 
also on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	Completion of the acquisition requires the approval of  
shareholders from both companies, the Federal Energy Regulatory 
Commission and the state utility commissions of Colorado and 
Wyoming. The companies anticipate closing the deal in six to eight 
months. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
