Nasdaq Composite:             2285.89  +  2.29
Gold(final) -    $289.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Levi Strauss To Slash 5,900 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Levi Strauss will close 11 of its 22 plants in  
North America and lay off about 5,900 employees, or 30 percent of 
its work force in the United States and Canada, as the jeans maker 
struggles with slumping sales. The San Francisco-based company said 
it will shift production to plants overseas, which will enable it 
to spend more time and money on product design and marketing, two 
areas where it has been lagging in recent years. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! Seeks Damages in India  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- California-based Yahoo! will seek  
unspecified damages from Indian ``cybersquatters'' in a patent 
case, counsel for the U.S. company said Monday. An Indian court 
granted an injunction Friday to the Santa Clara, California-based 
Yahoo!, which has brought a civil suit against ``Yahooindia,'' 
whose World Wide Web site resembles the familiar Yahoo! home page 
and offers India-related services and information. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler Starts Own Flights  
</P>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- Trans-Atlantic mergers require lots of  
trans-Atlantic travel. Just ask DaimlerChrysler, which started its 
own flights between Stuttgart and Detroit on Monday. Operating 
under the name DaimlerChrysler Aviation, the automaker's Airbus 
A320 with 52 seats will fly four times a week between its two main 
bases of operations, with a refueling stop in Iceland, the company 
announced. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Won't Revive Hijack Lawsuits  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to revive  
lawsuits stemming from the 1986 terrorist hijacking of Pan Am 
Flight 73 in Karachi, Pakistan. The justices, without comment, 
turned away arguments that allegations against Pan American World 
Airways and a security firm should be restudied in light of their 
decision last year on transfers of complex lawsuits from one 
federal trial court to another. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Nixes Japan Computer Appeal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today let stand findings  
that Japan's largest computer maker tried to sell four 
supercomputers to a U.S. research consortium at illegally low 
prices in 1996. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal in 
which NEC Corp. said it was denied a fair and impartial hearing 
before the Commerce Department found it in violation of antidumping 
laws by offering the supercomputers at prices far below their fair 
market value. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Lets Iowa Farm Case Stand  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling it  
was told casts doubt on all 50 states' efforts to protect farmers 
from being sued by their neighbors under public-nuisance laws. The 
justices, without comment, refused to review a decision by Iowa's 
highest court that struck down the state's ``right to farm'' law, 
similar to laws enacted in every other state. 

</P>
<P>
	Farmers Protest EU Agriculture Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Ten of thousands of farmers from across  
the European Union demonstrated in Brussels today, and some fought 
pitched battles with police, over plans to reform the EU's bloated 
agricultural subsidy programs. The protesters marched despite hail, 
snow, sleet and high winds during one of the worst days of a bad 
winter. 

</P>
<P>
	Sempra Energy Is Buying KN Energy  
</P>
<P>
	LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- Sempra Energy is buying the natural gas  
pipeline operator KN Energy Inc. for about $1.8 billion in cash and 
stock in a deal that would extend the rapid expansion of the 
California-based energy concern. The combined company under the 
deal announced Sunday would retain the name Sempra Energy and 
continue to be based in San Diego. It would have revenue of about 
$9.9 billion annually and more than 15,000 employees. 

</P>
<P>
	HSBC Buys Korean Bank Stake  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In another sign of progress in South  
Korea's financial cleanup, British banking giant HSBC is paying 
$700 million for a 70 percent stake in Seoulbank, a troubled lender 
that was nationalized last year. Under the deal announced Monday by 
HSBC Holdings PLC and South Korea's Financial Supervisory 
Commission, the South Korean government would keep 30 percent of 
the bank. South Korea will also take over the remainder of 
Seoulbank's bad debt. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Signs 1999 Budget  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin today signed into law  
Russia's austere 1999 budget, a document designed to help the 
country out of its worst economic crisis since the 1991 Soviet 
collapse. The budget was approved by both houses of parliament 
earlier this month with minimal opposition. Reflecting Russia's 
economic plight, the budget authorizes government spending of just 
$25 billion and revenues of only $21 billion -- tiny sums given 
Russia's huge size. 

</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong Unemployment Holds Steady  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Unemployment held steady at a record 5.8  
percent in the three months ending in January, the government said 
Monday in a report that offered up a gloomy outlook for the Chinese 
New Year. The Census and Statistics Department said 202,000 people 
were out of work in the November-January period, compared with 
201,200 in October-December. 

</P>
