<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine Lists Top 100 Racehorses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Man o' War, winner of 20 of his 21 career  
starts in 1919 and 1920, is the choice as Racehorse of the Century 
in a vote released Monday by the thoroughbred magazine The 
Blood-Horse. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blood-Horse polled seven racing officials and journalists to  
compile its list of the top 100 racehorses of the 20th century, 
which will be featured in the magazine's Feb. 27 issue and a book 
to be released this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Second to Man o' War in the poll is 1973 Triple Crown winner  
Secretariat, followed by Citation, Kelso, Count Fleet, Dr. Fager, 
Native Dancer, Forego, Seattle Slew and Spectacular Bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Evan Hammonds, managing editor of the The Blood-Horse, said Man  
o' War took first place on three ballots, while Secretariat earned 
three first-place votes and Citation one. 
</P>
<P>
	Man o' War took the top spot because he was listed second or  
third on each of the four ballots which did not pick him No. 1, 
Hammonds said. The experts varied more in their opinion of 
Secretariat, with one voter keeping him out of the top 10 entirely. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people feel that because he didn't win all his races,  
because he got beat a few times,'' Secretariat was not as worthy, 
Hammonds said. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel consisted of Howard Battle, racing secretary at  
Keeneland; Lenny Hale, vice president of the Maryland Jockey Club; 
Daily Racing Form columnist Jay Hovdey; Sports Illustrated senior 
writer William Nack; California senior steward Pete Pedersen; 
racing writer Jennie Rees of The (Louisville) Courier-Journal; and 
Gulfstream Park steward Tommy Trotter. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 192 horses received at least one vote in the  
balloting. 
</P>
<P>
	The only horse currently racing to make the Blood-Horse's list  
is 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Silver Charm at No. 63. 
Skip Away, the recently retired 1998 Horse of the Year, is No. 32. 
</P>
<P>
	Cigar, the all-time leading North American money winner with  
just short of $10 million in earnings, is No. 18. 
</P>
<P>
	All 11 Triple Crown winners made the list, from Sir Barton in  
1919 (No. 49) to Affirmed in 1978 (No. 12). 
</P>
<P>
	The only horse on the list never to race in the United States is  
Phar Lap of New Zealand (No. 22), who made his only North American 
start in Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
