<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Reach Steel Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia, facing the prospect of punitive  
tariffs on its steel shipments to the United States, agreed Monday 
to slash those shipments by 70 percent in return for continued 
access to the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal with the United States, Russia will limit  
shipments of hot-rolled steel to levels that existed in 1996 and 
restrict shipments of 16 other types of steel to 1997 levels. That 
was before the global financial crisis triggered a surge in cheap 
imported steel into the American market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, struggling to deal with the  
political problems caused by a record-high trade deficit, said the 
deal would save American jobs and help the struggling Russian 
economy at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	``These agreements deliver on the administration's commitment to  
respond vigorously to the surge in imports that has threatened the 
livelihoods of communities and workers around the nation,'' said 
Commerce Secretary William Daley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley acknowledged the administration was trying to strike a  
delicate balance between helping the U.S. industry and not shutting 
the door to all Russian steel at a time when the Russian economy is 
in a deep recession. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a legitimate concern about taking Russia to its  
knees,'' Daley said, noting steel production accounts for 7 percent 
of Russia's total economic output. 
</P>
<P>
	But the U.S. steel industry, its union and many of its  
supporters in Congress were quick to attack the agreement, saying 
it offered too little relief when a flood of imported steel is 
forcing production cutbacks, bankruptcies and thousands of layoffs 
at domestic steel plants. 
</P>
<P>
	``This agreement still allows too much steel to be imported at  
too low of a price,'' said Sen. Jay Rockefeller, R-W.Va. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel industry is pushing a bill in Congress that would  
impose worldwide quotas on the amount of steel that could be 
shipped into the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure has attracted 167 co-sponsors, but the Clinton  
administration is opposed, arguing the approach would encourage 
protectionist retaliation and increase trade barriers around the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia requested a negotiated settlement after the U.S. industry  
filed complaints charging Russia, Japan and Brazil with ``dumping'' 
steel in the United States at unfairly low prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department on Feb. 12 ruled against Japan and  
Brazil, announcing a preliminary determination for penalty duties 
as high as 80 percent on hot-rolled steel. That level of tariff 
would effectively block those two countries from the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil, the largest economy in Latin America, is now in a  
recession of its own because of the global financial turmoil. It 
asked the United States last week to begin negotiations on a 
``suspension agreement'' similar to the one Russia received Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	But outside experts said such a deal would be harder to grant to  
Brazil because of the way U.S. law is written. The administration 
had more leeway to negotiate an agreement with Russia because it's 
classified as a non-market economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The government reported last week that America's trade deficit  
surged by more than 50 percent last year to an all-time high of 
$168.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The global economic crisis has cut demand for U.S. exports while  
triggering cheaper imports into the country because of slumping 
demand in the rest of the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement with Russia, the annual quota for hot-rolled  
steel from that country was set at 750,000 metric tons with a floor 
put on the price this steel can be sold at, ranging from $255 to 
$280 per metric ton. Russia also agreed to an initial six-month 
moratorium on shipping any hot-rolled steel to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Russia agreed to separate quotas in 16 other steel  
product areas. Taken together, the quotas for hot-rolled and the 
other steel products will keep Russian shipments almost 70 percent 
below the levels reached in 1998 for the five years of the 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Commerce said it would not impose penalty tariffs on  
hot-rolled steel. Those could have ranged up to 218 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
