<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gardner May Start for Giants Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- Last season, spring training was a time  
of concern and doubt for Mark Gardner. His wife had just undergone 
a liver transplant, and he felt uneasy about being so far away as 
she healed. 
</P>
<P>
	A year later, Lori Gardner is doing fine and her husband is the  
most likely candidate to be the San Francisco Giants' opening day 
starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the season opener were tomorrow, it would be Gardy  
probably,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``Over the course of 
his career, he's earned it. He's the veteran of the staff. Why not 
Mark?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner was signed as a free agent by the Giants days before the  
start of the 1996 season, when the Florida Marlins decided to send 
Gardner to the minors but gave him a chance to work out a deal with 
another club. 
</P>
<P>
	He went 12-7 for San Francisco that season, earning the opening  
day spot the following year. Gardner was 8-2 through mid-June and 
the Giants won the NL West in 1997, but the end of the season was 
torture for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Lori was ailing, and was shortly thereafter to be diagnosed with  
liver cancer. Mark was winless in his last six starts and did not 
pitch again after Sept. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	Lori, a former softball player who met Mark at Fresno State, had  
a successful transplant in the middle of last February. Mark showed 
up late for spring training, and wondered whether he was doing the 
right thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough at the beginning. The thing that was bothering me  
last year was thinking, `Should I be here or should I be there?''' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lori insisted that Mark rejoin the team as soon as possible, and  
he opened the season as the No. 4 starter in the Giants' rotation. 
By the end of the season, Gardner was the team's best pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner went 5-1 with a 2.97 ERA in August and September as the  
Giants forced a one-game playoff with the Chicago Cubs for the 
wild-card spot. He started that game, and was the loser in a 5-3 
defeat at Wrigley Field. 
</P>
<P>
	He went 13-6 in 1998, becoming one of only a dozen major  
leaguers that have won at least 12 games and had an ERA of lower 
than 4.50 in each of the last three seasons. He set career highs 
for wins, innings (212) and strikeouts (151). 
</P>
<P>
	And he earned the right to probably get another opening day  
start. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's just more of an honor for what you've done the  
year before,'' Gardner said. ``I might be the guy that might give 
you a little solidification. I'm not an ace, I'm just going to be 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner signed a two-year contract with the Giants before this  
season, and came to training camp with a lot fewer distractions 
than last year. 
</P>
<P>
	This spring, Lori and their two sons are with Mark in  
Scottsdale. Baker, referring to the street that runs past 
Scottsdale Stadium, said much of the credit for Gardner's strength 
should go to his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was like a miracle on Osborn Road,'' Baker said. ``It was  
probably more amazing what she did, which affected what he did. 
What if she had wanted him to stay home? He's a strong dude. Both 
of them are strong.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
