<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinic Receives Anthrax Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A Planned Parenthood clinic received a  
letter in the mail this morning with a powdery substance and a 
threat that it contained anthrax, an FBI spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no known injuries, but 24 people inside were  
quarantined and washed with bleach and soap as a precaution and 
three would likely be checked out at a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not believe at this time that anyone is in any danger,''  
said FBI spokeswoman Bridgett Patton. However, hazardous material 
crews were at the scene as a precaution and the substance would be 
tested, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar letters were sent to clinics throughout the country last  
week. At least 14 letters claiming to contain anthrax were mailed 
to abortion clinics and Planned Parenthood centers across the 
nation and were postmarked in Lexington, Ky. Initial tests show 
that the threats were hoaxes. 
</P>
<P>
	There was also a rash of phony anthrax threats at clinics in  
several states last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately known whether the letter received in the  
Kansas City clinic also came from Lexington. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthrax mostly affects farm animals, but its germs, when inhaled  
by humans, can lead to death if not treated early with antibiotics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
