<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies Comfortable With New Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Golf clubs are allowed on the baggage  
carousel and Armani suits are not required on road trips. Welcome 
to the new rules under Colorado Rockies manager Jim Leyland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I normally don't have too many rules,'' Leyland said. ``The  
more you've got, the more you break.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In six years under manager Don Baylor, coats and ties were  
mandatory on Colorado's charter plane. Golfing was allowed on the 
road but golf clubs were not. Spring workouts started by 
mid-morning and finished well after lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, the Rockies are able to schedule afternoon tee times  
at posh resort courses because they are typically finished by noon 
following 2 1/2-hour workouts efficiently coordinated by third-base 
coach Rich Donnelly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody just feels comfortable,'' said infielder  
Kurt Abbott, who played for Leyland when the Florida Marlins won 
the World Series in 1997. ``Everybody knows what they have to do. 
It's about baseball, about doing things right. It's not about 
having to dress up or looking good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While some players trade their three-piece suits for polo shirts  
from the Greg Norman collection, don't expect the Rockies to show 
up at a New York hotel looking like a leftover from a Pearl Jam 
concert. 
</P>
<P>
	In giving his players some leeway, Leyland is trusting they will  
police themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be neat,'' he said. ``I basically let the players  
make the rule. You can wear a nice pair of jeans, but if guys start 
wearing jeans with holes in them, we can wear a suit and tie. We 
can wear tuxedos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under Baylor, the Rockies were allowed to have mustaches and a  
well-kept goatee. That policy will not change. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want my team to act like professionals and I want them to be  
disciplined, but I don't believe telling a grown man he can't have 
a mustache is a form of discipline,'' Leyland said. 
</P>
<P>
	The longer leash can be attributed to Leyland's resume, which  
includes 13 years as a major league manager, a World Series ring 
and three straight NL East pennants with the Pittsburgh Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Rockies were born in 1993, everything was a learning  
experience, and the owners had more input into the team rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of like with a family,'' Rockies owner Jerry  
McMorris said. ``It's always easier to loosen the reins than 
tighten the reins. ... We're changing with the times and the new 
manager.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Leyland's standards stem from common sense. The shorter  
workouts prevent players from getting bored shagging fly balls, and 
the dress code keeps them comfortable on cross-country charter 
flights that sometimes land at 3 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who's going to see us?'' relief pitcher Chuck McElroy said.  
``You don't want to spill soda or anything on an $1,100 suit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules are sure to be a hit with Colorado's more  
flamboyant personalities such as outfielder Dante Bichette -- who 
showed up with his hair dyed black and Elvis sideburns last season 
-- and relief pitcher Curtis Leskanic. 
</P>
<P>
	``He might have to have a dress code with me,'' Leskanic said,  
``otherwise I'll show up looking like I'm playing in the New York 
Penal League. Seriously though, it's just a matter of not doing 
anything stupid.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 16:13:56 </DATE_TIME>
