<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Darlington Winners Teach Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DARLINGTON, S.C. (AP) -- Two of Darlington Raceway's all-time  
winners were on hand to teach some of the younger NASCAR drivers 
how to get around the sport's oldest superspeedway. 
</P>
<P>
	David Pearson and Bobby Allison, both NASCAR Hall of Fame  
drivers with 15 Darlington victories between them, were at the 
track tutoring drivers Buckshot Jones, Dan Pardus and Busch Series 
rookie Jimmy Kitchens. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is Jimmy's first time here, and at this place you've got  
to take any help you can get,'' said Allison, who won five times at 
the 1.366-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Allison is a consultant to Kitchens' team and watched the rookie  
scrape the outside wall a couple of times on his first laps. 
</P>
<P>
	Allison said Kitchens and the others have to learn not to think  
you can come out and defeat Darlington. ``If you have that 
attitude, it will beat you,'' Allison said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pearson holds the track's Winston Cup mark with 10 victories and  
is one of the first called on by young drivers who want to learn to 
succeed at Darlington. 
</P>
<P>
	Pearson helped Jones, now a Winston Cup rookie, a few years ago  
when Jones first started the Busch Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``But Winston Cup is a different ballgame,'' Pearson said.  
``Darlington is different from any track they will ever drive on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also at the track Monday were Pearson's son, Larry, who won a  
Busch race here in 1995, Wayne Grubb, Bobby Hamilton and his son, 
Bobby Hamilton Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones led testing with a top lap of 163.647 mph, followed by  
Pardus at 163.484 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Drivers will continue testing this week in preparation for the  
TranSouth 400 on March 21. The Busch Series Diamond Hill Plywood 
200 is set for March 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying for both races is March 19.  
</P>
</TEXT>
