<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans At 23-Year Low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Soybean futures tumbled to 23-year lows on the Chicago Board of  
Trade Monday after the Agriculture Department's chief economist 
predicted crop prices could fall to $4 a bushel later this year. 
Grain futures also retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans fell after the USDA's Keith Collins told a farm outlook  
conference he sees no end to the decline in commodity prices during 
1999, largely because economic troubles in Asia have caused U.S. 
exports to fall sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for soybeans have fallen to new lows each day for more  
than a week amid indications world production will continue to 
increase even as there are few takers for the commodity. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. farmers last year harvested a record large crop, and  
analysts predict they will plant record acreage this year because 
of farm programs that pay more for soybeans than other crops. 
Further exacerbating the problem are expectations for a near-record 
Brazilian crop and a large crop from Argentina, which are likely to 
keep competition strong throughout the year. 
</P>
<P>
	South American soybeans account for a third of the world's  
supply, and Brazil, the biggest producer in the continent, is the 
world's second-largest grower behind the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins predicted farm income would drop this year by $3 billion  
to $4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans for March delivery fell 4 1/4 cents to $4.74 a bushel.  
Prices earlier in the session fell to $4.64 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver futures fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange  
after the cost of borrowing the metal -- an indicator of demand -- 
fell for the first time in several days. The decline prompted 
speculation that consuming countries are not in as dire need of the 
metal as originally thought. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver futures rose sharply last week after borrowing, or lease,  
rates soared. That led to speculation that demand for the metal for 
such uses as photography, electronics and jewelry-making could be 
on the rise for the first time in months. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants also noted exchange warehouse inventories  
have been tight for more than a year, leaving those short of the 
metal in a precarious position should a large consuming country 
like India suddenly experience a jump in demand. 
</P>
<P>
	March silver fell 14 cents to $5.46 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Cotton futures soared in the nearby contract month on the Board  
of Trade of the City of New York as textile mills scrambled to find 
high-quality supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Bad weather during the last growing season helped produce one of  
the smallest crops in recent history and seriously affected the 
quality of that which could be harvested. Still, the outlook for 
cotton has been poor because of weak world demand. 
</P>
<P>
	The USDA in its farm outlook said exports will remain at their  
second-lowest in 20 years, while cheaper Asian imports are starting 
to flood U.S. shores. 
</P>
<P>
	March cotton rose 2.59 cents to 62.68 a pound, while the May  
contract fell 0.04 cent to 57.39 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
