<HEADLINE> Alleged Arsonist Arrested in Mass. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) -- A man was arrested on arson charges in  
connection with a fire that destroyed more than a dozen businesses 
including offices of the local newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Detective Sgt. John Rodley said George Aldrich of Waltham was  
arrested Sunday. Rodley would not elaborate on Aldrich's alleged 
role in setting the fire, except to say tips from other people led 
to his arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saturday morning fire gutted the three-story brick building  
that housed The News Tribune, a 7,500-circulation newspaper that 
publishes afternoons Monday through Friday, as well as a military 
recruiting office, an instrument repair shop, and several other 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltham Fire Chief Thomas Keough said the three-alarm blaze  
started in the basement. No one was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The News Tribune continued normal publication, with a front page  
headline today reading, ``Out of the Ashes.'' Its editors and 
reporters were relocated to Needham at the central offices of 
parent company Community Newspaper Co., the Fidelity-owned 
newspaper group that publishes papers in dozens of Massachusetts 
communities. The paper is printed in Framingham. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of actually putting out the paper, we're not going to  
miss a beat,'' editor Jon Paul Potts said. But, he said, 
``psychologically, it's a big blow to the paper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You cover four or five fires a day when you're in this line of  
work and you never think you're going to be on the other side,'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
