<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Prices Rise in Quiet Trading / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose in quiet trading Monday ahead  
of congressional testimony by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 15/32  
point, or $4.69 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, fell to 5.35 percent from 5.38 percent late 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was restrained before Greenspan's regular testimony on  
the economy, which was set to begin Tuesday before the Senate 
Banking Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	But with no signs of inflation reviving, despite a remarkably  
resilient economy, there were expectations that Greenspan would not 
roil financial markets by signaling any move to cool off the 
economy by raising interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were up between 3/32 point and 1/8 point, and intermediate maturities 
were up 1/4 point to 1/2 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, rose 2.55 
points to 1,296.98 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.62 percent as the  
discount rose 0.07 percentage point to 4.51 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.61 percent, as the discount fell 0.02 percentage 
point to 4.45 percent. One-year yields were 4.71 percent as the 
discount rose by 0.01 percentage point from late Friday to 4.50 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.81 percent from 4.63 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose to 125 7/32 from 125 1/8. The average 
yield to maturity fell to 5.14 percent from 5.15 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
