<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Barring Aliens' Suits Stands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today left intact a ruling  
that bars aliens from suing over the discrimination they 
encountered in their U.S. jobs if they lacked the authority, under 
federal immigration law, to work in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by a Nigerian  
citizen whose undocumented immigration status squelched his 1995 
job-bias lawsuit even though his employer had not known he was 
unauthorized to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Obiora Egbuna, who is now a permanent resident alien, began  
working for Time-Life Libraries Inc. in Alexandria, Va., in 1989. 
At the time, he possessed a valid student work visa but it expired 
six months after he got the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Egbuna continued working for Time-Life Libraries until early  
1993, when he voluntarily resigned because he intended to return to 
Nigeria. When his plans changed, he sought to regain his old job 
but was refused. At the time, Egbuna still was not authorized to 
work in the United States. He obtained such authority later that 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Egbuna sued his former employer, contending that its refusal to  
rehire him was in retaliation for his previously having 
corroborated an employee's sexual-harassment allegations against a 
supervisor. His lawsuit accused Time-Life Libraries of violating an 
anti-bias law known as Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. 
</P>
<P>
	While the lawsuit was pending, Time-Life Libraries learned that  
Egbuna had not been authorized to work in this country when it had 
denied him re-employment. It sought to have his lawsuit thrown out 
for that reason, and a federal trial judge dismissed the case. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals  
reinstated the lawsuit, but the full 4th Circuit court killed it 
again by an 8-4 vote last August. 
</P>
<P>
	No one is entitled to Title VII protection unless he or she  
``was qualified for employment,'' the appeals court ruled in 
interpreting a 1986 federal law, the Immigration Reform and Control 
Act. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Egbuna said the  
appeals court's ruling conflicts with a 1995 Supreme Court decision 
that said employers can be held liable for discriminating against 
someone even if they later found a lawful reason to justify the 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	A later-discovered lawful reason can be used only in determining  
the proper remedy for the unlawfully motivated treatment, the 
unanimous 1995 decision said. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Egbuna vs. Time-Life Libraries Inc., 98-934.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
