<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olivetti Bid Portends Shakeup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Olivetti's audacious bid to take over a former  
state-owned monopoly five times its size portends an era of 
unprecedented upheaval for Europe's telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Established companies in Britain and Germany face a growing  
threat from smaller, more aggressive upstarts, while in the 
Netherlands, a long-dominant telecommunications firm is seen as 
increasingly vulnerable to an unfriendly takeover. 
</P>
<P>
	For consumers, the competitive trend likely means cheaper and  
better phone service. 
</P>
<P>
	``We favor competition. We agree very much with this opening of  
the market,'' said Anna Ciaberoni, head of the Italian consumer 
group Federconsumatori. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciaberoni expressed some concern over the size of the bid but  
said she was generally optimistic that if Olivetti succeeds, 
consumers will benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	The catalyst for these changes, last year's deregulation of the  
European telecommunications business, also has created pressure for 
mergers and acquisitions -- much like the recent wave of 
consolidation that is redefining the continent's car industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti's $58 billion bid to take over Telecom Italia, the  
world's sixth-largest phone company, ran into some obstacles Monday 
after Italy's stock market regulator, Consob, said Olivetti's 
weekend filing failed to meet the standards for a full-fledged 
takeover announcement. That's important because Italian law limits 
the defense a company can mount once it becomes the target of a 
takeover bid ruled valid by Consob. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling doesn't stop Olivetti from trying a takeover, but it  
does give Telecom Italia more room to try and fend it off. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom Italia said Sunday that Olivetti's bid is ``full of  
holes'' and was marshaling a defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti also must overcome potential resistance from the  
Italian treasury, which retains 3.4 percent of Telecom's shares and 
veto power over major decisions through 2000. Despite that veto 
power, Italy's Premier Massimo D'Alema said Monday his government 
needs to remain neutral. 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless of the outcome, Olivetti, a telecommunications  
newcomer that made its name building typewriters and computers, 
poses the biggest challenge seen so far in an industry still 
dominated by companies that long enjoyed monopoly rights. 
</P>
<P>
	In Britain, where deregulation of the industry began in 1981, at  
least two new firms have already carved out a niche serving 
businesses with fiber-optic phone lines. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the firms, COLT Telecom Group PLC, has expanded beyond  
British shores to build or plan networks in Germany, France, Italy 
and Spain. Since going public in 1996, COLT has grown into 
Britain's 48th-biggest company in terms of market capitalization. 
</P>
<P>
	British Telecommunications PLC has hardly been sitting still.  
The largest British phone company tried to buy the No. 2 U.S. 
long-distance carrier, MCI Communications Corp., in 1997. But 
British Telecom was outbid by WorldCom Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``Liberalization came earlier to the United Kingdom, and it's  
now coming to the rest of Europe,'' said John Curran, a 
London-based senior vice president at Donaldson, Lufkin and 
Jenrette, one of three U.S. investment banks backing the Olivetti 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The result, analysts say, is that younger, more entrepreneurial  
firms are starting to embarrass their larger domestic competitors, 
many of whom are still operated by national governments. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with Telecom Italia, analysts cite the former German  
telephone monopoly, Deutsche Telekom, as one of the region's 
underperformers. 
</P>
<P>
	Its main competitor, Mannesmann AG, is seeking to build a  
presence in Italy and has agreed to buy Olivetti's holdings in 
mobile operator Omnitel Pronto Italia and fixed-line operator 
Infostrada. Olivetti plans to use money from the sales toward its 
takeover of Telecom Italia. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom is vulnerable because of its weak management, said some  
analysts, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	But other European companies are potential takeover candidates  
due primarily to their small size. 
</P>
<P>
	The Scandinavian telecommunications market is seen by some as  
ripe for consolidation. Chicago-based Ameritech Corp., which 
already owns a stake in the Danish company TeleDenmark, is said to 
be weighing acquisitions elsewhere in northern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the biggest Dutch telecommunications company,  
Royal KPN NV, confirmed Monday that his chief executive, Wim Dik, 
doubts whether KPN can remain independent beyond the next several 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the long run, you could see three or four European carriers  
instead of a national carrier for each country,'' said James 
Sawtell, an analyst at Deutsche Bank's London office. 
</P>
<P>
	But not every competitor can aspire to pan-European or global  
status. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing the example of Swisscom, the newly privatized  
telecommunications arm of Switzerland's postal service, Sawtell 
said: ``There's a lot of virtue in being just a well-run domestic 
carrier.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
