<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Sees Farm Strain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- American farmers face another year of  
lagging exports and low prices, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman 
predicts. ``There is no point in trying to put a shiny gloss on 
it,'' he told a forum on the farm outlook. 
</P>
<P>
	Agency figures released Monday lowered U.S. farm export  
projections by $1.5 billion to $49 billion -- lower than last year's 
$53.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The news was a blow to U.S. farmers still struggling from last  
year's low prices for commodities and livestock. Farmers have 
become increasingly reliant on exports since government subsidies 
began phasing out as part of the 1996 farm law. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress late last year passed a $6 billion bailout and the  
government last month gave $50 million to hog farmers who are 
getting their lowest prices in four decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no point in trying to put a shiny gloss on it, no  
point in playing games of spin and denial. The facts are the 
facts,'' Glickman said at the department's annual forum. ``I wish I 
could say we are about to turn the corner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	USDA chief economist Keith Collins was even more blunt: ``All  
signs now point to higher farm financial stress in 1999.'' He 
predicted farm income would drop $3 billion to $4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. agricultural exports have been declining since 1996,  
when they reached a record $60 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian economic crisis is the main culprit, with exports to  
that region accounting for over 80 percent of the decrease. Large 
supplies by U.S. farmers have worsened the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	One commodity particularly vulnerable to the global slowdown is  
cotton, Collins said, noting that the projected $1.4 billion in 
cotton exports is the second lowest in 20 years. Cotton exports 
totaled $2.5 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Asian textiles and apparel are flooding the world market,''  
Collins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Just Monday, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. said it would close 11 of its 22  
plants in North America and lay off about 5,900 employees to deal 
with slumping sales. Last week, Cone Mills -- the world's largest 
producer of denim fabrics -- said it would cut 11.5 percent of its 
work force. 
</P>
<P>
	When buy clothes today, ``about 45 percent of the cotton in  
those textiles is imported,'' Collins said. 
</P>
<P>
	But cotton isn't alone. The greatest financial strain in 1999  
will be on field crops, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices, expected to average only $2.70 a bushel in 1998-99  
-- the lowest season-average price in 8 years -- probably won't rise 
more than 10 percent, Collins said. Corn, forecast at $1.95 per 
bushel this marketing year -- its lowest level in more than a decade 
-- should remain unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	As for soybeans, Collins said, ``Producers are being drawn to  
soybeans like filings to a magnet because for the moment it appears 
to be the least worst alternative.'' That bodes ill for its price. 
Soybeans, expected to average $5.20 per bushel this season -- their 
lowest since 1986-87 -- could average well below $5 a bushel, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and poultry production is expected to remain high but  
prices will make a small recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	For 1999, fed cattle prices are expected to average $65.50 a  
hundredweight, compared with $61.50 last year. Hog prices are 
expected to begin to recover in the second half of the year with 
prices of around $34 per hundredweight, 7 percent higher than last 
year but still far below the $45 range before the price slide. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins said it probably will take three to five years for U.S.  
exports to recover to the 1996 level. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the largest drops in exports is to Japan, where the  
continued recession has dropped the export estimate to $8 billion, 
15 percent below 1998. Overall, exports to Asia are forecast at 
$16.8 billion, compared with $19.6 billion in 1998. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
