<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 05:32:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MLB Spring Training Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	When last seen, David Wells was crying after the Yankees traded  
him out of New York. Now, the rival Mets seem eager to stop his 
tears. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets, on the lookout to add an ace, already have spoken to  
the Toronto Blue Jays about a trade for Wells. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did talk to the Blue Jays the day of the trade and  
(assistant general manager) Omar Minaya spoke with them the second 
day,'' Mets GM Steve Phillips said Sunday in Port St. Lucie, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``But right now he's part of their staff, and they're not  
trading him,'' Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays got Wells on Thursday as part of a three-player  
package for Roger Clemens. Wells does not seem thrilled at the 
prospect of pitching for his old team, and the Mets -- along with 
the Cleveland Indians -- are interested in acquiring the lefty. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing we'd be interested in is if there were a  
top-line starting pitcher available,'' Phillips said. ``Most trades 
probably won't happen until the end of spring, after the 
evaluations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells was expected to join the Blue Jays today at their camp in  
Dunedin, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're getting a good one in Wells,'' said Toronto catcher  
Darrin Fletcher. ``If you're going to get a starter, you might as 
well get one who is his caliber of player. We've been needing a 
left-handed starter, it has been the team's No. 1 priority. It cost 
us Roger Clemens, but we got him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also expected at camp today for his first workout was Oakland  
lefty Kenny Rogers. The Athletics' ace was the only one absent on 
the first day of practice for pitchers and catchers, though he 
showed up later at the team complex. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's somewhere in between harmless and a statement,''  
A's general manager Billy Beane said in Phoenix. ``I know this, 
Kenny doesn't like to leave his family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers demanded a trade in November, then rescinded it 18 days  
later. But he's made it clear he'd like to be nearer to his family 
in Tampa, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a couple of familiar faces showed up at spring  
training. Ken Griffey Jr. came by Seattle's camp in Peoria, Ariz., 
and talk-show host Jerry Springer took some swings with the 
Cincinnati Reds in Sarasota, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey was asked about the Mariners' running regimen this  
spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hit 56 home runs and played center field behind a team with  
a 5.00 ERA,'' he said. ``I got a lot of running in last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer, the former mayor of Cincinnati, wandered over from his  
home near the Reds' complex. He spoke with general manager Jim 
Bowden and manager Jack McKeon, and took nearly two dozen swings 
against coach Buddy Bell, never hitting a ball to the outfield 
grass on a fly. 
</P>
<P>
	``They laughed at me when I signed Deion (Sanders),'' Bowden  
said. ``What's the difference?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wally Joyner, meanwhile, liked what he was seeing in camp --  
especially after undergoing corrective eye surgery in the 
offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Diego Padres' first baseman had vision of 20/3,000  
before the procedure. The surgery improved his sight to 20/20 in 
his right eye and 20/25 in his left. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm seeing the ball well, I'm hitting, my fielding's fine,''  
Joyner said. ``I was thinking, I've got a couple more years to 
play. I've played with these bad eyes all my career. If there's a 
possibility of getting better eyesight, let's see if it helps.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
