<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans At 23-Year Low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Soybean futures tumbled to 23-year lows on the Chicago Board of  
Trade Monday after the Agriculture Department's chief economist 
predicted crop prices could fall to $4 a bushel later this year. 
Grain futures also retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans fell after the USDA's Keith Collins told a farm outlook  
conference he sees no end to the decline in commodity prices during 
1999, largely because economic troubles in Asia have caused U.S. 
exports to fall sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for soybeans have fallen to new lows each day for more  
than a week amid indications world production will continue to 
increase even as there are few takers for the commodity. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. farmers last year harvested a record large crop, and  
analysts predict they will plant record acreage this year because 
of farm programs that pay more for soybeans than other crops. 
Further exacerbating the problem are expectations for a near-record 
Brazilian crop and a large crop from Argentina, which are likely to 
keep competition strong throughout the year. 
</P>
<P>
	South American soybeans account for a third of the world's  
supply, and Brazil, the biggest producer in the continent, is the 
world's second-largest grower behind the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins predicted farm income would drop this year by $3 billion  
to $4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans for March delivery fell 4 1/4 cents to $4.74 a bushel.  
Prices earlier in the session fell to $4.64 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver futures fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange  
after the cost of borrowing the metal -- an indicator of demand -- 
fell for the first time in several days. The decline prompted 
speculation that consuming countries are not in as dire need of the 
metal as originally thought. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver futures rose sharply last week after borrowing, or lease,  
rates soared. That led to speculation that demand for the metal for 
such uses as photography, electronics and jewelry-making could be 
on the rise for the first time in months. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants also noted exchange warehouse inventories  
have been tight for more than a year, leaving those short of the 
metal in a precarious position should a large consuming country 
like India suddenly experience a jump in demand. 
</P>
<P>
	March silver fell 14 cents to $5.46 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Cotton futures soared in the nearby contract month on the Board  
of Trade of the City of New York as textile mills scrambled to find 
high-quality supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Bad weather during the last growing season helped produce one of  
the smallest crops in recent history and seriously affected the 
quality of that which could be harvested. Still, the outlook for 
cotton has been poor because of weak world demand. 
</P>
<P>
	The USDA in its farm outlook said exports will remain at their  
second-lowest in 20 years, while cheaper Asian imports are starting 
to flood U.S. shores. 
</P>
<P>
	March cotton rose 2.59 cents to 62.68 a pound, while the May  
contract fell 0.04 cent to 57.39 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Saberhagen Predicts Healthy Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- A year ago, Bret Saberhagen went to  
spring training with a repaired shoulder and an uncertain future. 
Now he's back with a 15-win season and a contract that could keep 
him with the Boston Red Sox for four more years. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not surprising for someone who was so good that he won  
the first of his two Cy Young awards when he was just 21. It's 
shocking for someone who had major surgery at 32 and missed most of 
the next two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank God that I got a second chance,'' Saberhagen says.  
``It's kind of like a dream come true again. I appreciate the game 
a lot more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had surgery on his right shoulder on May 28, 1996, while with  
Colorado, missed that entire season and didn't pitch in the majors 
again until Aug. 22, 1997, when he made his first start since Oct. 
1, 1995. He was 0-1 with a 6.58 ERA in six starts for Boston in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	When spring training began the following season, the Red Sox  
were very careful about bringing Saberhagen along slowly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had hopes to be in the rotation for my first start of the  
year,'' he said, ``but it took a lot of work to get there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saberhagen made it, beating Seattle and Randy Johnson 10-5 in  
the fifth game of the season. He allowed two runs on four hits in 
five innings. He went on to win five of his first six starts but 
was taken out after six innings in each of the other four wins to 
make sure his arm wasn't being overworked. 
</P>
<P>
	``At times it was frustrating, but it was just a matter of,  
after the game, sitting down and saying, `hey, we're not in this 
thing for one game,' '' Saberhagen said. 
</P>
<P>
	No, he's in it for a reborn career.  
</P>
<P>
	Saberhagen ended up with a 15-8 record and 3.96 ERA in 31 starts  
and never missed his turn in the rotation. He pitched 175 innings, 
felt strong at the end of the season and wants to work at least 200 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's miles past where he was at this point last year,''  
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``He's stronger. His arm has a 
little more resiliency. We figure we can get another 10 or 12 
pitches out of him a game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Pedro Martinez, Tim Wakefield and Saberhagen forming a  
solid starting corps, the Red Sox added veterans Mark Portugal and 
Pat Rapp to a rotation that's much more settled than last year's. 
Portugal was 10-5 with Philadelphia, which finished eight games 
under .500, and Rapp was 12-13 with Kansas City, which was 17 under 
.500. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they were on our team, they'd have won a lot more last  
year,'' Saberhagen said. ``So we're going to be in a lot more 
ballgames'' this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Saberhagen should be better prepared for the start of the  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been throwing down here for about a week now and been  
able to throw off the mound and come back and throw long toss the 
next day and feel very good,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, manager Jimy Williams wants to make sure he doesn't get  
carried away by Saberhagen's success and use him too much. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't get too glad happy about how well he did,'' Williams  
said. ``When you think about what the man has been through, you 
don't want to try to push the envelope too hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox apparently are convinced that Saberhagen's arm has  
recovered fully. They signed him last season to a contract for 
three years and an option for a fourth, when he'll be 38 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	That, he figures, will be enough.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to win 200 games. I have 156 right now so I should be  
able to do that if I stay healthy,'' Saberhagen said. And he'd love 
to cap a career that was in jeopardy a couple of years ago with the 
Red Sox first championship since 1918. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning in Boston would be something else,'' he said. ``I  
don't think you can compare it to anything because the city has 
waited so long for a championship. I'd love to be part of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's a possibility again now that his shoulder is healthy.  
</P>
<P>
	``Pitching was always something that just pretty much came  
natural to me,'' Saberhagen said, ``but after it's taken away and 
you've got to work to get back there you realize how tough it is 
and how fortunate you are.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
