<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 11:16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Judge Won't Step Aside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A federal judge today turned down a  
request to step aside in a possible contempt case against President 
Clinton over his testimony about his relationship with Monica 
Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolly Kyle Browning, who claims a long-term affair with Clinton  
before he became president, had said U.S. District Judge Susan 
Webber Wright was not the best judge to decide whether Clinton 
should be held in contempt. 
</P>
<P>
	She was the only person to ask Wright to step aside.  
</P>
<P>
	Larry Klayman of the conservative group Judicial Watch, which is  
representing Ms. Browning, said Friday that Wright would likely be 
a witness in a contempt case and that she could eliminate one 
ground for possible appeal by the president if she didn't hear the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said today that Browning and Judicial Watch did not  
set forth sufficient grounds on why she should step aside and let 
another judge handle the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Browning was a witness in Paula Jones' sexual harassment  
lawsuit against the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Browning says she and Clinton were classmates at Hot Springs  
and that they had a sexual relationship from the mid-1970s until 
sometime before January 1992. Clinton denied the relationship 
during testimony in the same case. 
</P>
<P>
	His motion also asked that the contempt issue be transferred to  
a federal court outside Arkansas, preferably the Northern District 
of Texas where Ms. Browning resides. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright had offered to step aside because of her contact with a  
House impeachment case manager. Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., wanted 
her testimony about Clinton's demeanor during his deposition 
testimony. But neither Clinton's nor Mrs. Jones' side requested 
such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright, who oversaw Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit  
against Clinton, said she waited to address the contempt issue 
because of the president's impeachment trial and an appeal of Mrs. 
Jones' case. The Senate voted earlier this month not to convict 
Clinton; Mrs. Jones' appeal ended with a settlement of the suit in 
December for $850,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge had dismissed Mrs. Jones' lawsuit last April 1, saying  
Mrs. Jones had failed to prove key elements of harassment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
