<HEADLINE> WTO Sides With U.S. In Apple Hassle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- A World Trade Organization appeals panel ruled  
Monday that Japan is acting illegally by blocking imports of fruit 
on health grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel supported U.S. complaints that Japan's testing  
requirement for imports of apples, cherries, nectarines and walnuts 
is not backed by scientific evidence and is too restrictive. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. apple farmers hope the ruling will open the way for them to  
export fruit more easily to the large Japanese market. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan insists on repeated testing of quarantine treatments each  
time a country tries to export a new variety of a fruit. Japanese 
officials say it wants to protect its plants from the codling moth. 
</P>
<P>
	The testing takes at least two years and is also costly for the  
government and producers, according to the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	A WTO panel came out against Japan in November, but Japan  
appealed against the decision. The appeals panel upheld most of the 
original ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
