<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Checks Report on Lauder Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is investigating a  
report that a company chaired by cosmetics heir Ronald S. Lauder 
has signed a deal with a state-run Yugoslav communications company 
in violation of U.S. sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James Foley said Monday the  
administration became aware of the purported deal last August as a 
potential sanctions violation. In response to a Treasury Department 
request, Lauder's firm responded with a full report, Foley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foley and a Treasury Department official said Treasury is  
reviewing the firm's activities. 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged deal, first reported in Monday's New York Times, was  
said to involve RSL Communications, one of Lauder's companies, and 
Telekom Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauder, reached in Jerusalem, denied the report. ``We are not  
doing business there,'' he said. ``We submitted a proposal to the 
State Department and asked, `How about this?' That's where it 
stands.'' He said other telecommunications companies also are 
trying to do business with Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauder is a former ambassador to Austria and chairman-elect of  
the Conference of Presidents of Major Jewish Organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery Fischer, legal counsel for RSL, told the Times, ``Our  
belief is that we have not violated the sanctions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that before the deal was signed in August, the company  
briefed Treasury Department officials and got no objection. 
</P>
<P>
	Fischer also told the Times the company had gotten approval from  
someone at the State Department but could not recall the person's 
name. Foley denied that the department had given such approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Another department official said the agency normally has  
contacts with the Treasury Department on such matters but that 
Treasury has the final say. At this point, the official said, the 
administration does not have enough information to know whether the 
alleged transaction is subject to an exemption. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, Clinton signed an executive order barring U.S.  
investments in Serbia after Belgrade used police and military force 
to crack down on Kosovo Albanians. A number of other Western 
nations took similar steps. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbia is one of two republics that make up the former  
Yugoslavia. The other republic, Montenegro, was exempted from the 
U.S. sanctions. 


</P>
</TEXT>
