<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfer Faldo Seeks Match Play Crown  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARLSBAD, Calif. (AP) -- From the far corner of the range Monday,  
Nick Faldo laid a club in the grass to work on his alignment, then 
turned around and hit lob wedges to a practice green behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years removed from his last tournament victory, two days  
away from a high-stakes match against Tiger Woods, Faldo is looking 
for what he calls ``synchronicity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had better find it pretty quick.  
</P>
<P>
	The Match Play Championship begins Wednesday, a 64-man field of  
single elimination over 18 holes at La Costa Resort with an early 
flight home for anyone who gets off to a bad start, $1 million for 
the player who can win six matches over five days against the best 
in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good opportunity,'' Faldo said, hopeful that a victory  
over the world's top-ranked player can help rejuvenate a Hall of 
Fame career that has fallen into disarray since winning in Los 
Angeles two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship is the first of  
the new World Golf Championship events, each with a $5 million 
purse but none as compelling as this one. 
</P>
<P>
	Match play has not been a part of the PGA Tour since a two-year  
experiment in Tucson ended in 1985. It has not been used in a major 
event that brings together the best players in the world since the 
1958 PGA Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is too young to be a major,'' said Mark O'Meara, the  
Masters and British Open champion. ``But this is the first time to 
get the top 64 players in match play, and there's a tremendous 
buzz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The field was determined by the top 64 in the world ranking  
published a week ago, and the brackets were drawn up like an NCAA 
tournament. If everything goes according to plan, Woods, David 
Duval, O'Meara and Davis Love III will meet in the ``Final Four'' 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't count on it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's anybody in this field whom you can take  
for granted,'' O'Meara said. ``People need to know we're talking 
about the top 64 in the world. It isn't like the No. 3 player 
against No. 300. The top 70 or 80 players are world class who can 
beat anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, the 64th seed happens to be Faldo, who once held  
the No. 1 spot for 81 consecutive weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	That spot currently belongs to Woods, who is starting to play  
like he deserves it. Woods ended a nine-month drought by winning 
the Buick Invitational two weeks ago in San Diego. He was in 
position to win again last week in the Nissan Open, taking a brief 
lead in the final round Sunday before finishing two strokes behind 
Ernie Els. 
</P>
<P>
	Already possessing awesome skills that have sent him soaring to  
the top of golf in just over two years, Woods loves the format as 
much as any American and is partially responsible for the renewed 
interest in match play because of his record three straight U.S. 
Amateurs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like Tiger has been gearing up for this,'' Jesper  
Parnevik said. ``He's been talking about this for a month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No matter how far he has fallen, Faldo is also a master of match  
play, having won more Ryder Cup matches than anyone in its 70-year 
history. His 39 victories around the world include two World Match 
Play Championships in England. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he didn't arrive at La Costa equipped with the same level  
of confidence as Woods. While Woods was serving notice to Duval and 
everyone else that he can still win any time he sticks a tee in the 
ground, Faldo was home in Florida with his fingers crossed. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed his last two cuts on the European tour to slip to No.  
65 in the world ranking, and only got in the field when Jumbo 
Ozaki, who rarely plays outside Japan, decided not to enter. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Faldo finds out what he can do with the opportunity. The  
fact the first five matches will be contested over 18 holes could 
be an advantage. Sunday's finals will be 36 holes, considered a 
fairer test of match play. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a stamina factor in 36 holes, and a bit more  
strategy,'' Faldo said. ``Eighteen holes is more like a sprint. But 
it's still match play. You play your opponent, don't you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	A half-dozen reporters followed him from the range to the 10th  
tee, and Faldo was clearly annoyed, sensing the hype over his 
opening match with Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	``So, this must be my official tournament interview,'' he said.  
``You know it's a big ... tournament when they come onto the tee 
with you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reminded by a spectator that there were children in the  
vicinity, Faldo pointed to reporters and said, ``Yes, they're right 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he turned around, hit his first drive down the middle and  
walked down the fairway with caddie Fanny Sunesson and a friend. 
</P>
<P>
	It won't be like that Wednesday. Woods will be with him, as well  
as thousands of people swept up in the drama of match play. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
