<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Held in Death of Ailing Wife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEARL RIVER, N.Y. (AP) -- An 86-year-old retired plumber has been  
charged with shooting his ailing wife to death on her 88th 
birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter Papeman called 911 about 5:15 p.m. Sunday and told  
dispatchers that he had just shot his wife, Louise, in the chest 
with a rifle, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Papeman, a former volunteer firefighter and World War II  
veteran, calmly surrendered to police who showed up at the couple's 
home in Pearl River, a New York suburb. Papeman pleaded not guilty 
to second-degree murder and was being held without bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Papeman had been sick for a year and had started dialysis  
six months ago, friends and neighbors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Detective Sgt. Terry Hutmacher confirmed she was in poor health,  
but refused to give details or say whether Papeman could have shot 
his wife to end her suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	The Papemans, who had no children, celebrated their 50th wedding  
anniversary in June. They loved to socialize, and Mrs. Papeman was 
active in community service with the Salvation Army, Meals on 
Wheels and other groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were a wonderful couple,'' said Maureen Walker, a friend  
of the Papemans for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
