<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United Tech To Acquire Sundstrand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- United Technologies Corp. is snapping up smaller  
rival Sundstrand Corp. in a $4.3 billion cash-and-stock bid aimed 
at bolstering United Technologies' position in the rapidly 
consolidating aerospace and industrial parts industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hartford, Conn.-based maker of Pratt &AMP; Whitney jet engines  
announced Monday it plans to fold Rockford-based Sunstrand into its 
Hamilton Standard division. The deal requires shareholder and 
regulatory approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination, to be renamed Hamilton Sundstrand and based in  
Connecticut, would allow United Technologies to better compete 
against such companies as General Electric Co. and Rolls Royce PLC 
in making smaller engines for the fast-growing regional jet market 
and in providing aircraft control systems, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies such as Boeing and Airbus Industrie increasingly are  
subcontracting aircraft systems, and a United Technologies 
acquisition of Sundstrand would better position it to offer 
one-stop shopping for various components, said Jon Kutler, 
president of the investment bank Quarterdeck Investment Partners, 
which specializes in the aerospace and defense industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the action now is in the subcontractor base, where you're  
seeing the players try to assemble businesses that make the guts of 
what ties an aircraft together,'' Kutler said. ``Each is trying to 
be more and more important to the prime (contractor), so they're 
offering a combination of services and products that lets the prime 
deal with fewer players and maintain tight schedules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the agreement, each Sundstrand share would be  
exchanged for $35 in cash plus 0.2790 share of United Technologies 
stock, for a minimum of $70, based on Friday's closing share price. 
</P>
<P>
	While the companies gave little indication of what effect the  
deal might have on Sundstrand's 10,400 employees, analysts said 
widespread plant closings were unlikely. Sundstrand spokesman Pat 
Winn said company was reviewing the 100 positions at the company's 
corporate offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase, expected to close by June, would add slightly to  
per-share earnings this year, with additional earnings growth in 
later years, United Technologies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sundstrand chairman Robert H. Jenkins will become chairman of  
Hamilton Sundstrand. Its president will be Ray Kurlak, Hamilton 
Standard's president. In 1998, nearly 60 percent of Sundstrand's $2 
billion in revenue came from aerospace customers, both in the 
military and commercial businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	United Technologies also owns No. 1 elevator maker Otis and No.  
1 air-conditioner maker Carrier, although its biggest moneymaker 
has been the Pratt &AMP; Whitney division. United Technologies earned 
$1.26 billion on $25.72 billion in revenue in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The company in recent months has moved to cut costs and boost  
higher-margin businesses. It announced last week it had put its 
automotive unit up or sale as competition in the subcontractor 
market heats up. 
</P>
<P>
	Sundstrand shares rose $10.25, or 17 percent, to $68.25 on the  
New York Stock Exchange. United Technologies stock fell $1.06 1/4, or 
less than 1 percent, to $126 1/2. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
