<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Higher; Dow Up 89 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks pushed higher this morning along with  
bond prices, amid optimism that interest rates will fall or at 
least remain stable through Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan's Congressional testimony on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The market also got a boost from a spate of merger  
announcements. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 89.84 at 9,429.79, led by banking and technology issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher, with the Nasdaq composite  
up 13.07 at 2,296.67, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index up 1.12 
at 1,250.49. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 12-to-7 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 107.09 million 
shares, below even Friday's slow pace. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ahead of Mr. Greenspan's testimony, we've got thin markets and  
a much firmer tone to the bond market,'' said William Meehan, 
market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald. ``People think that his 
testimony will be rather neutral, that he will say, `We're keeping 
our eyes out for inflation, but the risks are balanced.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Meehan said the lower interest rates have also paved the way for  
investors to return to technology stocks, which they had sold last 
week in favor of manufacturing and consumer names, Meehan said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Dow ended a roller-coaster session up 41.32 at  
9,339.95, after trimming a 97-point gain to zero and then 
recovering, all in the final 15 minutes of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was led higher by IBM, up 2 13/16 at 174 7/16;  
Hewlett-Packard, up 3 5/8 at 71 15/16; American Express, up 2 13/16 at 
106; and Citigroup, up 1 1/16 at 55 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial issues moved higher as yields in the bond market fell.  
The 30-year Treasury bond was up 3/8 point, pushing its yield, which 
moves opposite the price, down to 5.36 percent from 5.38 percent 
late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Individual stocks involved in merger announcements, including  
two big energy-company deals, were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominion Resources agreed to buy gas and oil-pipeline company  
Consolidated Natural Gas for $6.3 billion. The union would create 
one of the country's largest electric and gas utilities. Dominion 
Resources' shares were down 1 11/16 at 40 5/8, while CNG's shares were 
down 1/4 at 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Sempra Energy agreed to acquire KN Energy, a big natural-gas  
pipeline and storage operator, for $1.9 billion. KNE's stock was up 
1 1/16 at 22 5/8, and Sempra's shares were down 1 1/6 at 22 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, aircraft engine maker and Dow component United  
Technologies said it would buy Sundstrand for about $4.3 billion in 
cash and stock, in a move that will expand United Technologies' 
aerospace and aviation businesses. United Technologies' shares were 
down 3 7/16 at 122, but Sundstrand's shares were up 9 3/16 at 67 
3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Telecom Italia, the leading telecommunications service  
provider in Italy, is the target of a hostile takeover bid by 
smaller rival Olivetti. Telecom Italia's shares were up 2 3/16 at 
108 5/8. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
