<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A Spanish woman who was kidnapped while  
trying to adopt a child in Colombia was released Monday, but her 
husband remained in captivity. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria del Pilar Rojo, 36, and her husband Santiago Cavanas, 46,  
were abducted Sunday while driving in the rural zone of Sonson 
about 75 miles northwest of the capital Bogota, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the region is rife with leftist rebels who often  
kidnap people to help finance their armed struggle, though the 
kidnappers could also be common criminals or paramilitary groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Cavanas's kidnapping brings to 15 the number of foreigners being  
held in Colombia, which has the world's highest kidnapping rate. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 260 Colombians are being held by kidnappers. Last  
year, 1,794 people were kidnapped in Colombia, according to the 
president's office. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru will complete the privatization its state  
companies this year, bringing in $8.5 billion directly and $7 
billion in investment commitments, a top privatization official 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	President Alberto Fujimori's government began the successful  
privatization program in 1992 and has sold off 179 state companies 
to date, Juan Barcellos, director of Peru's Commission to Promote 
Private Investment, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The crown jewel of the program was the sale of a controlling  
stake in state telephone monopoly Telefonica del Peru to Spain's 
Telefonica de Espana in 1994 for $2 billion, far more than 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the state properties Peru plans to sell this year are the  
Cerro de Pasco mine, its train system, part of its electricity 
distribution grid, phosphate fields, and concessions to operate 
ports, airports and roads. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- An Italian tourist who disappeared while  
swimming at a popular beach in the Pacific coast state of Oaxaca 
was found dead on Monday, the government news agency Notimex 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The body of Gaetano Pitruzzella, who disappeared on Saturday,  
was found by local fishermen, said the state's deputy attorney 
general, Esteban Maldonado. 
</P>
<P>
	Maldonado said Pitruzzella was dragged away by strong tides at  
Zipolite beach, which prevented his companions from attempting to 
rescue him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian Embassy in Mexico City had no additional information  
on Pitruzzella's age or place of origin. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 


</P>
</TEXT>
