<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angels' DiSarcina Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Anaheim shortstop Gary DiSarcina is expected  
to miss at least one month after breaking his left forearm at 
training camp in yet another freak accident for the Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	DiSarcina, a sound fielder who hit .287 last season, was injured  
Sunday. Following a round of batting practice, he blindly turned 
and walked into the swing of first-base coach George Hendrick, who 
was hitting ground balls to infielders. 
</P>
<P>
	DiSarcina said he's generally a fast healer, so he's confident  
he'll be back before the Angels' opener April 6. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be around all the time, running a lot, because I want to  
be with the guys,'' he said. ``This is not going to ruin our frame 
of mind entering the season. I'm determined to make sure of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Angels manager Terry Collins said he overheard players in the  
training room asking aloud, ``When is this going to stop?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the spring of 1997, the Angels lost Chuck Finley for a few  
weeks when reliever Mike James accidentally lost control of a bat 
that hit the starting pitcher in the face and broke an orbital 
bone. 
</P>
<P>
	Late in the season, Finley broke his wrist when he slipped while  
backing up home plate. The next game, catcher Todd Greene broke his 
wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it isn't going to stop. Maybe this is a team that will  
always face adversity and have to overcome it,'' Collins said. 
``But we will not let that injury change our attitude because 
DiSarcina will be ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first workout for position players is scheduled for Tuesday.  
Collins said Craig Shipley, Jeff Huson, Luis Rivera, Andy 
Stankiewicz and rookie third baseman Troy Glaus will each get a try 
at shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know Craig can play shortstop because he has for me  
before,'' Collins said. ``I thought at one time Jeff Huson was 
going to be an outstanding major league shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rivera was an outstanding major league shortstop a few years  
ago. And Andy Stankiewicz grinds it out as good as any extra player 
I've been around,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The intriguing possibility is Glaus, a first-round pick in 1997  
who played some shortstop during an All-American career at UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	``We moved him to third because of Gary DiSarcina,'' Collins  
said. ``Had Gary not been on the team, Troy Glaus would still be 
playing shortstop.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 15:57:02 </DATE_TIME>
