<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Case Judge Won't Step Aside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A federal judge Monday refused to step  
aside and let another judge decide whether to cite President 
Clinton for contempt over his testimony in the Paula Jones case. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright said a conservative  
legal group did not provide sufficient grounds for why she should 
remove herself. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright had offered to consider stepping aside because of her  
contact with a House impeachment case manager and because her law 
clerk provided House managers with an affidavit. 
</P>
<P>
	The only request that Wright step aside came from Judicial  
Watch, a legal group representing Dolly Kyle Browning, a witness in 
Mrs. Jones' case who said she had an affair with Clinton before he 
became president. 
</P>
<P>
	Judicial Watch said that Wright could be a witness against the  
president and that her stepping aside now would eliminate one 
ground for possible appeal later. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright is considering a contempt charge against Clinton over his  
remarks about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. The president 
said in a 1998 deposition that he did not have a sexual 
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. He later acknowledged an 
``inappropriate relationship'' with her. 
</P>
<P>
	Last April, Wright dismissed Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment  
lawsuit. The judge said she waited to address the contempt issue 
because of the president's impeachment trial and an appeal of Mrs. 
Jones' case. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Jones' case ended in an $850,000 settlement in December.  
</P>
<P>
	The punishment for contempt can range from a reprimand to a fine  
or jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
