<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Near Top on NHL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Ottawa Senators' days as NHL doormats are over. Now they're  
the ones doing the stomping. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now it is great -- we can win any game,'' said captain  
Alexei Yashin. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk about respectability, the once-lowly Senators suddenly have  
the second-best record in the Eastern Conference -- one point behind 
Philadelphia. Their 32-16-8 mark is just two victories shy of their 
franchise best set last season. 
</P>
<P>
	High times for an expansion team that broke into the NHL in  
1992-93 with a 10-70-4 record and had only a 51-224-23 mark after 
the first four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're a good, hard-checking team and they are on you  
quick,'' Flyers coach Roger Neilson said after Saturday night's 4-1 
loss to the Senators. ``Once they got the lead, they didn't give us 
many opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's generally been the case of late for any team facing the  
surging Senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Ottawa has lost only three of its last 25 games (17-3-5). Their  
18 wins at the Corel Centre are already a record for home games, 
and their 16 games over .500 is a club best. 
</P>
<P>
	``Five years ago, it was bad -- the worst team I have been on in  
professional sports,'' Yashin said. 
</P>
<P>
	For trivia fans, the original starting lineup of the Senators:  
Peter Sidorkiewicz in goal, Ken Hammond and Brad Shaw on defense, 
Neil Brady at center, Jody Hull on right wing and Sylvain Turgeon 
on left wing. 
</P>
<P>
	There was one consolation for a last-place team: a high draft  
pick after the season. The Senators slowly but steadily built 
through the draft -- getting Yashin in 1992 and Daniel Alfredsson in 
1994 -- and with trades such as the deal for Shawn McEachern in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	They began turning things around in the 1996-97 season,  
finishing 31-36-15 and earning their first playoff berth. Last 
season, they finished over .500 for the first time at 34-33-15 and 
raised some eyebrows by beating the Eastern Conference-leading New 
Jersey Devils in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Damian Rhodes was a hero in Ottawa then, considered the  
Senators' No. 1 goalie. This season, Ron Tugnutt has taken over the 
spotlight while sharing the goaltending load with Rhodes. 
</P>
<P>
	Tugnutt leads the NHL with a 1.57 goals-against average, and has  
been one of the backbones of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been playing very good defensively, and great  
goaltending is always a very important part of a hockey game and 
very important part of winning success,'' Yashin said. 
</P>
<P>
	He thinks both Tugnutt and Rhodes are playing very well.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's probably why our team's been winning,'' Yashin said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
