<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MOMA Presents Major Italian Films </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- American lives may have no second acts, but some  
Italian lives are getting another chance -- on an American movie 
screen. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Second Act: Second Season,'' the Museum of Modern Art  
presents a series of postwar Italian films, most never commercially 
released in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Highlights of the show, which runs until March 2, include works  
by directors Federico Fellini, Lina Wertmuller, Sergio Leone and 
Francesco Rosi. 
</P>
<P>
	``Italian filmmaking from the late 1940s onward has helped  
define the idea of contemporary cinema and introduce new narrative 
strategies and expressive styles,'' says Lawrence Kardish, MOMA's 
curator of film. 
</P>
<P>
	Alessandro Blasetti's ``Peccato Che Sia Una Canaglia'' (Too Bad  
She's Bad, 1955) is a comedy featuring the first onscreen teaming 
of Marcello Mastroianni and Sophia Loren, as a Roman cab driver and 
the wily thief who wins his heart. The film spins on a politically 
incorrect, whimsical relationship in 1950s Italy -- a film era of 
romance wrapped in realism. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-week series which opened Thursday demonstrates that  
``film must be neither political nor correct. It's art,'' said 
Antonio Monda, a New York University professor of cinema who 
co-curated the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Also featured is Fellini's directorial debut, ``Luci del Varieta  
(Variety Lights, 1950), a love story in a vaudeville company 
starring Fellini's wife, Giulietta Masina; and Wertmuller's first 
film, ``I Basilischi (The Lizards, 1963), a look at provincial life 
in southern Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Leone's ``Once Upon a Time in America,'' a 1984 film starring  
Robert DeNiro, didn't fare well with U.S. critics when first shown 
here. Some blamed the failure of the Prohibition-era epic on a 
shortened, edited version released for the American market. This 
time, the movie arrives in its original 218-minute, director's cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Another rarity, ``Milarepa,'' is director Liliana Cavani's 1973  
parable about a young man driven by a life crisis to search for a 
new existence through Buddhism. The film anticipates the 
alternative spirituality later addressed by directors such as 
Martin Scorsese and Bernardo Bertolucci. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talk so much about Tibetan chic these days,'' says Monda.  
``But this is so much purer, simpler.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A film that also touches on spirituality is the 1984 ``Il Futuro  
e Donna'' (The Future is Woman), directed by Marco Ferreri and 
starring Gerard Depardieu. The story of a married couple and a 
lonely woman who enters their lives ``is about the mystery of a 
pregnant woman, and the sacred act of giving birth,'' says Monda. 
``It's a tough, great film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the reference in the series title to F. Scott  
Fitzgerald's dictum -- ``There are no second acts in American 
lives'' -- Italian directors seem to create characters with endless 
options in the face of life's scrapes. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, MOMA presented its first ``Second Act'' of Italian  
films that have left an imprint, but have long been ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's dozen films embrace three general themes -- the quest  
for spirituality, the individual caught in a socio-political drama, 
and the ``eternal'' soul of Italy's south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
