<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USOC Waits, Worries About IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- If the top official of the  
Olympics is looking for a ringing endorsement for his leadership in 
dealing with the Salt Lake bribery scandal, he should look 
someplace other than the U.S. Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In what has become a trend of distancing the USOC from the  
fallout of the Olympics' worst corruption case, executive director 
Dick Schultz said the International Olympic Committee might be 
unable to deal with needed reforms -- and that president Juan 
Antonio Samaranch might not necessarily be the right person for the 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	``That depends who replaced him,'' Schultz said when asked if it  
would be in the best interest of the USOC for Samaranch to step 
down. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a weekend meeting of the USOC's executive committee,  
Schultz said his faith that the IOC could come to grips with the 
worst corruption case in its history at an emergency session March 
17-18 was ``a wait-and-see thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think they are going to fall apart,'' he said. ``But I  
don't think they will get all they are trying to get done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An ethics report on the bribery scandal surrounding Salt Lake  
City's successful quest for the 2002 Winter Games identified 24 IOC 
members -- a fifth of the membership -- who benefited from $1.2 
million in cash, travel, medical care and other improper 
inducements from Utah bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine members have resigned or been expelled and another 13  
remain under investigation by the IOC, which has called the special 
session in Lausanne, Switzerland, to endorse the expulsions and 
consider reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Those under investigation include one of the most powerful  
people in international sports: Kim Un-yong, an IOC executive board 
member from South Korea and president of the international 
confederation of Olympic sports bodies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be interesting to see if they will be able to  
expel the people that, according to the information they have, they 
ought to expel,'' Schultz said. ``It's going to be an interesting 
meeting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting also will be asked to give a vote of confidence to  
Samaranch, who has been the target of increasing calls to resign in 
the wake of the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of those calls have come from outside the Olympic  
community, although international sponsors of the IOC -- most of 
them American based -- have complained loudly that not enough is 
being done to clean up the mess and retain the luster of their $50 
million investments in the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Schultz, who has maintained close ties with Samaranch since  
taking over at the USOC in 1995, did not call for the 78-year-old 
Spaniard to step down. But he also failed to give Samaranch 
overwhelming support. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our hope is that Samaranch can continue until they get some of  
these new things in place,'' Schultz said. Samaranch's term expires 
in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC executive board last month recommended changes in the  
way Olympic host cities are picked, most notably taking the vote 
away from the rank-and-file and giving it to a 15-member 
commission. That proposal has been sharply criticized by members, 
who say they would be punished for the corruption of others and 
stripped of one of the few meaningful duties they have. 
</P>
<P>
	Schultz, speaking at the end of a weekend USOC executive  
committee meeting, said he understood IOC leaders were preparing a 
longer list of recommendations to be presented at the March session 
and afterward. He did not have details. 
</P>
<P>
	Anita DeFrantz, an IOC vice president and a USOC executive  
committee member, was traveling Sunday and unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The USOC leadership was briefed by former Senate Majority Leader  
George Mitchell, whose independent ethics commission report on the 
Salt Lake scandal is due for release March 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell told a news conference Saturday the report would focus  
on preventing other scandals as U.S. cities bid for the Olympics in 
2012 and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	``The emphasis will be on recommendations for rules, compliance  
and enforcement, which we hope, if adopted, will prevent the 
occurrences that led to the creation of the commission,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
