<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Securitas To Acquire Pinkerton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. (AP) -- Security services firm Pinkerton  
Inc. is being acquired by Securitas AB of Sweden for $384 million 
in a deal they say will create the world's largest full-service 
security firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinkerton was founded in 1850 by Allan Pinkerton and is one of  
the world's best-known security providers, with annual revenue 
exceeding $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinkerton has more than 250 offices and 48,000 employees  
throughout the U.S., Canada, Latin America, Europe, Asia and 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``This merger is a dramatic milestone for the security  
industry,'' said Thomas Berglund, Securitas president and chief. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have spent 10 years building a strong and comprehensive  
European platform and Europe still represents a huge potential for 
further growth and improved profitability. The acquisition gives us 
a strong second base for a duplication of the last 10 years of 
development in Europe,'' Berglund said. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint announcement by Westlake Village-based Pinkerton and  
Stockholm-based Securitas said Securitas will pay $29 a share in 
cash for all outstanding shares of Pinkerton. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual revenue for the new company is expected to hit $3.5  
billion annually. It will employ 114,000 employees in more than 30 
countries in Europe, North and South America, and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined firm would account for about 5 percent of revenue  
generated in the global security market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This combination of two powerful security leaders will provide  
global corporations with access to a truly global network of 
security services,'' said Denis R. Brown, Pinkerton's chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are finding that U.S. corporations, in particular, are  
seeking to consolidate their security with fewer providers in order 
to create more integrated, well-planned security environments for 
their assets worldwide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pinkerton will become a wholly owned subsidiary of Securitas  
under the deal, which has been approved by the boards of both 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal requires regulatory approval.  
</P>
<P>
	Securitas said Brown would remain chief and become chairman of  
Pinkerton. Brown will also be nominated to the Securitas board. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
