<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oregon Family Sues Tobacco Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Jesse Williams was a loyal smoker of  
Marlboro cigarettes for four decades until he died of lung cancer 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Now his wife and six adult children are seeking more than $110  
million in damages from Philip Morris Inc. in a lawsuit that goes 
to trial this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming in the wake of a San Francisco jury's stunning $51.5  
million award to a former smoker, a jury verdict could ``turn a 
fluke into a trend -- that is something the industry would terribly 
want to avoid,'' said John Banzhaf, a law professor at George 
Washington University. 
</P>
<P>
	Banzhaf, who runs a nonprofit legal advocacy group, Action on  
Smoking and Health, said the Williams case is shaping up as another 
key battle in a campaign to make tobacco companies legally 
responsible for the health effects of their products. 
</P>
<P>
	``What it would do is multiply by many times the number of  
people who would want to bring these suits and the number of 
lawyers who want to take them,'' Banzhaf said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Charles Tauman of Bennett, Hartman &AMP; Reynolds, one of  
three Portland firms representing the Williams family, declined to 
comment on the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury selection begins today and opening arguments before  
Multnomah County Circuit Judge Anna Brown were scheduled to begin 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, a retired Portland Public Schools employee, was  
diagnosed with small-cell carcinoma of the lungs in October 1996 
and died five months later at age 67. The family maintains that 
Philip Morris exploited Williams' inability to stop smoking and 
deceived the public about the health dangers and addictive nature 
of cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit makes claims similar to Patricia Henley, 52, of San  
Francisco, who on Feb. 10 won punitive damages against Philip 
Morris that were three times the amount she had asked for. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal analysts said the tobacco companies' agreement last year  
to pay a $206 billion settlement with 46 states for the cost of 
treating tobacco-related illnesses might have made the industry an 
easier target, if jurors view the settlement as an admission of 
guilt and an indicator of how much money the industry has to spare. 
</P>
<P>
	A Philip Morris lawyer said the Henley verdict is unlikely to  
stand on appeal; two similar verdicts in Florida and one in New 
Jersey against cigarette makers were all overturned by appeals 
courts. Regardless, the Henley suit would have no bearing on the 
Williams case if jurors base their decision on the evidence, the 
lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every case, by its definition, is different. Every case is  
unique,'' said Michael York of the Washington law firm of Wehner &AMP; 
York. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990222.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 02:15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up, Tokyo Share Prices Up / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Group of Seven nations' apparent approval of a  
weak yen sent the dollar to an 11-week high in Tokyo today. 
Japanese share prices finished higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.98 yen in late trading, up 1.92 yen from  
late Friday in Tokyo and also above its New York level of 121.15 
yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 158.63 points,  
or 1.13 percent, to close the day's trading at 14,256.67. On 
Friday, the average closed down 48.75 points, or 0.34 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar climbed above 122 yen for the  
first time in 11 weeks after a weekend meeting of G-7 finance 
ministers and central bankers in Germany concluded without 
reference to the weaker yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors saw this as tacit acceptance of the currency's  
depreciation, and quickly bought up dollars, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-dollar sentiment was then reinforced when Bank of Japan  
Governor Masaru Hayami remarked after the meeting that the yen's 
recent weakness had been a ``desirable development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Sentiment toward the dollar is really bullish. Overseas  
players who are short on dollars keep buying and buying,'' said 
Hajime Sato, assistant general manager of foreign exchange at Daiwa 
International Trust Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's continued strength also derived from new U.S. data,  
released Friday, showing that the American economy remains robust. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Labor Department reported Friday that inflation  
remained tame, with consumer prices rising a barely perceptible 0.1 
percent last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Friday, the Commerce Department said the U.S. trade  
deficit in December narrowed unexpectedly to $13.8 billion, a 10 
percent drop over November. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged today from a low of 120.52 yen to a high of  
122.55 yen. In other currencies, the euro was traded at 134.40 yen, 
up from 134.17 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Japanese shares closed higher as the yen's  
retreat against the dollar prompted investors to buy 
export-oriented electronics and auto issues, including Toyota, 
Honda and Cannon. 
</P>
<P>
	``International blue chips are rising as Hayami's comments  
indicated the dollar could continue to rise,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, 
general manager of the stock division at Tokyo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	A weaker yen makes Japanese products more competitive in  
overseas markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of NEC Corp. also surged in value as investors expressed  
their approval for a major restructuring project the company 
announced last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The falling yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese  
government bond -- an effect of moves by the Bank of Japan to curb 
rising interest rates -- drove up share prices as well, analysts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower yields are a boon to companies, since they reduce the cost  
of borrowing money. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond yield dropped to 1.735 percent from Tuesday's finish of  
1.750 percent, driving its price up to 100.52 yen from 100.40 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 409 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange today, up from 402.96 million 
shares Friday. Advances outnumbered declines 840 to 296, with 157 
issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 14.41 points, or 1.32 percent, to 1,108.91 
points. The TOPIX closed down 0.77 points, or 0.07 percent, on 
Friday. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
