<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Feb. 22, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Both Sides Rest in Dragging Case  
</P>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- Dr. Tommy Brown, a pathologist, was the  
last of 43 prosecution witnesses to take the stand at the trial of 
John William King, one of the three white men accused of killing 
James Byrd Jr. last June because he was black. Brown said Byrd was 
conscious when he was dragged along a road by a chain around his 
ankles until his head was torn off by a concrete drainage duct. 
Prosecutors need to prove Byrd was alive when he was dragged in 
order to prove kidnapping and murder, which together would expose 
the alleged white supremacist to the death penalty. The defense 
also rested today, after presenting just three witnesses. Closing 
arguments were scheduled to begin tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Albanians Deciding on Plan  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians met tonight to  
decide whether to accept a peace agreement for Kosovo by tomorrow's 
deadline. Negotiators for the ethnic Albanians were holding out for 
a referendum after three years that could pull them out of Serbia, 
while the Kosovo Liberation Army was bargaining for a future role 
in Kosovo. The plan calls for autonomy but not self-rule. Secretary 
of State Madeleine Albright has said that NATO would not carry out 
the threatened bombing strikes against Serbs if the agreement does 
not have full support from the Kosovar Albanians. Albright also met 
today with the Serbs, but without making any apparent headway in 
breaking down resistance to using NATO peacekeepers -- a key 
provision of the pact. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Warns Greece Over Kurd Aid  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey asserted today it has a ``right to  
self-defense'' if Greece provides support to separatist Kurds -- a 
thinly veiled threat of military force against its neighbor and 
rival. The warning came as a Turkish newspaper reported that 
imprisoned rebel warlord Abdullah Ocalan had told interrogators 
that Greece gave his fighters weapons and training, claims that 
Greece has rejected in the past. Ocalan is expected to stand trial 
for waging a nearly 15-year insurrection in Turkey's southeast that 
has claimed an estimated 37,000 lives. Formal charges are expected 
to be filed tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets With Governors  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and the nation's governors  
grappled with differences over education policy, tobacco money and 
Internet sales taxes today. Clinton told the governors, ``I want to 
work with you.'' But he complained that some critics were trying to 
frame the political debate ``in partisan or ideological terms.'' 
Michigan Gov. John Engler, a Republican, said the issue of Internet 
taxes was ``the most difficult issue to solve.'' The governors are 
pushing for a system to collect sales taxes on Internet commerce, 
but the computer industry largely opposes the idea. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 212.73 As Stocks Soar  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials climbed 212.73 points to  
9,552.68 one day before Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's 
semiannual testimony on the state of the economy. Today's point 
gain was the biggest in five weeks, leaving the Dow about 90 points 
shy of the record 9,643.32. On the NYSE, advancers led decliners 
1,953-1,061. The Nasdaq was up 58.41 at 2,342.01. 

</P>
<P>
	Treatment Cuts Cervical Cancer Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A series of studies on cervical cancer has found  
that adding chemotherapy to radiation can cut the risk of death in 
half. Radiation has been the standard treatment since the 1950s for 
cervical cancer that has spread nearby, and the five-year survival 
rate for these women is now about 50 percent. The new studies 
proved so convincing that the National Cancer Institute took the 
unusual step of mailing letters to thousands of doctors urging them 
to adopt the new approach immediately. 

</P>
<P>
	HMO Trade Group Urges Reviews  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As prospects for ``patients' rights''  
legislation brighten, the HMO trade group is urging its members to 
voluntarily let patients who are denied care appeal to outside 
experts. And fearful that Congress' legislation will give patients 
the right to sue HMOs, the American Association of Health Plans 
today endorsed a set of principles that could be used in an 
external review process. External appeals give patients the right 
to challenge decisions by appealing to doctors not associated with 
the insurance company. 

</P>
<P>
	Astros' Alou May Miss Season  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Houston Astros outfielder Moises Alou has torn  
the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee and likely will 
miss most, if not all, of the season. The All-Star hurt himself 
last week when he fell off a treadmill while training at his home 
in the Dominican Republic. Alou finished third in the NL MVP voting 
last season behind Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
</P>
