<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	High pressure over eastern Canada brought fair skies but  
bitterly cold temperatures to much of the East on Monday while 
areas of the Plains dealt with close to a foot of snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Single-digit temperatures were reported from Pennsylvania to  
Maine, with winds up to 40 mph making it feel even colder in some 
areas. Snow showers were seen across the Great Lakes and into parts 
of New England, where up to 3 inches of snow was reported in some 
regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther south and west, areas from the Carolinas south into  
northern Florida reported temperatures in the 30s and 40s. Fair and 
cold weather also were reported over the Ohio and Tennessee 
Valleys. 
</P>
<P>
	Low pressure over the Plains brought widespread snow to parts of  
the Dakotas and south into Kansas and Nebraska, which saw some of 
the heaviest snowfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten inches of snow was reported by mid-afternoon in Mason City,  
Neb., near the center of the state, while up to 6 inches were 
reported in other areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The northern and central Rockies saw light snow with winds up to  
50 mph reported in parts of Montana, Wyoming and Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	A new storm system pushed into the Northwest Coast early Monday,  
bringing rain to areas of Washington and Oregon, with snow over the 
Olympics and Cascades. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from an afternoon high  
of 71 in Brownsville, Texas, to a morning low of minus 25 in 
Clayton Lake, Maine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
