<HEADLINE> Marlins' Mike Lowell Has Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida Marlins rookie third baseman Mike  
Lowell underwent surgery for testicular cancer and awaited 
pathology reports that will help determine further treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The prognosis for recovery is excellent,'' general manager  
Dave Dombrowski said Monday. ``It is not a life-threatening 
situation. We will know much more in the next 24 hours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A small testicular mass was discovered Friday when Lowell  
underwent a routine physical examination. Lowell, 24, had a 
testicle removed Sunday in an outpatient operation at a Fort 
Lauderdale hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did run some tests that showed it had not spread, so that  
was tremendous news,'' Marlins owner John Henry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell, who grew up in Miami, is a top prospect acquired Feb. 1  
from the New York Yankees for three pitching prospects. He's 
expected to battle veteran Kevin Orie for Florida's starting job at 
third base. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year Lowell hit .304 at Triple-A Columbus with 26 home runs  
and 99 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Marlins pitchers and catchers opened spring training Monday.  
Lowell, due to receive the pathology reports Tuesday, is scheduled 
to begin workouts with other position players Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If everything is OK, he's not going to skip a beat,'' manager  
John Boles said. ``He'd miss three or four weeks. He's in such good 
shape and he's such a strong young guy that he'd bounce back from 
this without any problem. The key is the pathology report.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several prominent players have been stricken with cancer since  
1996, including Andres Galarraga, Brett Butler, Eric Davis and 
Darryl Strawberry. Galarraga, the Atlanta Braves' first baseman, 
was diagnosed just last week with a cancerous tumor in a bone in 
his back and will miss the 1999 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
