<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Levi Strauss To Slash 5,900 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Levi Strauss, the company that put baby boomers  
in jeans but has been shunned by today's teens, is closing 11 
plants and laying off 30 percent of its work force in the United 
States and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The cutbacks announced Monday are Levi's latest step to bridge a  
generation gap that has seen sales of its stodgy five-pocket jeans 
eroded by trendier offerings from the likes of Old Navy, the Gap, 
Tommy Hilfiger, MUDD and JNCO. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no buzz for Levi's anymore,'' said Irma Zandl, who  
runs the marketing consulting firm Zandl Group. ``They missed the 
beat over and over, and kids have just moved on to hipper brands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The only one I know who wears Levi's is my dad,'' agreed Susan  
Chang, 15, of New York's borough of Queens, who wore a pair of JNCO 
jeans as she strolled down a Manhattan street Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't have any styles I want,'' added her friend Sam Lee,  
15. 
</P>
<P>
	Levi's will shutter 11 of its 22 plants in North America and lay  
off about 5,900 employees in the United States and Canada. Last 
year, it closed 13 U.S plants and cut more than 7,000 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The reorganization follows a tough year for Levi's, which  
watched its sales fall 13 percent to $6 billion. Levi's is 
privately held and doesn't disclose profits. 
</P>
<P>
	As it moves more production overseas -- where costs are much  
lower, Levi's said it will now have more time and money to spend on 
product development and marketing, two areas where it has been 
lagging in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Levi's has been especially slow at spotting current fashions and  
producing products quickly. For instance, it failed to jump on the 
trends in recent years for super, wide-bottom slacks or cargo 
pants, which have large pockets on the thighs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is truly a fast-food consumer who we are dealing with out  
there,'' said John Ermatinger, president of the Americas division 
for Levi Strauss. ``We need to get better at getting intimate with 
our consumer and understanding what they want immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among initiatives to jump-start sales, Levi's will try to  
release new products every 60 days -- it used to take up to a year. 
It will work closely with retailers to develop merchandise 
exclusively for their stores, Ermatinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last fall, Levi's began a new advertising campaign called  
``What's True,'' featuring teens wearing its jeans in ways that fit 
their personal style. For instance, in one print ad, a young 
dreadlock-sporting youth wears dark, baggy Levi's while standing on 
a sidewalk with a sign that reads ``Conformity Breeds Mediocrity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company is also arranging to have its baggy jeans and sexy  
shirts worn in movies and is using youthful celebrities such as 
actress Claire Danes to promote its brand.. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, analysts said Levi's revival will depend on whether it  
can get the masses -- especially the teen population -- talking about 
its brand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Levi's is very anxious to get cool again,'' said Zandl, the  
marketing consultant. ``But what they need is a marketing blitz 
that everyone notices and is talking about, like the dog in the 
Taco Bell ads or the Gap's great swing ad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Levi's focuses about winning back customers, thousands of  
its employees will lose their jobs in the next year. Levi's will 
close 10 U.S. plants and one in Ontario, Canada. Four plants in 
Texas will close, two in Tennessee, one in Georgia, one in 
Arkansas, one in Virginia, and one in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	At a sewing plant in El Paso, Texas, which makes 501 red tab  
jeans, 700 employees were told that their jobs would be terminated 
in the next year. It's the sixth Levi's plant to close in El Paso 
in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been working here for about 20 years and you know, it's  
like a family. I feel bad,'' said machine operator Thomas Alvarado, 
55, of El Paso. 
</P>
<P>
	Levi's will be offering benefits packages to U.S. employees that  
include up to three weeks of severance pay for each year of 
service, extended medical coverage and up to $6,000 towards 
training, education and business start-up expenses. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
