<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ocalan Under Interrogation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Imprisoned rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan  
has provided interrogators with a detailed accounting of Greek aid 
to his rebel group, the Kurdistan Workers Party or PKK, a Turkish 
newspaper reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey's president, meanwhile, used forceful language to warn  
rival Greece against supporting the Kurdish insurgents. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Greece chooses to continue with its illegal actions, we  
retain our right to take the necessary precautions for our right to 
self-defense which arises from international law,'' the state-run 
Anatolia news agency quoted Suleyman Demirel as telling Philippines 
television while on a visit to Manila. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan, captured in Kenya a week ago and taken to a Turkish  
prison island, is expected to stand trial for waging a 15-year war 
of insurrection that has claimed around 37,000 lives. 
</P>
<P>
	The national daily newspaper Hurriyet said Ocalan had  
acknowledged that Greece provided his guerrilla army with weapons 
and training, as well as a Greek Cypriot passport he used in his 
travels. 
</P>
<P>
	``Greece has for years supported the PKK movement. They even  
gave us arms and rockets. Greek officers gave guerrilla training 
and explosives training to our militants'' at a camp in Lavrion, 
Greece, the newspaper quoted Ocalan as telling interrogators. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey has frequently alleged in the past that Greece provides  
backing to the PKK, which it -- like the United States -- considers a 
terrorist group. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate response to the allegations in Greece,  
where today was a public holiday. Lavrion is the site of a United 
Nations refugee center, housing mainly Kurdish refugees from 
Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to past Turkish allegations, the camp has been  
examined repeatedly by international observers, who were unable to 
substantiate charges it served as a military training center for 
the PKK. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said the interrogation sessions were being  
videotaped, but did not say how it had obtained the rebel leader's 
statements. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said Ocalan had also told investigators of Greek  
assistance during five months of wandering as he attempted to find 
a country that would give him asylum. Just prior to being seized by 
Turkish commandos, he had been sheltering at the Greek ambassador's 
residence in Nairobi. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey has been harshly critical of Greece's aid to Ocalan and  
the PKK, and is demanding some form of censure of Greece by the 
European Union -- of which Greece is a member but Turkey is not. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ocalan affair has caused a political storm in Greece, with  
top government officials losing their jobs in the fallout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope Greek politicians may come to realize that dialogue  
with Turkey would be a much safer way of addressing common problems 
than giving support to terrorism,'' Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit 
told reporters Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan has not yet been formally arrested. At the time of his  
capture, he was already on trial in absentia on terrorism charges. 
A new set of formal charges could come this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
