<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rough Weather Stalls Ship Cleanup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOS BAY, Ore. (AP) -- Rough weather forced Coast Guard crews to  
stop pumping oil from the grounded cargo ship New Carissa again, 
shifting efforts today to preparing to tow the broken bow section 
out to sea. 
</P>
<P>
	An 825-yard cable being flown in from the Netherlands was  
expected to arrive today, allowing a tug to take another try at 
pulling the bow from the beach when the weather allows, perhaps 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A team was flown by helicopter to the ship today to assess the  
extent of fractures that have been growing in the bow section over 
the course of 19 days grounded in the pounding surf. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy surf from a winter storm forced pumping from the ship to  
tanks on shore to stop Sunday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 100,000 gallons of liquid has been pumped into  
containers on shore. Because it is a mixture of oil and water, 
crews could not immediately determine how much of the estimated 
135,000 gallons of fuel oil remain on board. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are definitely going to try to get the ship off, even if  
there is some oil still on,'' said Mike Szerlog, the Oregon 
Department of Environmental Quality's on-scene representative. 
</P>
<P>
	Pumping began about 6 p.m. Saturday and was stopped at midnight  
because of high tide and heavy surf threatening the hose lines. It 
had resumed shortly after noon Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Navy explosives team set the ship afire in a spectacular blast  
on Feb. 11, and the burning ship broke in two by the next morning. 
The bow section of the 640-foot vessel still had one-third of the 
original 400,000 gallons of gooey black fuel oil aboard, despite 
the efforts to burn it off. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the ship drifted aground Feb. 4, at least 70,000 gallons  
have leaked into the ocean along one of the most environmentally 
sensitive beaches in the state. Biologists have found oil coating 
27 of the 97 snowy plovers that have been counted in Oregon. The 
bird is listed as threatened under the Endangered Species Act. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 70 dead birds have been found, 32 of them oiled.  
Another 50 birds were in rehabilitation Sunday, including 15 snowy 
plovers. 
</P>
<P>
	Weather will be a factor in the decision to begin towing, but  
rough seas actually may lend salvage crews a hand by rocking the 
ship free. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking for weather to pick up a little to help get the  
vessel off the sand,'' said Coast Guard Chief Gene Maestas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
