<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Jan Hawkins    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jan Hawkins, a Cambridge University Press editor  
who worked to bring computers into schools, died of breast cancer 
on Feb. 9. She was 47. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hawkins had been teaching on the education faculty at  
Harvard University and also served as director of the Center for 
Children and Technology, where she had worked since 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	At Cambridge University Press, she worked on the ``Learning by  
Doing'' series, and often helped museums and schools bring 
computers and other technology into their programs. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Michael Higgins    	
</P>
<P>
	RIVERSIDE, Ill. (AP) -- Glass artist and designer Michael  
Higgins, half of the husband-wife team who created the colorful and 
sought-after ``higgins'' glass, died Feb. 13 at age 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the household objects he and his wife Frances created  
from vividly colored fused glass over their 50-year joint career 
are in the collections of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the 
Smithsonian Institution, the Corning Glass Museum and London's 
Victoria and Albert Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1950s and '60s, the couple worked with major glass  
manufacturers and potteries to adapt their techniques for mass 
production, but in 1966 they moved to Riverside to return to 
independent studio work. 

</P>
<P>
                        *The Rev. Walter Lini    	
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- The Rev. Walter Lini, the father  
of independence for the Pacific island nation of Vanuatu, died on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death of the Anglican priest, who was born in 1942,  
was not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanuatu, formerly known as the New Hebrides, gained independence  
from joint British and French rule in 1980. It has about 170,000 
residents, and is 1,200 miles northeast of Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Lini served as the fledgling republic's prime minister from  
independence until he was ousted in 1991. He since had other 
Cabinet roles, including deputy prime minister for most of last 
year. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Wilmer Mizell    	
</P>
<P>
	Kerrville, Texas (AP) -- Former congressman and major league  
baseball pitcher Wilmer ``Vinegar Bend'' Mizell died Sunday while 
visiting his wife's family. He was 68 and had suffered a heart 
attack four months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Mizell, who lived in Midway, N.C., served from 1968 to 1974 as  
the representative from North Carolina's 5th District. 
</P>
<P>
	Mizell acquired his nickname from the place where he grew up,  
Vinegar Bend, Ala. From 1952-62, he pitched for the St. Louis 
Cardinals, Pittsburgh Pirates and New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1960, Mizell helped the Pirates win the World Series. He  
posted a 13-5 record with a 3.12 ERA that season with the Cardinals 
and Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	After retiring from baseball, Mizell was elected as a  
commissioner in Davidson County. After he lost his U.S. House seat 
in 1974, President Gerald Ford appointed the Republican as 
Assistant Secretary of Commerce for Economic Development. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1982, Ronald Reagan picked him to become an assistant  
secretary of agriculture for governmental affairs -- the agency's 
top lobbyist in Congress. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Ralph F. Reikowsky    	
</P>
<P>
	HENDERSONVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Ralph F. Reikowsky, a longtime  
editor with the Washington Post, died Friday. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death was not available.  
</P>
<P>
	Reikowsky was an editor for the Washington Post for 32 years  
until his retirement in 1982. After his retirement he moved to 
Hendersonville. 
</P>
<P>
	He served in the U.S. Army Air Corps during World War II.  
</P>
<P>
	Reikowsky is survived by a son, two daughters, two sisters and  
two brothers. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Paul Schmidt    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Paul Schmidt, who translated Arthur Rimbaud's  
poems and Anton Chekhov's plays and worked in avant-garde music and 
theater for much of his life, died Friday from complications from 
AIDS. He was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	An expert in Slavic languages, Schmidt spent many years  
translating the writings of Velemir Khlebnikov, an obscure Russian 
poet who died in 1922. Schmidt brought Khlebnikov's play 
``Zangezi'' to the stage in Los Angeles in 1986. It later ran at 
the Brooklyn Academy of Music. 
</P>
<P>
	For the academy's 1995 Next Wave Festival, he composed a  
libretto for the opera ``Alice,'' which was based on Lewis 
Carroll's ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland'' and ``Through the 
Looking Glass.'' Composer Tom Waits and director Robert Wilson 
collaborated on the project. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt's collection of Rimbaud translations, titled ``A Season  
in Hell'' after the poet's masterpiece by the same name, was 
published in 1997, with photographs by Robert Mapplethorpe. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Gene Siskel    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Film critic Gene Siskel, known for the thumbs-up  
and thumbs-down reviews he and Roger Ebert shared on their popular 
TV show, died Saturday. He was 53. 
</P>
<P>
	Siskel had surgery in May to remove a growth from his brain, but  
returned to the syndicated television show ``Siskel &AMP; Ebert'' soon 
afterward. He announced earlier this month he was taking time off 
from that show to spend time recuperating from the surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Siskel wrote movie reviews for the Chicago Tribune and also did  
reviews for ``CBS This Morning,'' WBBM-TV in Chicago and TV Guide. 
</P>
<P>
	Siskel and Ebert were likely the most recognizable movie critics  
in the nation. Their trademark ``thumbs-up'' and ``thumbs-down'' 
reviews became a benchmark for the movie industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Their show's continuing success was largely attributed to the  
chemistry between the tall, balding Siskel and the heavyset Ebert. 
They appeared to practice a one-upmanship that was in the tradition 
of the rivalry of their newspapers. Ebert is a critic for the 
Chicago Sun-Times. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Joseph E. Tawil    	
</P>
<P>
	NEWTON, Mass. (AP) -- Joseph E. Tawil, an Archbishop Emeritus of  
the Melkite Catholic Diocese in Newton, died Wednesday. He was 86 
and had Parkinson's Disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Tawil was appointed Patriarchal Vicar in Alexandria and was  
consecrated bishop in 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, Tawil was appointed Apostolic Exarch for the United  
States by Pope Paul VI. He succeeded Bishop Justin Najmy, the first 
Melkite bishop in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Melkites are part of the Eastern Rite, a group of Catholic  
churches organized under ethnic lines and traceable to the churches 
established during the earliest days of Christianity. Melkites 
accept the authority of the pope but have considerable autonomy in 
ritual. 
</P>
<P>
	During his tenure, Tawil founded eight new parishes and five  
missions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
