<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Employee Contradicts Exec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Directly contradicting Microsoft's most senior  
executives, including Chairman Bill Gates, an employee accused of 
conveying an illegal proposal to a software rival insisted Monday 
he didn't believe the rival, Netscape, posed a threat to Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Rosen, general manager for new technology at Microsoft  
Corp., testified before a judge who was clearly unimpressed with 
his answers and to muted laughter from the courtroom audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates once criticized Rosen in  
e-mail to another Microsoft executive as ``a little naive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Halfway through Rosen's testimony Monday, U.S. District Judge  
Thomas Penfield Jackson urged Justice Department lawyer David Boies 
to ``accelerate the process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moments later, when Boies complained in a private meeting among  
lawyers and the judge that Rosen's answers were causing delays, 
Jackson empathized: ``I know exactly what he is doing, Mr. Boies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen was an important witness because he led a Microsoft  
delegation in June 1995 to a disputed meeting with executives from 
Netscape Communications Corp., whose own Internet browser software 
at the time dominated the market. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the most sensational allegations of its antitrust  
case, the government accuses Microsoft of offering at the meeting 
to illegally divide the market for such software, threatening to 
``crush'' Netscape if it continued selling its browser on computers 
using newer versions of the Windows operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen earlier called the charges ``fiction, absurd and untrue''  
and said they were ``either fabrications or the products of a 
fundamental misunderstanding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Boies confronted Rosen with e-mail he wrote in June 1995  
describing his attempts to ``establish Microsoft ownership of the 
Internet (browser) platform for Win95,'' Rosen said that 
``ownership'' meant keeping a promise to Netscape. 
</P>
<P>
	``The word 'ownership' means delivering on something you  
promise?'' the judge asked incredulously. When Rosen said yes, the 
judge rolled his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	At other times during Rosen's testimony, the judge thumped his  
hands on his bench and shook his head. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen contended that he didn't believe Netscape posed a threat  
to Microsoft until late in 1995, despite the company's most senior 
executives telling him otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	Government attorneys showed Rosen sworn testimony from the  
company's senior vice president, Paul Maritz, calling Netscape at 
the time ``a significant potential serious competitor.'' And they 
showed Rosen e-mail that Gates sent in May 1995 to all employees 
announcing that ``a new competitor born on the Internet is 
Netscape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember thinking that Bill was probably wrong. ... I  
probably had a better perspective than Mr. Gates did about 
Netscape's intentions,'' Rosen testified, bringing gasps from the 
courtroom audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen said he had talked with James Barksdale, Netscape's chief  
executive officer, ``and I believed him when he said he was not 
trying to be a competitor with Microsoft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boies also confronted Rosen with e-mail he wrote in May 1995,  
weeks before the disputed Netscape meeting, proposing that 
Microsoft ``wrest leadership of the (browser) evolution from 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen initially denied sending the e-mail until the government  
showed that at least one person had received it. Then he explained 
that his use of the word ``wrest'' actually meant ``take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You mean, you wanted it, and Netscape wanted to give it to  
you?'' Boies asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' Rosen said to more laughter from the courtroom.  
</P>
<P>
	Rosen's testimony left Boies clearly exasperated by day's end.  
In the middle of a long answer, the government's lawyer interrupted 
Rosen to announce curtly, ``Your Honor, I have no more questions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The points on the witness' credibility had been made,'' Boies  
said later outside the courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, which called Rosen a ``low-level employee,'' said the  
sudden decision to stop questioning the witness meant that ``the 
bulk of Mr. Rosen's testimony about the meeting was unchallenged,'' 
spokesman Mark Murray said. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
