<DOCNO> APW19990222.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-22 19:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Wells: Yanks Are Still in My Heart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUNEDIN, Fla. (AP) -- On his first day with the Toronto Blue  
Jays, David Wells said part of him was still with the New York 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are the enemy now but they are in my heart and on my  
mind,'' Wells said Monday, four days after New York dealt him to 
Toronto for Roger Clemens. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, who has always been a Yankees fan, became a star in New  
York by pitching a perfect game against Minnesota last May. He even 
wore an original cap worn by Babe Ruth on the mound one day. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was fun while it lasted,'' the 35-year-old left-hander  
said. ``There were no heroes last year; we just played as a team. I 
love everyone of them as my brother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, who didn't want to talk about his feelings on the day of  
the trade, was angry at reporters who went to his residence in Palm 
Harbor, saying they were ``invading my privacy,'' and at one point 
made an obscene gesture at media members. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coming onto private property is something that's uncalled  
for,'' he said. ``It's something that in the situation that went on 
was very emotional for me. But to come over to my house and bother 
me like that, is very inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells began his major league career with the Blue Jays in 1987  
and spent six years in Toronto before being released. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm clear-minded and ready to get started and ready for the  
1999 season, to help this team win the pennant,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto general manager Gord Ash said he has no intention of  
trading Wells. Cleveland and the New York Mets have been mentioned 
as possible suitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not discuss any deals with David Wells,'' Ash said.  
``In the words of George Bush: Read my lips -- David Wells will not 
be traded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Following the stunning trade, Wells went to Miami for a few days  
of golf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went down there, played golf and saw some friends,'' he  
said. ``Being traded isn't fun, but I'm a grown man and I can 
adapt. It's tough to leave a team that won 125 games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto thinks the deal, in which it also acquired reliever  
Graeme Lloyd and second baseman Homer Bush, makes it a wild-card 
contender. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Toronto got the better part of the deal,'' Wells said.  
``The key to winning is pitching and this team has some good 
pitchers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He'll have to prepare himself for a return to SkyDome, a much  
different place to play than Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a different culture in Toronto and you have to adjust,''  
he said. ``The fans aren't like in New York but they're fans. Now 
I'll make those fans happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells said his carefree personality won't change.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just like to have fun; I just like to be me,'' he said.  
``It's what my Mom made me -- she made me a complete person. You 
live your life the way you want it, as long as you do your job 
between the lines.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
